<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RuralPoor-Candidates-1stAdd     03-04 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rural Poor-Candidates - 1st Add,0891</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: rural areas.</HEAD>
<HEAD>JESSE JACKSON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jackson, a native of South Carolina, said: ``The cornerstone of
anti-poverty policy is full employment at adequate wages. Punitive
work programs aren't the answer for families on welfare. People
need livable wages, access to education, training, and affordable
child care. We also need strong affirmative action and
comparable-worth policies to ensure equal opportunity to hold good
jobs at adequate wages. ...
   ``We must significantly increase the minimum wage, to at least
$4.65 an hour, and index it to average wages. ... We need a
uniform, national benefit to needy families, single-parent and
two-parent alike ... (and) a comprehensive, universal national
health care program.
   ``We need to change the incentives for corporations to close
plants on workers here and move them to repressed labor markets
abroad.''
   ``The key to reducing rural poverty is a rural development
program designed to return the profits of rural labor to the
countryside. A rural development program must begin with a
commitment to preserving the family farm.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PAUL SIMON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Poverty is a curse wherever it is prevalent, but rural poverty
is particularly devastating as it can drain entire communities of
their resources and productivity.''
   Simon proposes an $8 billion public works program, the
Guaranteed Job Opportunity Program, to ``provide a job opportunity
for those who want to work'' and earn 10 percent more than welfare
or unemployment compensation.
   ``We must bring farm prices back up, and expand our farm economy
with farm-related manufacturing. ... We need farm policies that
encourage greater diversification,'' including loans to give
farmers ``time to make the transition to a new crop.''
   Simon is co-sponsoring legislation to create a $2.5 billion
federal child care program, which he called ``a particular concern
in rural areas because of the distances between jobs ... and the
lack of well-developed public transportation.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Here are the Republicans' replies:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GEORGE BUSH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Opening markets abroad is my top agricultural priority ... We
should also concentrate on developing new markets for our farm
products at home. I strongly support the development of alcohol
fuels. ...
   ``Finally, we should emphasize development of our rural economy.
America has been hit hard in recent years. What rural America must
do is attract new businesses by offering a productive work force
and strong infrastructure. To help rural America rebuild itself, we
should have a partnership of the federal, state, and local
governments, and the private sector. ...''
   ``We should ensure that rural hospitals are treated fairly under
federal health programs'' and create ``rural, as well as urban,
enterprise zones.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ROBERT DOLE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I am committed to a federal role in helping those Americans
who need help in entering the mainstream of society. As someone who
is disabled as the result of wounds received during World War II, I
am sensitive to the needs of people who, due to factors beyond
their control, may need a boost in climbing the ladder of
opportunity. For these people, I am committed to continuing and
strengthening programs that provide assistance and promote the goal
of economic self-sufficiency, not dependence on government aid.
   ``Furthermore, I would ensure that the benefits of the federal
programs reach rural communities. Currently, federal funding
formulas, particularly those which target low-income groups,
discriminate against rural America. Retraining programs should
focus on the explosion in services and information-based
industries. And finally, the federal government should use existing
loan programs to foster private investment in rural industries.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JACK KEMP</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I believe the best way to make opportunity real for every
rural community across the South is to lower interest rates and
income tax rates, while focusing new pro-growth incentives for
entrepreneurship, investment and business growth in depressed rural
areas.
   ``I have proposed enterprise zones for depressed urban and rural
areas. Experience with state enterprise zones proves that federal
tax incentives, regulatory relief, and community involvement can
unleash a flood of new seed capital, new businesses, and new hope
for the rural South.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PAT ROBERTSON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The costly welfare bureaucracy must be steamlined so that
funds reach those truly in need. ... I would initiate measures that
would restore people to productive lives, while giving special
attention to the needs of single women with children, and the
long-term health care needs of the elderly.
   ``We need a youth opportunity wage to bring our young people
into the job market, and more on-the-job training for them. ... The
needs of our rural citizens deserve the same priority as those of
their city counterparts.''
   ``Resolving poverty in the rural South goes hand-in-hand with
upgrading excellence in education. Education is the turnkey.''
   Robertson proposed launching a private program ``to combat
illiteracy among America's poor _ all without spending one dime in
government assistance. ... I would move swiftly to mobilize every
resource to provide rural students with qualified teachers and a
competitive, quality education _ an urgent need in the South.''
   ``With the decline of industrial relocation to the Sunbelt, more
creative initiatives must be taken to stimulate the Southern
economy. ... Strategies of cooperation between government,
universities and business that helped spark an economic revival in
the Northeast can be adapted to the unique growth potential of the
South.''
</TEXT>
