<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Collaborators     03-04 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Collaborators,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Collaborators Face Growing Danger From Neighbors</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OBEDIYEH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ibrahim Radaydeh's name is
scrawled on walls all over town. He is a marked man and knows it.
His fellow Palestinians may kill him as an informer.
   Palestinians suspected of collaborating with Israel have been
attacked by their neighbors. One was lynched.
   It is a sign of the spread and greater organization of the Arab
uprising that began 12 weeks ago in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Israel was shocked when other villagers in Qabatiyeh hanged
Mohammed Ayad from a utility pole and burned his house. During the
five-hour rampage last week, Ayad fired on the crowd with an
Israeli-issue Uzi submachine gun, killing a 4-year-old boy.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization applauded the lynching in
leaflets distributed in the West Bank.
   Arsonists have burned shops or homes of other suspects, many of
whom have been identified by name on a pirate Arabic-language radio
station.
   About two dozen Palestinians have renounced connections with
Israel over mosque loudspeakers in the past two weeks, handed over
Israeli-supplied weapons to village leaders and received letters
saying they have reformed, the Arab-run Palestine Press Service
reported.
   It said most West Bank villages are believed to have a few
collaborators, although the agency estimated they total less 1
percent of the 800,000 Arabs in the territory.
   Residents say there are about 10 suspects in Obediyeh, a town of
7,000 people on the outskirts of Bethlehem. The main job of
informers in the current turmoil is to give Israeli authorities the
names of activists in their villages.
   Some work for money, special privileges or promotions in their
jobs in Israel. Others became informers in exchange for shorter
sentences after they were arrested.
   Israeli soldiers have done little to help the collaborators, and
leaders of both major parties have said that may cost Israel the
few allies it has among Palestinians.
   ``As a Jew and a soldier, I am ashamed,'' former Defense
Minister Ariel Sharon of the right-wing Likud bloc said after Ayad
was lynched. ``How could we have left this man without help for so
many hours? This was a moral failure.''
   Amnon Linn, a legislator from the center-right Labor Party,
said: ``Now every Arab in the occupied territories knows this is
what he can expect if he is working with us to achieve peace.''
   Radaydeh, 41, is suspected of helping his nephew, Ali Abu Bakr,
give the Israelis information. Abu Bakr is said to have bragged
about a year ago that he worked with the army.
   His neighbors were willing to overlook it then, but not now in
the heat of the uprising.
   He three-room home, where he lived with his wife and six
children, was gutted by fire last week and he fled the town. His
burned-out car still sits outside the shell.
   ``If Abu Bakr tries to come back here, he will be massacred,''
said an elderly man, barefoot and wearing a long robe, who gave his
name only as Khalid. ``Parents whose sons were arrested will be
after him.''
   Some villagers said they had suspected Radaydeh for months but
most became convinced he was a collaborator only last weekend, when
he was seen standing on a dirt road watching about 100 masked
villagers protest.
   No soldiers were there, but the next night troops entered town
and arrested 32 of the protesters.
   That was enough for Radaydeh's neighbors. Spray-painted messages
like this appeared on the walls of homes throughout Obediyeh: ``We
warn collaborators like Ibrahim Radaydeh to flee as soon as
possible. Beware, hypocrites.''
   One protester who not at home when the soldiers came was
31-year-old Jamil, who would not give his last name.
   ``Collaborators are worse than the Israelis,'' he said. ``They
are an internal enemy. They know everything and can do more harm.
Radaydeh has no future in this village.''
   Jamil stood outside a friend's house watching the road for signs
of Israeli army jeeps.
   During an interview in his home, Radaydeh insisted on his
innocence. He squinted nervously, smoking a cigarette.
   ``I want you to write that I went to a Bethlehem newspaper and
asked them to publish an announcement denouncing my nephew, Abu
Bakr,'' he said. ``I think collaborators should be lynched. I want
the PLO to know I am not one. These are rumors spread by a few
vicious children.''
   His neighbors are unmoved.
   Mahtar Assin, the mukhtar, or town leader, sipped thick, sweet
Arabic coffee and said: ``Whatever he says, the Palestinian
revolution may well take its revenge next on Ibrahim. If he wants
to be safe, Radaydeh should leave Obediyeh now.''
</TEXT>
