<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0228EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO-Gorbachev     03-04 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO-Gorbachev,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Leaders Differ On Dealing With Gorbachev</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His name didn't appear on the agenda,
but it was on nearly every leader's lips during the first NATO
summit since Mikhail S. Gorbachev assumed power in the Kremlin
three years ago.
   Gorbachev was a shadow on the wall as President Reagan and
leaders of 15 Western democracies tried to size up their potential
foe.
   The two-day session was designed mainly to present a united
front on key arms control issues before Reagan travels to Moscow in
May or June for his fourth summit with the Soviet Commmist Party
leader.
   But the alliance meeting showed how intensely Washington and its
North Atlantic Treaty Organization allies are trying to assess the
implications of Gorbachev's efforts to open up parts of Soviet
society. They wonder whether it will help Western security or harm
it.
   The meeting also underscored the difference in Western views _
particularly between Washington and London on one hand and Paris
and Bonn on the other _ about how NATO governments should deal with
Gorbachev.
   Some want to give Gorbachev the benefit of the doubt; others do
not.
   The issue is important to NATO because Gorbachev in recent
months appears to have succeeded in portraying himself to much of
the West European public as more of a peace seeker than the West's
leaders.
   A Gallup poll last year said 58 percent of Britons thought
Russia sincerely wanted peaceful relations with NATO, while only 33
percent thought its foreign policy initiatives should be treated
with great suspicion.
   The West German magazine Der Spiegel says that according to
recent polls conducted on its behalf, Gorbachev has become the
first Soviet leader to get a higher popularity rating than an
American president.
   The Reagan administration is worried about the popularity among
many West Europeans of Gorbachev's goal of eliminating all nuclear
weapons from the European continent.
   Washington fears that if this happened the trans-Atlantic
partnership would be severed and Western Europe would be vulnerable
to Soviet intimidation.
   A joint NATO declaration Thursday noted ``encouraging signs of
change'' in Soviet policies and welcomed moves to open up the East
bloc societies.
   But it also said the Western nations must ``look beyond
pronouncements'' for tangible and lasting changes that directly
address the issues that have kept the European continent divided
for four decades.
   This was a reference partly to what the NATO countries consider
to be a systematic denial by the Soviets of basic human rights for
their citizens, and, in part, the Soviet military domination of
Eastern Europe.
   Yet for all their words of caution, some Western leaders appear
increasingly convinced that Gorbachev is genuine in saying he wants
to establish more peaceful relations with the West at a lower level
of arms.
   ``Gorbachev has opened possibilities that we should take
advantage of dynamically and boldly. That's where the challenge
lies,'' Belgian Prime Minister Wilfried Martens told the NATO
conference.
   He said ``the future of Europe'' may depend on the outcome of
Gorbachev's reform efforts.
   French President Francois Mitterrand was quoted by his aides as
telling the Brussels summit that the Soviet Union was undergoing an
``historic transition.''
   ``We must not be naive, but we must show flexibility that will
enable dialogue and which will have an effect on Gorbachev's
actions,'' he said.
   Last week, Mitterrand was quoted in a French newspaper interview
as saying NATO should put off plans to modernize some of its
nuclear weapons in Europe in order not to upset the trend of
improving East-West relations. He did not specifically address this
in Brussels.
   Most of the other alliance leaders want to go ahead with the
weapons modernization program.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said after Thursday's
meeting that NATO must keep its defenses strong by upgrading
nuclear as well as non-nuclear weaponry, regardless of signs of
change in the Kremlin.
   ``So long as our defense stays sure, we have nothing to fear''
from Gorbachev's reforms, she said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDITOR'S NOTE: Robert Burns has covered the North Atlantic</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Treaty Organization from his base in Brussels since 1984.
</TEXT>
