<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Swindall'sHouse     03-04 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall's House,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dream Home Becomes Nightmare For Congressman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What was to have been U.S. Rep. Pat
Swindall's dream house has turned into a political albatross,
dripping with threatened lawsuits and leaving the congressman
battling suggestions of money-laundering.
   Swindall designed the 12,500-square-foot house for him and his
wife, Kimberly, near Stone Mountain State Park.
   ``The ultimate irony is I started out wanting to build a log
cabin,'' said the Republican congressman.
   Nine subcontractors have filed liens against the property, and
Swindall has appeared before a federal grand jury investigating an
accused money launderer who once lent the congressman money.
   Swindall, a lawyer, has tried to stay out of court over the
thousands of dollars in contested bills and said he has asked his
pastor and his general contractor's pastor to help him resolve the
dispute.
   ``There is a route you ought to follow that is biblically
prescribed in Matthew 18,'' said Swindall. ``First, you confront
the person alone, which I've done, and he denied everything.
Secondly, you take them before their church, which I intend to do.
I don't think Christians ought to be suing other Christians.''
   The three-story mansion, built on 13 heavily wooded acres and
overlooking a small lake, has seven bedrooms, 7{ bathrooms, a
mother-in-law suite, a swimming pool, a tennis court and a
three-car garage.
   The size and cost of the house was made an issue by Ben Jones, a
Democrat who nearly upset Swindall's 1986 re-election bid. Jones
said it was built at cut rates by John Sauers, a political
supporter tied to the religious right.
   Swindall, 37, laughs at hints of a ``sweetheart deal'' from
Sauers, his general contractor, because the two and numerous
subcontractors are feuding over unpaid bills.
   Swindall blames Sauers for delays, poor workmanship and cost
overruns that he said tacked $300,000 to the price of the house.
Their contract was an oral, cost-plus-10-percent agreement that
gave Sauers unlimited access to Swindall's construction account,
the congressman said.
   Swindall claims Sauers, whom he fired in November, failed to pay
subcontractors and used the congressman's credit to buy supplies
for other projects.
   Sauers denies the charges and says he built Swindall a fine
home. The house costs ``were extremely fair,'' he said, adding that
Swindall's claims of shoddy work ``is like telling Van Gogh he
can't paint or Michaelangelo he can't sculpt.''
   Rusty Johnson, a Smyrna flooring contractor, is among the
subcontractors who say the congressman owes them money.
   ``You try to pay your taxes then your damn local congressman
don't pay you,'' said Johnson, who says Swindall owes him $5,395.
He said he rejected an offer from Swindall to settle at 50 cents on
the dollar.
   Swindall said the cost overruns led him to borrow $150,000 from
former Atlanta businessman Charles LeChasney, indicted in January
on federal money-laundering charges.
   While seeking a permanent home loan last fall, Swindall said, he
negotiated an interim construction loan from LeChasney but returned
the $150,000 check after becoming suspicious of him.
   Swindall voluntarily testified about the loan before a federal
grand jury last month.
   The congressman admits to ``poor judgment'' in some dealings
with Sauers but blames part of his predicament on ``placing too
much responsibility on my wife.''
   The house ``was my wife's project,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
