<DOCNO> AP880304-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MinimumWage     03-04 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minimum Wage,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Approves Increase in Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to raise the federal minimum wage
from $3.35 an hour to $4.65 over the next three years has won House
subcommittee approval, but organized labor failed in a bid to tie
future increases to inflation.
   With voting along strict party lines, the Democratic-controlled
House labor standards subcommittee approved the bill on Thursday.
The full House Education and Labor Committee plans to take up the
measure next week.
   Subcommittee Chairman Austin J. Murphy, D-Pa., said the current
minimum of $3.35 an hour ``no longer provides the same level of
opportunity to improve one's life that it once did.''
   ``Our actions here today represent a step in the right
direction,'' he said. ``An increase in the minimum wage will
certainly help many low-wage workers achieve a measure of dignity.''
   Organized labor supports the legislation, while the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce and the National Restaurant Association oppose any
minimum wage increase.
   The subcommittee approved the legislation 6-3 with all the
Democrats for the measure and all the Republicans opposed.
Democrats earlier defeated several Republican-sponsored amendments
either to water down the legislation or kill it outright.
   One amendment, sponsored by Rep. Thomas E. Petri, R-Wis., would
have increased the minimum just 65 cents over the next three years.
It was rejected on party lines.
   However, labor did not gain all it had been seeking over the
past year. The subcommittee, on a motion by Timothy J. Penny,
D-Minn., refused on a 7-2 vote to tie future increases to inflation.
   Penny said he was ``concerned about something like this being on
automatic pilot. Congress should review any future increases.''
   He also said automatic increases in the minimum wage could lead
to higher inflation.
   Rep. Augustus F. Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the full
committee, disputed that argument, saying ``wages lag behind
inflation and will always do so as long as they are based on past
experience.''
   A similar bill has been introduced in the Senate by Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Labor and Education Committee.
The panel has held hearings but has not placed the measure on its
business agenda yet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BankDeregulation     03-04 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Deregulation,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supporters Say Senate Bill Would Benefit Customers Through
Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation broadening the power of banks to
enter the securities industry but narrowing their opportunities to
offer insurance would offer a mixed bag to consumers of financial
services.
   The provisions are contained in a bill passed late Wednesday by
the Senate Banking Committee. The bill, which must go before the
full Senate, dismantles most of the barriers between commercial and
investment banking in place since the Depression.
   Supporters say businesses and state and local governments would
pay lower underwriting fees because of added competition in the
securities business. They say individual investors would pay lower
mutual fund fees for the same reason.
   Home buyers could save as much as $1,000 on a $100,000 mortgage,
says Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., chairman of the committee and
the bill's sponsor.
   Consumer groups are also hailing a section, sponsored by Sen.
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., that provides new safeguards on home
equity loans.
   But limits on bank involvement in insurance, also sponsored by
Dodd, could hamper competition in that field, they say.
   Despite the lopsided 18-2 vote by the Senate committee,
signaling almost certain passage in the full Senate, similar bills
in the House face more uncertain prospects. There, jurisdiction
over the issue is shared by the Energy and Commerce and the Banking
committees.
   House Banking Committee Chairman Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
has expressed great skepticism about allowing banks too many new
powers.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the finance
subcommittee of the Energy and Commerce Committee, has said he
favors phasing in new powers for banks so federal regulatory
agencies aren't swamped.
   ``It is essential that Congress link the introduction of new
powers to regulatory preparedness,'' he said in a statement
Thursday.
   The home equity loan section of the Proxmire bill requires
lenders to disclose the interest rate on loans in a clear and
uniform manner as well as closing costs and repayment terms. It
also would prohibit lenders from unilaterally changing the terms of
a home equity line of credit after the contract is signed.
   Michelle Meier, an attorney for the Consumer's Union, and Leslie
Gainer of U.S. PIRG, a group associated with consumer activist
Ralph Nader, said in a statement that the Proxmire version is an
improvement over a similar home equity bill in the House, which
does not bar unilateral changes.
   Another section would make it easier for consumers to shop for a
place to put their money by requiring banks and mutual funds to
advertise in a uniform manner the interest rate paid on deposits
and money market accounts.
   Under the bill, banks would get immediate power to underwrite
mortgage-backed securities, commercial paper and municipal revenue
bonds.
   They would be able to deal in mutual funds and corporate bonds
six months after enactment. But, in a concession to the securities
industry, banks would not be allowed to underwrite corporate stock
_ viewed by senators as the riskiest securities area _ unless
Congress authorizes that in a separate vote early in 1991.
   On insurance, the bill permits state officials to authorize
state-chartered banks and bank holding companies to underwrite
insurance within their home states. But they will not be able to
sell insurance outside their home state. And the bill would close
loopholes that permit some national banks to sell insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
