<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0258EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Taxes     03-04 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Taxes,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Element Of Truth In Both Gephardt's Charge And Dukakis' Denial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In campaign sparring, Rep. Richard Gephardt has
accused Democratic rival Gov. Michael Dukakis of taxing average
families to close a state budget deficit. Dukakis, for his part,
claims he has cut a record amount in taxes.
   Both men have a point.
   Dukakis, governor of Massachusetts for nine of the past 13
years, has served the state as chief executive in the best and
worst of times. In that period, the state has increased taxes by
about $500 million and cut taxes in a series of steps by more than
$700 million.
   As governor, Dukakis signed all those measures. Some he
initiated, some he merely tolerated and some he resisted.
   In a campaign debate Monday night, Dukakis criticized Gephardt
for his 1981 federal tax bill vote, saying the ``Iowa Gephardt''
soft-pedaled that vote.
   Gephardt shot back, asking ``What about the Massachusetts
Dukakis that raised taxes on average families?''
   Dukakis responded by saying he had ``cut taxes five times in the
last four years.''
   But Gephardt persisted: ``Why did you raise taxes on average
families in 1974?''
   In fact, Massachusetts did raise taxes under Dukakis in 1975,
when Dukakis took office from a Republican governor and inherited a
$530 million deficit in a $4 billion budget.
   The deficit forced Dukakis to go back on the ``lead-pipe''
guarantee he made in his 1974 campaign not to raise taxes. Acting
with the Legislature, Dukakis borrowed $450 million to close the
gap and put through $110 million in ``sin'' taxes and another $350
million in a surcharge on the state's 5 percent income tax.
   Dukakis also imposed drastic cuts in social spending, which
balanced the budget but which are widely blamed for costing him the
governorship in 1978, when he was defeated by conservative Democrat
Edward J. King. One of King's top advisers, Edward Reilly, is now a
Gephardt strategist.
   Since Dukakis returned to office in 1983, state taxes have been
reduced by more than $700 million, according to Frank Keefe,
Dukakis' secretary of administration and finance. Keefe also notes
that Massachusetts has seen its bond rating improve and the cost of
state and local government fall to near the bottom of national
rankings.
   ``I think the governor deserves the reputation of being the
biggest tax-cutter in the history of the commonwealth _ a record I
don't think will be matched in two generations,'' Keefe said.
   Dukakis does, however, have bitter detractors in Massachusetts.
Prominent among them is Barbara Anderson, executive director of
Citizens for Limited Taxation, a tax-fighting group that has been
supplying ammunition against Dukakis to the rival campaigns of
Gephardt and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
   Anderson said in an interview that if tax cuts are defined as
any reductions Dukakis signed, ``then you'd have a wash.''
   But she argues that Dukakis has consistently resisted tax cuts
over the years and proposed only minor ones. She notes that Dukakis
opposed Proposition 2{, the 1980 ballot question that limited local
property taxes, although she does not note that virtually every
politician did.
   Her group's list of grievances against Dukakis also includes
keeping the income tax surcharge for 10 years, advocating a
graduated state income tax in 1976, increasing the capital gains
tax in 1983, proposing $300 million in business taxes to fund an
infrastructure bank, vetoing a tax cut for senior citizens and
pushing for a ``unitary'' tax on multistate corporations.
   But CLT's biggest complaint involves a protracted, complex
struggle over taxes in 1986 that resulted in repeal of the surtax
and the imposition by the voters of a cap on state revenues.
Anderson claims Dukakis resisted both moves at every turn.
   Richard Manley, head of the non-partisan Massachusetts Taxpayers
Foundation, gives Dukakis more credit.
   ``I think it's fair to say Dukakis has never been
philosophically a guy who wants to cut taxes. But I think it's also
fair to say that the surtax part of the 1975 package hung around
his neck like an albatross,'' Manley said.
   ``He's no pal of mine. But if you look at the thing objectively,
the fact is the (1975) deficit was inherited and somebody had to
pay it,'' he said. ``Did he repeal the surtax? No. The Legislature
did. He went along ... but I don't think it's fair to say in any
way that he's a tax raiser.''
</TEXT>
