<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SuperTuesdayMedia Bjt   03-04 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Super Tuesday Media, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airwaves Heat up as Super Tuesday Looms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. entered his first
``attack ad'' in the Super Tuesday sweepstakes as two of his
Democratic rivals went at each other over a commercial about
corporate contributions.
   The political TV ads heated up and proliferated Thursday in
preparation for the presidential primaries and caucuses next week
in 20 states, most of them in the South.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis sparked a chain reaction with
his new ad challenging Rep. Richard Gephardt's message to the
little people that ``it's your fight, too.''
   The Dukakis ad consists of a rolling list of corporate political
action committees that have contributed to Gephardt's campaign.
``Is Dick Gephardt really fighting your fight, or theirs?'' asks
the narrator.
   Gephardt, who has been running ads criticizing both Dukakis and
Gore for days, staged an airport news conference and blasted
Dukakis for questioning his sincerity and record of fighting for
working people.
   ``I'm very upset about it,'' Gephardt told reporters at
Baltimore-Washington International Airport. ``I've never made a
decision in my public life based on (PAC) contributions. Some who
are raising money for me were grievously damaged by (the 1986) tax
reform.''
   Gephardt accused Dukakis of accepting millions from ``special
interests who do business with the state of Massachusetts'' and
said his campaign would release a partial list on Friday.
   ``The Dukakis campaign does not take a dime of corporate PAC
money or any money from a lobbyist registered in the state of
Massachusetts,'' responded Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach.
   Gore introduced a 60-second ad consisting entirely of an excerpt
from a debate last month in Dallas. It is running ``in a great
number of markets in a great number of states,'' said Gore
spokesman Mark Armour.
   The spot shows the Tennessee senator accusing Gephardt of voting
against minimum wage increases, against creating the Department of
Education, for tuition tax credits and for Reaganomics _ and
reversing his positions on all four issues.
   ``The next president of the United States has to be someone the
American people can believe will stay with his convictions. ...
You've got to be willing to stand your ground and be consistent,''
Gore tells Gephardt.
   A Gephardt spokeswoman said the Missouri congressman's campaign
would have no direct response to the Gore ad.
   Negative commercials, dubbed ``attack ads'' by the campaigns,
were the order of the day for the Republican front-runners as well.
Vice President George Bush and Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole
continued their television attacks on each other in ads that began
earlier in the week.
   A GOP official said he is not worried about the intensity of the
campaign as long as the two keep their advertising accurate.
   ``This is hardball. We're talking high stakes here,'' said Frank
Fahrenkopf, chairman of the Republican National Committee.
   ``I think the tone and rhetoric really in both campaigns has
gotten pretty rough,'' Fahrenkopf told reporters in Boston. But he
added, ``In many ways I've welcomed what's happened. In January I
was concerned with the lack of fire in the belly.''
   Both Bush and Dukakis have stepped up their Super Tuesday media
campaigns in recent days, both in scope and frequency of ads, and
Gore was expected to do the same. ``We intend to outspend the other
Democratic candidates on media in the Super Tuesday states,''
Armour said.
</TEXT>
