<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CollegeRacism 1stLd-Writethru a0893 03-04 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-College Racism, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0893,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Student Activist Receives Threatening Letter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with fraternity banned from
campus; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Tillard will ...'; SUBS 11th graf
pvs, `On Monday ...' with two grafs to UPDATE with ban.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A black student activist at the University of Pennsylvania was
under 24-hour protection Thursday after receiving a death threat,
and an all-white fraternity was banned from campus for hiring two
black strippers for a party.
   Earlier Thursday, about 300 people rallied at Dartmouth College
in a protest against bigotry.
   The threat was made against Conrad Tillard, director of the
Organization of Black Consciousness, which had called for the
ouster of the primarily Jewish fraternity Zeta Beta Tau from the
Ivy League school in Philadelphia.
   The university had charged that black strippers at a ZBT party
in September danced naked with a prospective freshman pledge before
a jeering audience shouting racial epithets.
   The threatening letter was sent to a reporter at the school
newspaper, the Daily Pennsylvanian. The writer claimed to be a
student member of the Jewish Defense League.
   However, school officials said they do not believe the writer is
a student, and the JDL denied any connection with the threat.
   Tillard will receive round-the-clock protection by campus police
``as long as it necessary,'' said security spokeswoman Sylvia
Canada.
   Police said they were investigating the letter. The FBI also
said they have received the letter but declined comment.
   ``The main thing it said was that I was a target on their hit
list,'' Tillard said. ``It also said that in general they're trying
to stop the rise of this black power group that I'm helping bring
about.''
   In Hanover, N.H., the rally was sparked by a conservative
off-campus student newspaper's criticism of a black professor's
teaching ability and his music course. The night before, about 200
people held a candlelight march.
   Members of Dartmouth's Afro-American organized the protests
aimed at The Dartmouth Review. Four Review staff members are
charged by the school with harassing the professor, William Cole,
after confronting him in his classroom over the article.
   At the rally, music professor John Appleton defended his
colleague, saying, ``We must find a away to put an end to Jim Crow,
to jingoism, to sexism and to just plain ignorance that the Review
seeks to foster on this campus.''
   On Monday, demonstrators at a Penn rally sponsored by the
Organization of Black Consciousness had called for the ouster from
campus of a ZBT, which was charge by the university with lewdness,
indecent exposure and hazing.
   Late Thursday, the 112-member fraternity announced that it had
been banned from campus until at least the fall of 1989.
   The threatening letter did not mention the fraternity incident,
Tillard said.
   ``The racial tension on the campus has been very, very high for
a long time,'' said Jacqueline Wade, director of Penn's
Afro-American Studies department. ``This is just one indicator of
the level. It's part of a larger whole of racism on this campus.''
   Penn spokesman Bill Epstein said university officials believe
the death threat was written by a Penn student. ``We've checked
around,'' said Epstein. ``There's no sign of the JDL.''
   Mordechai Levey, international director of the New York-based
JDL, said that several Jews on campus were affilitated with the
organization but that the JDL played no role in the threat.
   Rabbi Howard Alperg, director of the Jewish Campus Activities
Board, called the ZBT incident deplorable but added: ``To claim
that it is now a Jewish-black issue is also deplorable.''
   ``There are black radicals who are trying to turn it into a
black-Jewish issue,'' Alperg said. ``That is perceived by Jewish
students as being anti-Semitic.''
   Relationships between black and Jewish students were strained in
1986 during a confrontation over attempts by the Black Student
Unity Conference to have Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan
give a speech.
   Farrakhan did not speak; his organization said it was not
satisfied with the security arrangements.
   On Wednesday, minority students at Hampshire College in Amherst,
Mass., ended their nine-day occupation of a dormitory office after
administrators signed a 16-point agreement aimed at encouraging
racial harmony.
</TEXT>
