<DOCNO> AP880304-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CopKilled     03-04 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cop Killed,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arrested in Slaying of Rookie Cop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said they arrested two men late Thursday
in the slaying of a rookie police officer shot at point-blank range
in his patrol car Feb. 26 outside the home of a drug witness he was
guarding.
   The men, whose names were not released, had been picked up
Thursday for questioning along with two women who were later
released, said Officer Peter O'Donnell, a police spokesman.
   Details of the arrests in the slaying of 22-year-old Officer
Edward Byrne will be released Friday, he said.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward had described the slaying as
an ``assassination'' meant to intimidate drug witnesses. Byrne was
killed by shots from a car that had apparently coasted up to his
early in the morning.
   Since the slaying, detectives have flooded the Queens
neighborhood, arresting 256 street-level crack dealers in hopes of
extracting information about the killing.
   ``Shooting at cops, it's just bad for business. I think
experienced criminals know that; perhaps these inexperienced ones
will learn it,'' Ward said.
   The reward for information leading to the conviction of the
killer grew to $130,000 Thursday with a $25,000 contribution from
members of the New York Stock Exchange. More than 10,000 officers
attended Byrne's funeral.
   WNBC-TV reported Wednesday night that investigators identified
two men _ including the gunman _ and two women believed to have
been in the car from which the shots were fired.
   A police spokesman, Capt. Tom Fahey, asked earlier about the
WNBC report, said, ``The case has not been solved. The reward is
still in effect, we still need the cooperation of the community to
help us solve this case.''
   The broadcast report also said police believed the killing was
ordered by Lorenzo ``Fat Cat'' Nichols, 29, a reputed drug kingpin
sentenced Feb. 25 to 25 years to life in prison for narcotics and
weapons possession.
   He is also awaiting trial on charges he had his parole officer
killed for revenge.
</TEXT>
