<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignViaSatellite     03-04 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Via Satellite,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates Blitz Local Newscasts With Satellite Interviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly every night for the past week and a
half, Sen. Albert Gore Jr. has delivered himself by satellite to
television stations in Super Tuesday states for interviews on local
newscasts.
   The Tennessee Democrat also appeared via satellite for a
campaign pep rally with supporters assembled in more than 50
locations and for a question-and-answer session with students on
more than 100 college campuses.
   ``Everybody is having to do things like this in view of
campaigning in 20 states at the same time,'' said Arlie Schardt, a
spokesman for Gore. ``It's economical and it's the best method of
reaching large numbers of voters.''
   As the approaching Super Tuesday primaries strain campaign
warchests and candidate schedules, satellite ``uplinking'' is being
used by presidential hopefuls to increase their exposure to voters
in the cheapest way possible.
   Though many stations refuse these brief interview opportunities,
the chance for ``live'' time with the candidates has become
attractive to smaller stations in areas where the contenders are
not likely to appear in person.
   But some media experts say the new high-tech tool of the 1988
campaign does not serve the public well.
   ``It plays on the vanity of the local media because everyone
wants to be seen interviewing a presidential candidate, but the
tough questions aren't being asked'' by the local interviewers,
said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a communications professor at the
University of Texas at Austin.
   ``The candidates won't run into any Sam Donaldsons in the 132nd
market,'' said Stephen Hess, senior fellow at the Washington,
D.C.-based Brookings Institution, referring to ABC's tough,
sometimes abrasive White House correspondent.
   Costs for transmitting via satellite vary depending on location
and equipment used, but generally it is far less expensive than
producing and airing an advertisement.
   Airing a 30-second ad on a Boston television station during the
popular Cosby Show program can cost $30,000, while buying 90
minutes of satellite time that can be used for five-minute
interviews by 18 stations costs about $2,000, said Gary Galanis, a
spokesman for Democrat Paul Simon's campaign.
   ``We at this point don't have the resources to buy even a
minimum amount of paid advertising, which would probably be about a
million dollars to hit all the Super Tuesday states,'' Galanis said.
   ``You can't mold your message as well with satellite interviews,
but you can get two to three minutes on a local newscast,'' he
said. ``Paid advertising ... is the best thing, but the next best
thing is satellite uplinks.''
   Tim Archie, a spokesman for Republican Bob Dole, said large
stations in major markets are less likely to accept a satellite
interview because they are in cities where the candidates are
appearing anyway. These stations also often have a reporter on the
road with the campaigns.
   But for other stations, satellite interviews ``give the stations
a sense of an exclusive,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0347EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CensusUndercount     03-04 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Census Undercount,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Census Adjustment Decision Is Attacked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A number of Democratic congressmen want the
final totals of the 1990 national census adjusted to make up for
the many minority group members and city dwellers they say will be
overlooked.
   Commerce Department and Census officials, who have refused to
agree to such changes, were criticized Thursday at a hearing for
making ``shameful'' and ``political'' decisions.
   Every Census since 1790 has seen at least some criticism for the
so-called ``undercount,'' and the complaints have grown in recent
years despite improvements in census taking.
   Officials estimate that in 1980 only about 1 percent of
Americans were missed in the national head count. But they admit
the problem was much greater among minorities and in cities than it
was for other groups.
   Studies were launched to try and determine if adjustments could
be made to compensate for this problem, but last October the
decision was announced that there would be no adjustment in 1990.
   Pointing out that the people usually missed are most often
minorities and city residents, where the Democratic party
predominates, Rep. Charles Schumer of New York termed the decision
not to adjust ``shameful'' and ``political.''
   He said the action was not based ``on fair-minded concern about
accurate statistics; it's a raw exercise of partisan politics.''
   Schumer's remarks came Thursday at a hearing of the House Post
Office and Civil Service census subcommittee. Reps. Mervyn M.
Dymally of California and Robert Garcia of New York also raised
concerns about the decision not to adjust. All three are Democrats.
   Commerce Undersecretary Robert Ortner denied that politics were
involved in the decision, contending that statisticians disagree on
whether there is an accurate method of making adjustments.
   ``I don't think it would make the problem any better if we were
to devise an elaborate mathematical system to make up new
numbers,'' Ortner said.
   The focus of the problem is the fact that all 435 seats in the
House of Representatives and billions of dollars in state and
federal money are distributed on the basis of the figures collected
every 10 years by the Census Bureau.
</TEXT>
