<1ST_LINE>r p PM-KansasGOP     03-04 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kansas GOP,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kansas Republicans Elect Final 14 Delegates Saturday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEW FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas Republicans convene Saturday to elect
the last 14 of the state's 34 delegates to the Republican National
Convention, and it's expected to be a good day for Bob Dole.
   All will be pledged to support the Kansas senator on the first
ballot in New Orleans, since Dole claimed all but 16 of the 1,249
county delegates elected five weeks ago in the Kansas GOP caucuses.
   The convention also will ratify the election of five delegates
recommended from congressional district conventions held Feb. 20.
The other 15 national delegates were elected at the district level.
   No contests are expected for the 14 slots still to be filled,
but some challenges are expected for the final 14 alternate
delegates to be elected. Kansas also has 34 alternates.
   Gov. Mike Hayden, Sen. Nancy Kassebaum and other elected
officials, party leaders and prominent Republicans will claim the
14 open delegate positions, sources said. Their election is not
automatic, but nobody is expected to challenge them for the slots
out of respect for their prestige and position.
   The 1,249 delegates elected at county conventions Feb. 1-7 are
all eligible to attend the state convention and vote on the
national delegates, but some are not likely to show up.
   Hayden, who is expected to be elected chairman of the delegation
going to New Orleans in support of Dole, and Kassebaum will address
the convention.
   State GOP Chairman Fred Logan Jr. said Dole also may talk to the
convention by telephone but the senator will not come to Topeka.
   ``The main order of business is to elect the rest of our 34
delegates for Bob Dole,'' Logan said.
   The national convention is Aug. 15-18 in New Orleans.
</TEXT>
