<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-AmericanJews     03-04 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-American Jews,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Jews Say Criticism of Israel Should be Private, Not
Public</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Jewish leaders ending a visit to
Israel say they are still troubled by the ongoing violence in the
occupied lands but are convinced that U.S. Jews should air their
criticisms in private, not public.
   It is a formula supported by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who
told the American Jewish leaders this week: ``It is absolutely
un-Jewish and very dangerous to join an anti-Israeli front with
non-Jews'' by publicly chastizing Israel.
   The 42-member Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations
met in Jerusalem for a week-long annual conference that ended
Thursday.
   Morris B. Abram, the group's chairman, said he had arrived with
``a good deal of anguish, a good deal of anxiety and misgivings.''
   Other American Jewish leaders also have spoken publicly of their
concern over seeing nightly television footage and reading daily
news reports on the Israel army's tough tactics to quell three
months of unrest in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Reports of troops using excessive beatings of Palestinians and
burying alive four Arabs near Nablus heightened that unease.
   But Abram said that, after private meetings with Israel's
political and military leaders, ``I have not the slightest doubt
the policy is to use restraint ... and the time is not right to
publicly criticize Israel's handling of the unrest.
   ``The question is not whether American Jews have the right to
express dissatisfaction. Of course they do,'' Abram said in an
interview with The Associated Press. ``The question is, on matters
of Israel's defense and security, is public criticism effective or
prudent?''
   Shamir called on the U.S. Jewish leaders to stifle outspoken
criticism among their ranks.
   ``Every critical statement of a Jewish leader does much more
harm than many violent demonstrations in Gaza,'' Shamir said. ``It
is inconceivable that, God forbid, American Jews would permit
themselves to be used in the campaign against us.''
   Not all U.S. Jewish leaders agree they should be silent partners
with Israel.
   ``We as Jews need to cut through our illusions and
self-delusions about Israel,'' Albert Vorspan, vice president of
the Union of American Hebrew Congregations, told the organization.
   He said American Jews should speak out about their concerns and
warn Israeli leaders that ``the TV pictures that multiply every day
are potentially explosive'' in terms of Israel's image abroad.
   Vorspan also expressed frustration that Israel's divided
government seemed to be throwing away a chance for peace.
   He described U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz's Middle East
peace mission as ``a shuttle between Shamir and (his rival, Foreign
Minister Shimon) Peres.''
   The deep divisions in Israel's government concern some U.S.
Jewish leaders as much as Israel's inability to put down the
anti-occupation unrest. Some warn that that issue is potentially
more damaging to Israel's relations with the United States than the
riots themselves.
   Zvi Rafiah, a retired Israeli diplomat who served in Israel's
embassy in Washington, said U.S. leaders are alarmed because Israel
appears ``incapable, even incompetent in resolving one of its most
important problems, the peace process.''
   In a speech to the Jewish leaders, Rafiah warned: ``The
Palestinian problem has become a time bomb in our relationship with
the United States.''
</TEXT>
