<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MilitaryReserves 350   03-04 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Military Reserves, 350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Says Reserve Forces Are Reaching Capacity Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-level board of military and civilian
advisers is departing from its normal policy stance and questioning
the future of a build-up in reserve forces.
   The suggestion that the reserve forces may be overextended comes
as budget problems appear likely to prevent any significant growth
in reserve and National Guard forces in fiscal 1989.
   In recent years, the 22-member Reserve Forces Policy board has
consistently argued that more money be appropriated for the
reserves because of their increasing role in military preparedness
and strategy.
   The Selected Reserve Forces _ the drilling, so-called ``weekend
warriors'' _ now total more than 1.1 million people, compared with
the 2.1 million on active duty.
   Under the so-called ``Total Force'' policy adopted in 1973, many
of those reservists and Guardsmen would go to war before their
active-duty counterparts because of the equipment they use or the
jobs for which they have been trained.
   The policy board, in its just-released fiscal 1987 report,
repeats its plea for greater financial support for the reserve
forces. But it also advances the unexpected suggestion that the
Pentagon should attend to the strength of its active-duty forces
first.
   ``An appropriate balance should exist between the active and
reserve components,'' the board stated.
   According to Col. Phil Fogel, an aide to the panel, the board
issued its warning this year in part because of declining
projections for military spending.
   ``When you have budget constraints, people tend to want to shift
more responsibilities to the reserves to save money,'' Fogel said
Thursday.
   ``The board is saying you've got to have a sufficient
active-duty force, and that you can't shift like that without
providing the necessary resources, money, spaces in schools, etc.''
   The board said it thought ``the most suitable missions for the
National Guard and reserves are those with low peace-time activity
levels and high war-time surge requirements.''
   ``If a mission must be performed on a daily basis or requires
daily training, that mission is best suited to the active
component,'' the panel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
