<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirForceFurloughs 350   03-04 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Force Furloughs, 350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Criticize Air Force for Furlough Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force officials have been told by
lawmakers to scour their budget for money that would avert the
temporary furlough of more than 80,000 civilian workers.
   Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, chairman of the House Armed Services
readiness subcommittee, told Air Force Comptroller General Claudius
Watts on Thursday that the Air Force could wring the necessary
funds out of its budget.
   ``If the initiative does not come from the military..., it'll
come from this one member,'' the Massachusetts Democrat said.
``These humane issues _ the quality of life that we take such a
deep interest in _ are not going to be affected.''
   Under the Air Force plan, 82,500 civilian workers in the Air
Force Logistics Command could be furloughed for up to 10 days this
year.
   ``I wish I could guarantee to you that no one would be
furloughed,'' Watts told the subcommittee. ``But I can't.''
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, said the command would only need to
find $167 million out of its total budget of $5 billion to avert
the furloughs.
   ``We're spending $60 million on a club system for our service
people and $13 million to subsidize golf courses,'' said Kasich.
``We can start by cutting out the $13 millon for golf courses. I
think we've got to find the money.''
   The logistics command is responsible for transporting Air Force
supplies as well as repairing and maintaining equipment. It has
about 7,300 workers at its headquarters at Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base near Dayton, Ohio, and another 2,500 at the Newark
(Ohio) Air Force Station.
   In addition to Wright-Patterson and Newark, the logistics
command operates major centers at Ogden, Utah; Sacramento, Calif.,
San Antonio, Texas; Oklahoma City; Warner Robins, Ga.;
Davis-Monthan Air Force Base in Arizona; and Battle Creek, Mich.
   Rep. Jim Hansen, R-Utah, has introduced a bill aimed at averting
the furloughs by increasing from $1.5 billion to $4 billion the
amount of money the Pentagon could transfer from one account to
another.
</TEXT>
