<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SenateArrests     03-04 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senate Arrests,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Debate Arresting Senators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans said they were treated like
``common criminals.''
   The Senate's Democratic leader said the Republicans were merely
``cry-babies'' and should act like adults.
   For five hours Thursday, senators talked about and briefly
debated the legality of the Senate's vote last week to ``arrest
absent senators.''
   At one point, spectators in the Senate gallery may have thought
they had wandered into a courtroom.
   Facing the presiding officer at the bench was Sen. George
Mitchell, D-Maine, drawing on his experience as a former federal
judge to defend the Democrats' vote last week to arrest Republicans
who refused to show up for a quorum call.
   On the other side of the ornate chamber stood Sen. Arlen
Specter, citing his background as a former Philadelphia district
attorney and arguing that senators should enjoy the same
protections against illegal arrest as ``common criminals.''
   That vote resulted in the Senate sergeant-at-arms chasing
senators down corridors and finally entering the locked office of
Sen. Robert Packwood with a team of detectives. The senator was
escorted to the Senate, where he was picked up and carried into the
chamber, feet first.
   Packwood, an Oregon Republican, seemed amused.
   But 17 other Republicans were not, and they spent much of the
day Thursday condemning the whole episode. They introduced a
resolution asking the Rules Committee to tighten procedures by
which senators can be arrested and forced to attend the Senate.
   Specter, R-Pa., charged that ``an arrest is an arrest is an
arrest'' and demanded that in the future, warrants be changed to
``include a written statement establishing the reasons for arrest.''
   The resolution also proposed a rule change that would prohibit
the seizure of an absent senator between 11 p.m. and 8 a.m.
``unless the pending business is of a compelling nature.''
   Through it all sat Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.,
the man who had proposed the rarely-used motion to arrest.
   He said the complaining Republicans were ``cry-babies'' and the
arrest warrant carried no penalties other than requiring senators
to show up for work.
   ``We bored the American people today with almost four hours of
talk about the `tough life' of senators,'' Byrd complained.
   He called the whole debate ``a tale of woe'' and suggested
``there are several million Americans who would be glad to trade
places with us.''
   Byrd singled out the provision that would limit late-night
arrest warrants other than for ``compelling'' reasons. ``Who's to
determine that?'' Byrd asked. ``The Senate determines that and it
determined that the other evening.''
   Packwood was seized in his office at about 1:30 a.m. last
Wednesday when he and most other Republicans fled the chamber to
prevent the Senate from establishing a quorum. A quorum of 51
senators was needed to keep the Senate in session, and the
Republicans were trying to end an all-night debate on a campaign
spending bill.
   Packwood's unique arrival gave the Democrats a quorum and the
Senate remained in session all night.
   Packwood was not a sponsor of the resolution, introduced
Thursday, and referred to the Rules Committee.
   In addition to Specter, sponsors included Sens. Alan Simpson of
Wyoming, John Chafee of Rhode Island, William Armstrong of
Colorado, Rudy Boschwitz of Minnesota, Thad Cochran of Mississippi,
John Heinz of Pennsylvania, Dan Quayle of Indiana, Mitch McConnell
of Kentucky, Kit Bond of Missouri, Dan Evans of Washington, Robert
Kasten of Wisconsin, Alfonse D'Amato of New York, Gordon Humphrey
of New Hampshire, Jake Garn of Utah, John Warner of Virginia and
Malcolm Wallop of Wyoming.
</TEXT>
