<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0439EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoldierofFortune     03-04 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldier of Fortune,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Magazine Was Negligent In Publishing Killer's Ad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $9.4 million damage award to the family of a
woman whose killer was hired through a Soldier of Fortune magazine
classified ad is ``sending out a warning'' to other publishers, the
jury foreman says.
   An attorney for the magazine said it would appeal Thursday's
verdict in favor of Gary Wayne Black, 18, and his grandmother,
Marjorie Eimann, 64, who sought $22.5 million in their lawsuit.
   ``This fight goes three rounds like a lot of First Amendment
cases,'' said Soldier of Fortune attorney Larry Thompson. ``We lost
the first round but put your money on us in the next two rounds.''
   After deliberating for 12 hours over three days, the jury
awarded Black $1.5 million, $400,000 to Mrs. Eimann and $7.5
million in punitive damages to the plaintiffs.
   ``We're sending out a warning or message to other publishers
that ads placed in a certain context can be a very dangerous
message and publishers as such should be responsible,'' said jury
foreman Herman Castex.
   Sandra Black, Black's mother and Mrs. Eimann's daughter, was
shot to death Feb. 21, 1985, at her home in Bryan, about 90 miles
northwest of Houston.
   Mrs. Black's husband, Robert, is on death row for paying John
Wayne Hearn $10,000 to kill her. Hearn is serving three life terms
in Florida for that slaying and two others.
   Robert Black contacted Hearn through a classified ad Hearn
placed in late 1984 in Soldier of Fortune, the self-styled
``Journal for Professional Adventurers.''
   In a pretrial decision, U.S. District Judge David Hittner ruled
that the Boulder, Colo.-based magazine and parent company Omega
Group Ltd. could not enjoy full First Amendment protection because
of the ad's commercial nature.
   ``This will have no effect on the legitimate press,'' said
plaintiffs' attorney Ron Franklin. ``Soldier of Fortune knew in
fact that it was advertising for contract killers and that offers
no First Amendment protection.''
   Publishing and legal experts were not as certain.
   ``When magazine publishers' advertising people hear a big
verdict based on this kind of ad, they may be more concerned than
necessary to accept controversial advertising,'' said Slade
Metcalf, chairman of legal affairs for the New York-based Magazine
Publishers Association.
   ``These kinds of cases really open the door,'' said David
Protess, a professor at Northwestern University's Medill School of
Journalism in Evanston, Ill. ``There's very little case law on
media negligence. There are almost no precedents.''
   Attorneys said it could take 18 months before the case reaches
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans.
   Mrs. Eimann shook hands and hugged the six jurors after the
verdict. ``I lost a daughter and he lost a mother,'' she said,
looking at her grandson. ``We felt something had to be done to save
other people's lives.''
   Soldier of Fortune publisher Robert K. Brown said the verdict
would not affect the future of his publication, which sells about
150,000 copies monthly.
   ``Please understand this was a terrible tragedy, a terrible
crime,'' he said. ``We have a great deal of empathy for them, but
we didn't do it.''
   ``This means every publisher is going to have to read every ad
and look into the minds of those placing the ad,'' Brown said.
   Hearn's ad in four issues of Soldier of Fortune read: ``Ex
marines. `67-69 Nam vets. Ex-DI, weapons specialist _ jungle
warfare. Pilot. ME. High-risk assignments. U.S. or overseas.''
   Attorneys and witnesses for the family said ``high-risk
assignments'' meant Hearn and others placing similar ads were
willing to commit crimes.
   Soldier of Fortune witnesses defended the publication as a
legitimate military journal and described the ads as providing
employment for Vietnam veterans as bodyguards, security workers or
mercenaries overseas.
   But the family's lawyers linked at least nine other crimes to
ads before September 1984, including a 1982 Houston murder-for-hire
case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0439EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSCommission     03-04 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Commission,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Commission Backs Additional $2 Billion for Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A White House commission has adopted its
chairman's recommendation to pour an additional $2 billion a year
into the the fight against AIDS.
   The panel unanimously approved retired Navy Adm. James D.
Watkins' 60 pages of suggestions Thursday night during a brief
business meeting that wrapped up four full days of hearings on a
variety of topics _ such as testing and protection against
discrimination _ that are to be addressed in subsequent reports.
   Watkins had outlined his recommendations at a news conference
last week and they were formally considered by the full commission
on Monday.
   The final version contained no substantive changes although
there were some additions to emphasize particular areas of concern.
   For example, a paragraph was added to emphasize ``that available
data do not provide a basis for comfort or complacency to any
segment of our society. ... We express our concern that inaccurate
and misleading statements suggesting that (the virus) cannot be
spread through heterosexual activity could stimulate transmission
among those who would see such reports as bases for ignoring the
danger that does, in fact, exist.''
   In a section on drug abuse, a sentence added to say: ``In
addition to direct transmission, the use of drugs that impair
judgment can contribute to sexual transmission.''
   That had been suggested by Commissioner Theresa L. Crenshaw, a
physician who specializes in sex therapy and has expressed the view
that alcohol, marijuana and other drugs can lower inhibitions and
result in people engaging in risky sexual behavior that they
otherwise would avoid.
   The bulk of the increased spending called for in the report _
about $1.5 billion a year in federal and local funds _ would go
directly to attacking intravenous drug abuse. The rest, all federal
funds, would go for development of drugs to treat the disease and
additional ways of caring for AIDS patients, such as more group
homes for those who do not require constant hospitalization yet are
unable to care for themselves.
   ``The recommendations are geared toward the establishment of a
`treatment on demand' system for IV drug abusers, whereby treatment
would be immediately available for any IV drug abuser,'' the report
said.
   Health authorities are convinced AIDS is spreading most rapidly
among IV drug users _ who often pass the virus by sharing
contaminated needles _ and their sexual partners and offspring.
   It is estimated that there could be as many as 20,000 babies
infected with AIDS by 1991, most of them catching it directly or
indirectly from the estimated 1.3 million IV drug users in the
nation.
   The other two sections of the report focus on patient care and
basic research for drug development to treat the disease.
   The commission recommends expanding resources for the Food and
Drug Administration, expanding community based clinical trials and
``removing placebos in clinical trials whenever possible.''
   The section on patient care says the aim is ``to promote a
continuum of comprehensive, accessible, cost-effective high quality
care for persons infected with HIV.'' HIV is the medical term for
the AIDS virus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0648EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TripleHit-and-Run     03-04 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Triple Hit-and-Run,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hit-and-Run Driver Kills Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MCLEAN, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three young men standing on the side of a
road were killed and a fourth injured when they were hit by a
passing van that then fled the scene, authorities said.
   Fairfax County Police spokesman Walter Carmichael said the
accident occurred about 10 p.m. Thursday in a suburb of Washington,
D.C., as the victims were attempting to change a tire on the car in
which they had been riding.
   Witnesses told police that a white van struck the youths as it
passed their car, knocking them between 25 and 50 feet, Carmichael
said. The three were pronounced dead on the scene, while the fourth
victim was rushed to Fairfax Hospital, where his condition was not
immediately available.
   Names and ages of the victims were not released, although
Carmichael said all three appeared to be in their late teens or
early 20s.
   An all-points bulletin was issued for the van, but Carmichael
said witnesses provided little more information than its color.
</TEXT>
