<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBI-Surveillance     03-04 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Surveillance,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Conduct Called McCarthy-like in Domestic Spy Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel chairman investigating FBI
conduct says a bureau official used McCarthy-like tactics when he
disclosed unproven allegations against an anti-Reagan organization.
   In a floor speech Thursday night, Rep. Don Edwards, chairman of
a House Judiciary civil rights subcommittee, likened the disclosure
to misuse of FBI files by the late Sen. Joseph McCarthy in the
early 1950s.
   McCarthy used ``investigatory information from the FBI'' to
label government officials as communists without proving the
allegations, Edwards said.
   Edwards' panel and the Senate Intelligence Committee are
investigating the FBI's March 1983-June 1985 probe of opponents of
President Reagan's Central America policy. The lawmakers want to
know whether the bureau improperly investigated political activity
protected by the First Amendment.
   The intelligence panel held a public hearing Feb. 23, at which
FBI Executive Assistant Director Oliver B. Revell sought to justify
the bureau's investigation. The probe focused primarily on the
Committee In Solidarity with the People of El Salvador, but it
broadened to include a number of other groups and individuals.
   Revell released a report that detailed some of the allegations
against CISPES, none of which were proved by the FBI.
   ``During the McCarthy era, it was a common practice of the FBI
to secretly disclose investigative, file information to
congressional committees,'' Edwards, D-Calif., said.
   ``If the FBI responds to criticism by doing publicly, before TV
cameras, what it once did privately, then we have not come very far
at all,'' he said.
   FBI spokeswoman Sue Schnitzer said: ``Mr. Revell testified at
the request of the committee. This was an open hearing and
therefore the information provided at that hearing was not of a
classified nature.''
   Edwards said he was not trying to prove or disprove the
information, but said the allegations amounted to ``guilt by
association'' since no charges were ever filed against CISPES or
its members.
   Some of the information released at the hearing was made public
previously under a Freedom of Information Act lawsuit filed on
behalf of CISPES. Other information disclosed at the hearing had
not been made public before.
   Edwards called Revell's disclosure of ``unsupported
allegations'' at a public hearing ``a major violation of the key
rule for police investigatory files _ that none of the information
can be published except according to established rules and
safeguards.''
   ``Improper release of file information by the government ... is
a violation of the constitutional and statutory right of privacy
and can cause grave injury to innocent people or groups,'' Edwards
said.
   Among the allegations that Edwards said should not have been
released:
   _Claims that some CISPES members were ``involved in the
distribution'' of a Soviet-forged document to the media.
   _A statement that CISPES was ``believed to have been established
with assistance of'' the Communist Party of the USA.
   _Linking CISPES' political support of the Salvadoran guerrilla
group FMLN to terrorist actions by that organization, suggesting,
according to Edwards, that ``CISPES was somehow connected with
these actions.''
   _A possible connection between CISPES and two bombings in
Washington, because one took place ``about the same time'' of a
CISPES rally in the capital; and responsibility for the second was
claimed by a group with positions ``similar'' to those of CISPES.
   The FBI never brought any charges against CISPES or its members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
