<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices inched up in trading today on optimism
about Japan's economy, while the U.S. dollar dipped slightly as
traders awaited market-affecting news.
   The dollar closed at 129.22, down 0.08 yen from Thursday's
close. The dollar opened at 129.16 yen, and ranged between 129.16
and 129.30 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average index of
225 selected issues finished the day at 25,615.62 points, up 19.31
points, or 0.07 percent, from Thursday's close of 25,596.31 points.
   ``The market is strong,'' said Yoshio Ogawa of Nikko Securities.
``There aren't any real factors today, but the market is still
looking good for the same reasons as late last month _ Japan's
economic fundamentals look good, and that is affecting trading.''
   ``There were no important trends today, with the market holding
fairly steady,'' said an analyst who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``But trading was very active.''
   Although volume was a heavy 1.3 billion shares in the first
section, share prices closed mixed, with pharmaceuticals up and
banks and other financials lower, according to dealers.
   The U.S. currency topped the 129-yen barrier in active trading
Thursday, but the market failed to gain momentum due to the lack of
new incentives, said a currency dealer with a major commercial bank
in Tokyo.
   ``This was the kind of day that is very hard to comment on,''
said a foreign exchange analyst who requested anonymity. ``Very
little happened.''
</TEXT>
