<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-PrizeWinner     03-04 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Prize Winner,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prize-Winner Besieged by Pleas for Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A factory director whose labor-efficiency plans
won him a $2,700 prize has decided to give up the money because of
the lingering stigma against wealth and a deluge of request for
handouts, a newspaper said today.
   The prize, 10,000 yuan, is a huge sum for most Chinese, equal to
10 years' wages for the average urban worker and double that for a
typical peasant.
   Zhang Xingrang, director of the No. 1 Plastic Factory in the
eastern city of Shijiazhuang, decided not to keep the money after
being besieged with petitions for loans, the state-run Workers'
Daily said.
   The paper said he was receiving dozens of letters each day from
strangers wanting to share in his new wealth, with friends and
co-workers adding to the chorus.
   Zhang won the prize for developing what he called a ``full-load
work plan'' for allocating labor more efficiently at his factory.
He became a nationally famous labor hero, winning praise from
Communist Party leader Zhao Ziyang.
   The Workers' Daily said colleagues told Zhang, ``Old Zhang, now
that you're rich don't forget we helped you. You can eat meat now,
a little soup or some bones is enough for us.''
   One letter-writer pleaded for 375 yuan to buy a three-wheeled
pedicab so he could take his children _ including 9-year-old
triplets _ to school.
   ``Take pity on these children,'' he pleaded, addressing Zhang as
``the god of wealth.''
   Another writer said he needed 2,000 yuan to get out of
``financial straits,'' adding, ``This amount is nothing to you.''
   The paper said Zhang feared criticism that has been heaped on
other factory directors who have become rich in recent years
because of incentives and profit-sharing programs designed to spur
production.
   He put the money in a bank and is busy trying to devise a
give-away plan that will satisfy most people, the paper said.
   Zhao declared last October that China is in the ``primary stage
of socialism'' and that it is permissible in this stage for some
individuals to become rich while others lag behind.
   Egalitarianism was the rule for most of China's first four
decades under communism. In recent years, the Chinese government
has relaxed many of its economic policies, allowing for free
enterprise. But many of the new rich have been criticized and even
hit with criminal charges for acquiring large amounts of money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
