<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     03-04 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ms. Magazine Opens Washington News Bureau</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ms. magazine will be opening a news bureau in
Washington and veteran political reporter Peggy Simpson has been
appointed bureau chief.
   ``Ms. intends to become a force in Washington,'' said
editor-in-chief Anne Summers. ``We aim to become an authoritative
voice in national political affairs on behalf of women. We will be
non-partisan, but will express our views forthrightly.''
   Simpson ``combines the special qualities we were looking for _
solid experience of political and economic reporting, with a
special sensitivity to how these impact on women,'' said Summers.
   Simpson, has covered national politics since the early 1970s,
first for The Associated Press and since 1982 for Hearst
Newspapers. She has covered every national political convention
since 1972.
   Ms., one of the first magazines focusing on political issues
involving women, was acquired late last year by Fairfax
Publications Ltd., a major Australian publisher.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Dept. Denies Visa to President of Sinn Fein</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has violated ``the spirit
and letter'' of a new law by denying a visa to the head of the
legal political wing of the Irish Republican Army, says a New
York-based group advocating the end of British rule in Northern
Ireland.
   Gerry Adams, president of the IRA's Sinn Fein, was denied a visa
because of his alleged involvement in terrorist activities in
Northern Ireland, Donna Sherman, a State Department spokeswoman,
said Thursday.
   ``He was ineligible under (the section) of the Immigration and
Nationality Act which excludes from admission to the U.S. people
who are personally involved with terrorist activities,'' Sherman
said.
   But Martin Galvin, spokesman for the Irish Northern Aid
Committee in New York, said in a statement, ``Irish-Americans are
outraged by the refusal of the State Department to comply with the
spirit and letter of the new visa provisions.''
   He was referring to an amendment to an appropriations bill,
passed last year, which in effect overturned that portion of
immigration law allowing the U.S. government to deny visas to
aliens who participate in political activities in their native
countries which would be legal for U.S. citizens in the United
States.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
is outlawed on both sides of the border, although Sinn Fein is
legal.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>USAir Orders 50 Boeing 737s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir says it has agreed to buy 50 Boeing 737
jetliners with options for 30 additional aircraft, a deal worth
$2.4 billion if all the options are exercised.
   Delivery of the new jets will begin in April 1989 and continue
through December 1991, the airline said.
   The twin-engine, short-to-medium range aircraft is the most
popular jet ever sold by the Seattle-based Boeing Co. The deal with
USAir brings to 2,001 Boeing 737s on order.
   Edwin Colodny, USAir chairman and president, said the order ``is
indicative of the health and vitality'' of the airline, which has
its headquarters at Washington National Airport.
   ``Our track record makes it possible to order these new aircraft
which will benefit our passengers and the communities we serve,''
Colodny said in a statement.
   USAir Group, the holding company for USAir as well as Piedmont
Aviation and Pacific Southwest Airlines, recently reported a 1987
net income of $194.6 million on revenue of $3 billion.
</TEXT>
