<1ST_LINE>r p PM-RobertsonRevelation 1stLd-Writethru   03-04 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson Revelation, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0517,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Said He Was `Called by God' to Usher Second Coming</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 1st graf, bgng ``Republican presidential ...'' to change
Friday to today.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential hopeful Pat Robertson
said God had spoken to him, calling him to usher in the second
coming of Jesus Christ, a newspaper reported today.
   In a tape of a December 1984 address to a religious seminar in
Dallas, Robertson said Christ's return is imminent and would be
accompanied by Christians ``taking dominion'' over the wealth and
property of non-believers, the Los Angeles Times reported.
   In a reference to Dallas' downtown office buildings, Robertson
said: ``Imagine the time the people of God have inherited that
property, because the Bible says that the wicked lay up and heap up
treasures for the righteous.''
   In the 1984 tape, Robertson said God had told him ``I have
called you to usher in the coming of my Son.'' He also briefly
speaks in tongues, a form of unrecognizable language uttered by
those who practice charismatic Christianity, during his closing
prayer.
   Robertson has said he received the prophecy in 1968 through
Harald Bredesen, a close associate who laid his hand on Robertson's
head and spoke as if God were speaking through him.
   However, when questioned about the prophecy, both Bredesen and
Robertson characterized it as applying to Robertson's ministry, the
Christian Broadcasting Network. Robertson resigned from CBN before
undertaking his presidential campaign.
   Bredesen said, ``We would all be appalled and Pat would be
appalled,'' at the prospects that Robertson's remarks would be
construed to mean that God's words applied to him personally.
   Asked Thursday to comment about the 1968 prophecy, Robertson
said Bredesen ``may have been referring to Middle East
television,'' and predicted Robertson's role in ``spreading the
gospel thoughout the Middle East'' via CBN's transmitter in Lebanon.
   However, in an April 1982 letter to CBN contributors, Robertson
quoted the Bredesen prophecy and said God has assigned a ministry
to CBN ``to prepare the way for the second coming.''
   Robertson has rebuked reporters for referring to him as a former
television evangelist. He insists on being evaluated on the basis
of his record as a businessman, educator and founder of the
multimillion-dollar Christian Broadcasting Network.
   Robertson contends that examinations of his religious beliefs in
the context of his presidential campaign constitute bigotry. And he
maintains that his fervent evangelical beliefs would not interfere
with his execution of presidential power.
</TEXT>
