<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CopKilled     03-04 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cop Killed,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Two in Policeman's Slaying</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: News conference scheduled for 11 a.m. EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested two men in the slaying of a
rookie patrolman who was shot in the head as he guarded a drug
witness last week, a spokesman said today.
   The suspects were picked up Thursday afternoon in the borough of
Queens and questioned for about six hours before their arrest
around midnight, said Officer Peter O'Donnell.
   Two women picked up with the men were released, O'Donnell said.
   The suspects' names, the charges and other details will not be
released until a news conference today, O'Donnell said.
   Officer Edward Byrne, 22, was shot three times in the head at
point-blank range early Feb. 26 while sitting alone in a patrol car
outside the Queens house of a man who had complained to police
about neighborhood crack dealers.
   The Daily News and New York Times, quoting unidentified sources,
said one of the four picked up was 24-year-old Todd Scott of
Queens. The newspapers said Scott works for Howard ``Pappy'' Mason,
an associate of reputed drug kingpin Lorenzo ``Fat Cat'' Nichols.
   Nichols, 29, was sentenced Feb. 25 to 25 years to life in prison
on drug and gun charges, and is awaiting trial on charges he had
his parole officer killed for revenge. Mason is awaiting trial on
charges he helped carry out the killing.
   Police have speculated that Nichols may have ordered Byrne's
killing as retribution for his long sentence.
   Since the slaying, police have rounded up 294 suspected drug
dealers in their investigation.
   ``Shooting at cops, it's just bad for business. I think
experienced criminals know that; perhaps these inexperienced ones
will learn it,'' Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said Thursday.
   ``The community has been very helpful,'' Ward said.
   The reward for information leading to a conviction grew to
$130,000 Thursday with a $25,000 contribution from members of the
New York Stock Exchange.
   WNBC-TV reported Wednesday night that investigators had
identified two men, including the gunman, and two women believed to
have been in the car that quietly coasted up to Byrne's police car
before he was shot.
   WNBC-TV said police believe the women accompanied the men so it
would look like they were out on a date if stopped. Police declined
to comment on the report.
</TEXT>
