<HEAD>Lott Reports Spending $250,275 Despite Having No Republican
Opponent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Trent Lott, R-Miss., who has no
Republican opponent in his bid for a U.S. Senate seat, reports he
has spent $250,275 in campaigning this year.
   Lott's opponent in November will be decided in next Tuesday's
Democratic primary between Rep. Wayne Dowdy, D-Miss., Secretary of
State Dick Molpus and Biloxi pipe fitter Gilbert Fountain.
   Despite the absence of a challenge for the GOP nomination to
succeed the retiring Sen. John C. Stennis, D-Miss., the Lott
campaign since January has employed an expensive series of TV
commercials telling Mississippians about his accomplishments during
his 16 years in Congress.
   Campaign finance reports on Wednesday show Lott, from Jan. 1 to
Feb. 17, had raised $118,839 and spent $250,275.
   The reports also show Lott had $599,250 in cash on hand at the
end of 1987. With the new funds coming in this year, it boosts his
campaign receipts to $718,090.
