<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CondorEgg     03-04 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Condor Egg,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Condor Egg Breeds Hope For Species</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first egg produced by a pair of captive
California condors is a huge success for biologists trying to save
the endangered species, even if it proves to be infertile, a
curator says.
   The egg, laid Thursday at San Diego Wild Animal Park, will be
inspected for fertility Monday, officials said.
   ``If it's not fertile, we would still remain happy,'' said Bill
Toone curator of birds for the San Diego Zoo, which is affiliated
with the park. ``We (now) know they will breed in captivity.''
   Only 27 of the giant birds exist, all in captivity at the park
or the Los Angeles Zoo.
   The 10-ounce, pale blue-green egg was moved from a nest to an
electronic incubator, said park spokesman Tom Hanscom. If fertile,
the egg is expected to hatch within two months.
   The egg may be infertile because the female is old and her mate
may be sexually immature, park officials said.
   By taking the egg from its parents at an early point, scientists
hope to induce the pair to produce a second egg to replace the one
they lost.
   The incubator will maintain a constant temperature and humidity
for the egg. Handlers will turn it 180 degrees twice a day,
imitating the behavior of a mother condor's care in the wild.
   California condors, which have a wingspan of about 9 feet, are
dark reddish-brown, with a curved beak. They were decimated in the
wild by lead poisoning from eating lead shot in animal carcasses,
biologists said.
   The last one living in the wild was captured and brought to the
Wild Animal Park last April in the effort to save the species.
   Since 1981, scientists have successfully hatched 13 condors in
captivity from eggs taken in the wild.
   Wildlife biologists hope to breed sufficient numbers of the
condor in captivity and release the captive-bred birds into a safe
environment in the wild.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
