<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-04 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ice Storm In Ohio Valley, Showers In South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm coated parts of the Midwest with ice and snow, while
rain fell in much of the South and sections of the West Coast. Snow
also fell in the nation's central region.
   Freezing rain was reported across central Indiana into central
Ohio late Thursday. Overpasses and bridges in Indiana were covered
by up to 2 inches of ice, resulting in numerous accidents and power
outages.
   A half-inch of ice was reported in Ohio, where slippery roads
were blamed for at least four highway fatalities.
   Three to 8 inches of new snow was reported across parts of
northern Indiana and northern Ohio, including 6 inches at Peru,
Ind., and Findlay, Ohio.
   Snow also fell from Pennsylvania and much of New York into
central parts of New England. One to 3 inches was reported late
Thursday across parts of northern Pennsylvania, with up to 6 inches
expected.
   Up to 3 inches of snow was reported at Binghamton, N.Y., late
Thursday, and up to 6 inches was expected in central New York by
the time the storm ended today.
   Showers and thunderstorms dampened the Mississippi and Tennessee
valleys through the Gulf Coast into northern Florida. Heavy rain,
small hail and gusty winds accompanied the storms across the South.
   More than 3{ inches of rain was reported in the 24 hours ending
at about 2 a.m. at Tallahassee, Fla., and nearly 3 inches at New
Orleans.
   Snow developed late Thursday across southeast Kansas, southwest
Missouri, northeast Oklahoma and northwest Arkansas. Nearly an inch
fell early today at Monett, Mo., and 1 to 3 inches was reported
across southeast Kansas late Thursday.
   Light rain was scattered across eastern Montana along a
stationary front that reached from southern Alberta into the
northern High Plains. Snow was falling across parts of
north-central Wyoming.
   A frontal system off the Pacific Coast brought scattered
rainshowers along the coast of Oregon and northwest California.
   For today, snow was forecast from northern and western
Pennsylvania across New York and New England; scattered rain or
snow across southeast Missouri, southern Illinois, and northern
sections of the Ohio Valley; rain from Kentucky and Tennessee
through the middle Atlantic Coast region, with showers and
thunderstorms likely over northern Florida, Alabama, Georgia and
the Carolinas; scattered rain or snow showers across the northern
high Plains; snowshowers widely scattered over the mountains of
Wyoming and Colorado; and rain across the Pacific Northwest.
   Much of the nation will have highs in the 40s or 50s. Highs will
be in the 20s and 30s from the Dakotas through the Great Lakes and
New England; in the 30s in the middle Mississippi Valley and
northern sections of the Ohio Valley; the 60s and 70s from
California across the desert Southwest, and from southern and
central Texas to the southern half of the Atlantic Coast; and about
80 over southern and central Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 6 below
zero at Marquette, Mich., to 74 at Miami.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 58 rain; Boston 34 drizzle; Buffalo 27 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 60 showery; Cincinnati 31 foggy; Cleveland 25
snow; Detroit 21 partly cloudy; Miami 73 partly cloudy; New York 42
foggy; Philadelphia 43 foggy; Pittsburgh 32 rain; Portland, Maine
29 snow; Washington 44 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck, N.D. 24 fair; Chicago 26 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 36 fair; Denver 33 fair; Des Moines 20 fair;
Indianapolis 28 cloudy; Kansas City 25 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul
19 fair; Nashville 60 showery; New Orleans 65 foggy; St. Louis 28
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 35 fair; Anchorage 34 cloudy; Las Vegas 55
cloudy; Los Angeles 58 cloudy; Phoenix 57 fair; Salt Lake City 47
partly cloudy; San Diego 57 cloudy; San Francisco 51 partly cloudy;
Seattle 40 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 10 fair; Toronto 16 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
