<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CigaretteSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0542 03-04 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigarette Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0542,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoker So Addicted She Consumed A Pack While in Labor, Witness
Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf with 2 grafs to fix garble.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rose Cipollone was so hooked on cigarettes
that she smoked a pack while in labor with her first child, even
though she had tried to quit, an addiction expert testified in
support of her family's liability suit.
   Dr. Jerome Jaffe cited several instances on the stand Thursday
to show that Mrs. Cipollone was so dependent on cigarettes that
smoking governed her behavior until her death of lung cancer at age
40.
   He depicted a smoker who picked butts from the garbage, ordered
groceries just to have cigarettes delivered and puffed away even
after part of her lung had been removed.
   Mrs. Cipollone became a vivid presence for the first time during
the five-week federal court trial. After her death in 1984, her
widower, Antonio of Lakehurst, carried on the suit against three
tobacco companies.
   The defendants _ Philip Morris Co., Lorillard Inc. and Liggett
Group Inc. _ deny they are responsible for her death. One of their
arguments is that Mrs. Cipollone smoked of her own free will.
   Jaffe, a clinical psychiatrist and director of the National
Institute of Drug Abuse's research center in Baltimore, described
what he learned about Mrs. Cipollone's smoking habits during a
75-minute interview at her lawyer's office months before she died.
   ``She was dependent, and I thought heavily dependent, on tobacco
and cigarettes,'' Jaffe said.
   Under cross-examination by Liggett lawyer James V. Kearney,
Jaffe acknowledged that he did not examine Mrs. Cipollone
physically and never saw her smoke.
   Until now, testimony in the case has centered on allegations
that the companies failed to do enough research on the health
effects of smoking, tell the public what they did know or put a
safer product on the market.
   As the focus shifted to Mrs. Cipollone, Jaffe related that when
she was in labor with her first child in 1947, she was asked by
doctors what she wanted. Her answer was a glass of water and _
despite having nearly quit during her pregnancy _ a cigarette. The
doctors brought her a pack.
   ``She said, `I smoked a whole pack before the baby was born,'''
according to Jaffe, who referred to his notes of the interview
while being questioned by Marc Z. Edell, an attorney for her estate.
   In 1964, when the surgeon general's report linking smoking and
disease came out, Mrs. Cipollone consciously tried to ignore it.
   ``It's typical,'' Jaffe said. ``It's the heart of most
dependences. ... Denial is the cardinal symbol.''
   In 1981, when a spot was found on her lung, Mrs. Cipollone threw
away her cigarettes. But Jaffe recalled her saying ``I was smoking
when I went into the hospital'' for a lung operation.
   She continued to smoke after the operation, he said, stopping
the following year when her right lung was removed.
   Jaffe also served as a special consultant to the president for
narcotics and dangerous drugs from 1971 to 1973.
</TEXT>
