<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lepers-Mariel     03-04 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lepers-Mariel,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Exile Leaders Say Lepers Were Forced To Join Mariel Boatlift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cuban government forced some lepers to join the
1980 exodus for the United States from the Port of Mariel, Cuban
exile leaders claim.
   The charges came during a campaign by Cuban exile groups seeking
to have their homeland's Communist government declared in violation
of human rights.
   The exile leaders say expelling the lepers against their will
violates their rights, and they hope to bring up the matter before
the Commission on Human Rights meeting now in Geneva.
   ``Castro did not show any respect for the human rights of lepers
or for the American people,'' said Jorge Mas Canosa, head of the
Cuban American National Foundation.
   About 30 of the patients being treated in Miami for leprosy, or
Hansen's Disease, arrived during the 1980 boatlift, which brought
about 125,000 refugees to the United States.
   A leper now living in Louisiana said he was forced onto a
Florida-bound vessel on May 3, 1980.
   ``They said `You go or we will put you in prison,''' Jose
Antonio Perez Ortiz, 41, said in an interview taped last week. ``I
could not work. I said `Send me there.'''
   Angel Pino, spokesman for the Cuban Intrests Section in
Washington, denied the charge, saying all who left Cuba did so
voluntarily.
</TEXT>
