<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Paramedic-Mom     03-04 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Paramedic-Mom,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paramedic Gets The Call, Saves Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramedic Michael Flaherty jumped into his
emergency vehicle and recognized the address: One of his parents
was in trouble.
   ``If you walk in and see your mother on the floor, you react,''
Flaherty said. ``I gave her mount-to-mouth ventilation. Everything
worked.''
   His parents were having breakfast Wednesday when his mother,
Theresa, 65, collapsed about 8:45 a.m.
   ``When I heard the address, I could have run there faster than
the ambulance, if that had been necessary,'' Flaherty said.
``Nobody was going to beat us to that address.''
   Flaherty's father, Peter, who is not trained in cardiopulmonary
resuscitation, applied chest compressions before the younger
Flaherty and his partner, Jake Willens, arrived.
   Mrs. Flaherty was rushed to St. Francis Hospital in Evanston
where she was in fair condition, apparently suffering from
inadequate blood supply to her heart.
   Chief Fire Department Paramedic Ronald Smith praised Flaherty's
actions. ``He saved his mother's life. He brought her back,'' Smith
said.
   ``I didn't know if it was a heart attack or respiratory
arrest,'' Flaherty said. ``No paramedic or firefighter wants to
resuscitate or work on his own parents or children or friends.
   ``But when something happens and you have to do it, you react,''
he said.
</TEXT>
