<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0643EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     03-04 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Block Demonstration, Four Rebels Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian troops prevented Tamil students
from holding demonstrations they called for today, warning people
that they would be shot if they gathered, reports from the region
said.
   Sri Lankan military officials said four Tamil rebels were killed
Thursday in a shootout with Indian troops in a village near the
northern town of Jaffna.
   The officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said the rebels were killed after they attacked an Indian patrol.
They said one Indian soldier was badly wounded.
   India has about 45,000 soldiers in Sri Lanka to enforce an
Indian-sponsored peace accord signed last July to end the Tamil
rebels' four-year separatist insurrection.
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest of the rebel
groups, has rejected the accord. The Tigers have been the focus of
Indian search operations in and around Batticaloa, a town 140 miles
northeast of Colombo.
   Protest marches were called for in Batticaloa by the Eelam
Revolutionary Organization of Students, which has endorsed the
peace accord but alleges Sri Lankan soldiers are violating it
through shootings and arrests. Under the accord, the Sri Lankan
army is to be confined to barracks.
   In telephone interviews, Batticaloa residents said that Indian
troops drove through the town warning civilians they would be shot
if they violated orders prohibiting public gatherings.
   The residents, speaking on condition of anonymity, said no
incidents were reported.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million population. They claim they are discriminated against by
the island's majority Sinhalese Buddhists, who control the
government and military.
   The peace accord signed July 29 calls on the Tamils to lay down
their arms in exchange for more political autonomy in the northern
and eastern regions where they live.
   India has become involved because it has about 60 million ethnic
Tamils in its southern states who are sympathetic to their Sri
Lankan brethern.
</TEXT>
