<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NYCChancellor 1stLd-Writethru a0532 03-04 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NYC Chancellor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0532,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Incoming Chancellor Says He'll Cut School Bureaucracy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS 3rd graf to clarify</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City's new schools chancellor says he
will begin shaping up one of the nation's most troubled school
systems by abolishing time clocks and paring down the bloated
central bureaucracy.
   Richard R. Green's inaugural message, delivered amid
unprecedented pomp and splendor Thursday in the ornate chapel of
Erasmus Hall High School, was that New York City's schools are ``on
trial. Business as usual must come to an end, and it must do so
today.''
   Green left behind a 30-year career in Minneapolis schools to
lead the 939,000-pupil system, the largest in the nation with a
$4.8 billion annual budget.
   Green was ushered into the oak-paneled chapel by six children
wearing sashes reading ``The Class of 2000.'' Greeting him on the
speaker's podium were Gov. Mario M. Cuomo, Mayor Edward I. Koch,
Board of Education president Robert F. Wagner, Jr., and other
dignitaries, all wearing academic robes.
   Frequently departing from a prepared text of a 20-minute
inaugural address, Green took a generally conciliatory tone toward
the many problems and constituencies he faces. But he vowed that
the infamous central bureaucracy would likely face cuts, especially
with Mayor Koch pressuring the board to find $28 million in budget
savings.
   ``I have heard that 110 Livingston Street has been immobilized
by the twin abuses called apathy and cynicism,'' he said. ``This is
a new day.''
   ``By July 1, I will have a management team in place that I can
rely on. And there will be some transfers out of 110 Livingston,''
he said, referring to the Brooklyn headquarters of the city Board
of Education.
   He also vowed to remove the time clocks that teachers are
required to punch. And he said that ``We are going to find a way to
open schools to parents who want to use facilities and I am certain
we can reach a new accommodation with our custodians.''
   Green did not mention his controversial suggestion of an
11-month school year which he made off-the-cuff on Wednesday while
touring several schools.
   United Federation of Teachers president Sandra Feldman called
the 20-minute speech ``an exciting beginning. He was both tough and
caring. I was especially gratified that he singled out the work
done by the city's teachers and the fact that they don't get enough
recognition as professionals.''
   The city's first black chancellor has his work cut out for him.
The system, which has 32 autonomous districts, has a dropout rate
pegged by the School Board at 30.7 percent. An independent panel
put the figure at 50.4 percent.
   Many of the city's 1,050 school buildings are deteriorating, and
an estimated 25 percent have serious problems.
   Green's staff of 61,000 teachers exceeds the number of students
in the Minneapolis system, yet officials expect the city will need
40,000 new teachers by 1994.
</TEXT>
