<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Contras-Reax     03-04 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras-Reax,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Contra Aid, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Contras: House Aid Rejection Puts Us On The Defensive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newest House rejection of aid for the
Nicaraguan Contras has put the rebels on the defensive as they near
face-to-face peace talks with the Sandinista government, a Contra
spokeswoman says.
   The House rejected a $30 million humanitarian aid package
Thursday night, only hours after Contra leaders agreed to meet the
Sandinistas inside Nicaragua without a mediator.
   ``Every time the United States turns its back on the Contras, it
puts us in a less favorable position,'' said Contra spokeswoman
Marta Sacasa. The Sandinistas ``will become even more intransigent
and more hard line.''
   The failed bill had limited the use of the funds to food,
clothing and medical supplies and a plan to help young war victims.
The 216-210 vote against the package meant the rebels, whose last
U.S. aid ran out Tuesday, would be left without new supplies unless
Congress passes another measure.
   ``We of course wanted a positive vote, but the death or survival
of the Nicaraguan Resistance is not tied to the U.S. Congress,''
Ms. Sacasa said. ``We have adapted and we will continue to adapt.''
   She said this setback, coupled with a Feb. 3 House rejection of
a $36.2 million aid package proposed by President Reagan, makes it
clear the Contras cannot count on the United States.
   ``We are fighting against an enemy that doesn't have these kinds
of problems. The aid from the Soviet Union has not stopped flowing
to the Sandinistas,'' she said.
   While a date for the peace conference has not been set, the
Contras on Thursday accepted in principle an offer of face-to-face
talks made by Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega.
   But the Contras insisted in a communique that Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo of Managua, who was dismissed by Ortega as a
mediator after two previous negotiating sessions, be present as a
``witness and guarantor.''
   Ortega has proposed that the talks take place in southern
Nicaragua with his brother, Defense Minister Humberto Ortega,
heading the government delegation.
   The Contras appointed Adolfo Calero, considered to be one of the
more hardline directors, to head their delegation.
   ``We are accepting a face-to-face meeting in Nicaraguan
territory,'' director Alfredo Cesar said after a daylong meeting of
the directorate.
   Ortega had suggested that the meeting be held in the town of
Sapoa near Nicaragua's Costa Rican border on March 10-12, but Cesar
said the time and place should be worked out later.
   The communique signed by the five directors of the Nicaraguan
Resistance, as the Contra rebels are formally called, lambasted
Ortega for dismissing Obando y Bravo as a mediator.
   It called the action ``unilateral and dictatorial,'' and praised
the cardinal for his help in pushing the peace talks.
</TEXT>
