<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-04 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Kate Reed ambled into her
bathroom early one morning and flipped on the light, she found she
didn't need a cold shower to wake up _ there sat a 6{-foot long boa
constrictor on her toilet seat.
   She went back to her husband, Rob, and calmly said, ``Honey,
please wake up. There's a snake in the bathroom.
   ``He sat bolt upright in bed and said, `What?'''
   Meanwhile, their dog, Tootsie, slept calmly on the bathmat.
   The snake escaped Jan. 28 from upstairs neighbor Brian Wycoskie,
who, after a call from Rob Reed, came downstairs to retrieve his
wayward pet, named Cleopatra.
   Wycoskie said he hadn't told the Reeds about the escape because
he thought someone had stolen it.
   Cleopatra apparently slithered down Wycoskie's toilet on
Thursday and picked the wrong pipe to return home.
   ``I found out they're a water animal,'' said Wycoskie, who also
owns Connie the Florida cottonmouth rattlesnake, Hercules the
tarantula, Sting the scorpion, Vince the black widow spider and
tropical gecko lizards named Abbott and Costello.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM BAY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caught in rush-hour traffic with his wife
in labor, Ray Snyder stopped at a convenience store to call for
help _ but left with a baby boy born in the back of his pickup
truck.
   ``It happened in five minutes, but it seemed like a lifetime,''
said Debbie Spivey, a schoolteacher who stopped at the store to buy
a soda but wound up helping to deliver the 8-pound, 9{-ounce baby
Thursday.
   Mrs. Snyder and son were doing fine at Holmes Regional Medical
Center in nearby Melbourne in east central Florida.
   She said she hopes her next child is born in a hospital. ``You
don't ever want to have a baby in a pickup truck,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old girl who earned $500 by going
without television for a year says she doubts she'll revert to
heavy TV watching, even though she's now free to do so.
   ``I think I'm going to continue on doing my homework first,''
Jenny Machalleck said Thursday after watching her first television
program since March 2, 1987.
   ``I'm really happy with how my grades have come out,'' she said.
``They weren't bad before, but now they're at the head of the
class.''
   Earlier in the day, she received the $500 check her parents had
promised if she could go a full year without TV. They made the deal
to cure her of her six-hour-a-day addiction to the tube.
   But Jenny said she was too busy doing homework Thursday night to
celebrate by watching the show she had wanted to, ``Cosby.''
   She said she finished in time to watch the last half of
``Cheers.''
   Her first TV viewing in year was fun, she said, ``because I
hadn't watched in so long. But I found I hadn't really been missing
anything. I was just not as enthusiastic as I thought I would be.''
</TEXT>
