<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CollegeRacism     03-04 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-College Racism,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Student Activist Receives Threatening Letter; Fraternity
Closed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE L. BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Pennsylvania fraternity that
sponsored a strip show in which white students jeered black dancers
has been ordered to close for 1{ years, and a black student
activist received a death threat he believes stemmed from a protest
of the incident.
   Blacks and feminists at Penn have complained bitterly during the
past few weeks about the rush party at the all-white fraternity.
During the party last September, two black women stripped,
performed sexually explicit acts and danced naked before an
audience that shouted racial epithets, according to the university.
   The school on Thursday ordered the 112-member Zeta Beta Tau to
close for at least 1{ years because of the incident, the fraternity
said.
   ZBT President Zane Brown, in a statement, apologized for the
incident but said the decision by the Penn judicial board was
``unjust.''
   The death threat was made earlier this week against Conrad
Tillard, director of the Organization of Black Consciousness, in a
letter sent to a reporter at Penn's student newspaper, the Daily
Pennsylvanian.
   The writer claimed to be a student member of the Jewish Defense
League, but school officials did not believe the claim, and the JDL
denied any connection with the threat. The fraternity that was
ordered closed is primarily Jewish.
   ``The main thing it said was that I was a target on their hit
list,'' Tillard said. ``It also said that in general they're trying
to stop the rise of this black power group that I'm helping bring
about.''
   Tillard will receive around-the-clock protection by campus
police that will continue ``as long as is necessary,'' said
security spokeswoman Sylvia Canada. Philadelphia police said they
were investigating the letter; the FBI also acknowledged receiving
a copy but declined to comment.
   Tillard said he believed the letter stemmed from a rally Monday
sponsored by his group, which called on the school to oust ZBT.
However, the letter did not mention the fraternity incident,
Tillard said.
   Black officials said the fraternity incident and the death
threat reflect growing racial tension not only at the Ivy League
campus but at colleges around the country.
   ``What is happening now, in terms of the real tensions on
campus, is just the tip of the iceberg,'' said Jacqueline Wade,
director of Penn's Afro-American Students Department. ``I think
we're going to see across the nation something that's very
reminiscent of the '60s.''
   ``Racism never left the university environment,'' she said.
   Meanwhile, at Dartmouth College in Hanover, N.H., about 300
people rallied Thursday to protest bigotry. The day before, police
guarded the offices of a conservative weekly campus newspaper that
revived stinging attacks on a black professor and reawakened
charges of racism at the school.
   Rabbi Howard Alperg, director of Penn's Jewish Campus Activities
Board, said ``black radicals'' are trying to turn the fraternity
controversy into a black-Jewish issue.
   But Daniel Gamulka, chairman of the Jewish Student Council, said
the fraternity incident enraged both white and black students.
   ``The Jewish community does not support what happened at ZBT,''
said Gamulka. ``They find it offensive, just as anyone would.''
   Relationships between black and Jewish Penn students have been
strained since a verbal confrontation between the groups in 1986,
when the Black Student Unity Conference planned to feature a
keynote address by Louis Farrakhan, Nation of Islam leader.
Farrakhan's critics say he is anti-Semitic.
</TEXT>
