<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0833EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Rand-Drugs     03-04 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rand-Drugs,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Despite Increases In Seizures, Drug Flow Grows in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increases in federal seizures of
imported cocaine and marijuana raise the demand for greater amounts
of drug imports and likely fatten the coffers of Latin American
drug producers, a study concludes.
   The study, released Thursday by the Rand Corp., found that more
and more narcotics shipments are being stopped at the borders, but
an even greater number are getting through to meet demands of
American drug users who are ``relatively insensitive'' to higher
prices that may result.
   ``While interdiction raises smugglers' risks, they adapt in the
short run and learn in the long run. Very large increases in
expenditure might lead to more seizures and arrests, but not to
large decreases in consumption,'' said the study by the research
institute.
   Between 1981 and 1986, the government tripled its spending in
the war against imported drugs, from $237 milion to $801 million,
the study said. The military portion of that rose from $1 million
to $196 million.
   Despite the increase, the amount of cocaine reaching U.S. users
rose from between 38 and 68 metric tons in 1981 to between 111 and
153 tons in 1985, the latest year for which figures were available.
   The amount of marijuana entering the United States during the
same period rose from between 8,700 and 12,700 metric tons to
between 9,447 and 12,228 metric tons.
   Seizures of cocaine rose from less than 2 metric tons to more
than 25 metric tons, while seizures of marijuana were halved from
4,000 metric tons to 2,000 metric tons.
   The figures were based on official estimates of the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Adminstration, the study said.
   In addition, Latin American drug manufacturers may be getting
even richer because they make money whether the drugs are
successfully smuggled or not, said the study.
   Meanwhile, it added, a stepped-up seizure of cocaine from
Colombia has caused a shift to Mexican and domestic sources.
   The study, which looked only at cocaine and marijuana, comes as
Congress considers a proposal that would make the Defense
Department a primary agency in the interception of drugs at
substantially increased costs to taxpayers.
   The Defense Department now serves a secondary role, mostly by
providing radar surveillance and limited air and sea pursuit, to
the three agencies that have primary responsibility in stopping the
drug flow: the Coast Guard, the Customs Service and the Immigration
and Naturalization Service.
   Meanwhile, on Thursday the U.S. Coast Guard said it has ended
its routine drug-smuggling patrols by land and sea off the West
Coast because of budget constraints.
   The decision to stop routine sea patrols and surveillance
flights will result in more smugglers successfully delivering their
cargo, Rear Adm. A. Bruce Beran said.
   Beran, commander of the Coast Guard district that includes
California, Oregon, Nevada and Arizona, said he ended the patrols
six weeks ago in an effort to trim some $1 million from his
district's budget.
   He cited as an additional budgetary pressure some $100 million
in cuts to Coast Guard funding contained in a proposal for the 1989
federal budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
