<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BoatHijacked     03-04 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boat Hijacked,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tugboat Repossessed By Its U.S. Owners In Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROSARITO BEACH, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tugboat leased by a company in
this small fishing village in northern Baja California was
repossessed, reportedly at gunpoint, by its U.S.-based owners early
today, the U.S. Coast Guard said.
   Coast Guard officials in San Diego received a distress call in
broken English early today on an emergency radio channel reporting
that armed men were hijacking the vessel, said Jeff D'Annolso of
the San Diego office.
   ``The report said six armed Americans went aboard the tugboat
Northern Warrior,'' said Petty Officer Reid Crispino of the Coast
Guard station in Long Beach.
   The report was called in by the Chartering Panama Co., which
runs a fleet of tugboats that escort tankers in and out of Rosarito
Beach, about 30 miles south of the U.S.-Mexico border, Crispino
said.
   The tugboat was leased to the Mexican company by Seattle,
Wash.-based Stabbert & Associates, he said.
   ``We contacted the owners in Washington and they confirmed they
were repossessing the tugboat due to a lack of payments by the
lessee,'' Crispino said.
   Investigators had not determined how many men boarded the boat,
which was in port at the time, or confirmed whether they were armed.
   Crispino said the Coast Guard had no control over the matter
because it took place in Mexican waters.
   ``If (Chartering Panama Co.) wants to pursue the matter, they'll
have to go to a civil admiralty attorney. It's now a legal
matter,'' he said.
</TEXT>
