<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DalkonShield     03-04 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dalkon Shield,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gynecologist Accused Of Perjury In Suit Against Dalkon Shield</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago obstetrician has been indicted on
federal charges that he lied on the witness stand about his role in
tests concerning the safety of the Dalkon Shield birth control
device.
   Dr. Louis G. Keith, 53, an obstetrician-gynecologist at
Northwestern University Medical School at Chicago, testified
falsely about transfer of bacteria by the tail string of the
intrauterine shield, the Justice Department said Thursday in
announcing the indictment.
   Keith faces eight counts of perjury and one count of obstruction
of justice. If convicted on all counts, he faces 45 years in prison
and $85,000 in fines. An FBI spokesman said Keith was expected to
surrender in Chicago today and be arraigned March 17 in Tampa.
   ``Dr. Keith is innocent and will be vindicated,'' said his
lawyer, Matthew Kennelly. ``That is all I will say.''
   On March 15, 1983, Keith told jurors in a Tampa lawsuit against
A.H. Robins Co., the manufactuer of the IUD, he had performed
experiments that verified the safety of the birth control device.
In fact, he did not design, direct, conduct or do the scientific
experiments ``about which he testified,'' the indictment announced
in Washington said.
   The alleged perjury came during the suit brought by Linda Harre
of Tampa, who alleged that the shield caused her to become sterile.
She lost the $12.5 million suit.
   Mrs. Harre won a new trial in March 1985 when the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta issued a scathing opinion
attacking the veracity of Keith's testimony.
   Five months later, A.H. Robins filed for protection from its
creditors in federal bankruptcy court in Richmond, Va., a measure
which barred future action on pending lawsuits, including Mrs.
Harre's.
   John D. Taylor, a spokesman for A.H. Robins in Richmond, Va.,
said Thursday evening that Keith had testified for the company in
several lawsuits, and the firm has no reason to believe he ever
lied.
   The company halted production and sale of the Dalkon Shield in
the United States and abroad in 1974, although distribution
continued in some foreign countries until early 1985, said Taylor.
   Some 200,000 claims have been filed against A.H. Robins by women
who contend they suffered pelvic infections, sterility or
spontaneous abortions because of the Dalkon Shield. A.H. Robins
sold 2.8 million of the devices between 1971 and 1974 and has paid
more than $300 million in legal damages involving its shield.
   Robins spokesman Roscoe Puckett said the firm is awaiting court
approval of a reorganization plan that would set aside $2.375
billion to settle claims relating to the Dalkon Shield.
</TEXT>
