<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Bangladesh 3rdLd-Writethru a0559 03-04 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0559,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Increases Majority in Parliament</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more results, Ershad's party
increasing majority in Parliament; CORRECTS that Parliament has 330
sted of 300 seats; ADDS details on 1986 results and number of
eligible voters. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad's
Jatiya Party increased its majority in Parliament today after
national elections marked by violence, fraud and an opposition
boycott.
   At least 11 people were reported killed and more than 300 were
injured during voting Thursday for 299 contested seats in the
330-seat Parliament. Turnout appeared very low and even Jatiya
Party members acknowledged ballot boxes were stuffed.
   With results in for 194 races, Jatiya candidates had won 176
seats. In 18 of those contests, they ran unopposed. One race was
postponed because one of the candidates for the open seat was
killed.
   A coalition of 73 minor opposition parties won nine seats,
according to Election Commission figures. Two other small parties
had one seat each, and independents gained seven.
   Another 30 seats in Parliament are reserved for women, who are
chosen later.
   Opposition leaders alleged that the outcome was due to rigged
voting, which is common in Bangladesh politics.
   The opposition, which launched a campaign Nov. 10 to demand
Ershad's ouster, succeeded in shutting down most of Dhaka on
election day with a general strike. But the government said the
election, the fourth in Bangladesh's 17 years of independence from
Pakistan, was ``successful and peaceful.''
   Foreign reporters who visited polling stations in and around
Dhaka noted a low turnout and much vote tampering.
   Ershad, a former army general who seized power in a 1982
bloodless coup, called the elections in a failed attempt to appease
the opposition.
   At separate news conferences today, chief opposition leaders
Sheik Hasina and Khaleda Zia vowed to continue the campaign to oust
Ershad, who was elected president in 1986 in balloting they say was
rigged.
   In those elections, the Jatiya Party won 152 seats in
Parliament. The main opposition Awami League won 102, and small
parties held the rest.
   The two opposition leaders said rallies in Dhaka were planned
for Saturday to protest the balloting.
   Ershad scheduled Thursday's elections after he dissolved
Parliament last December, 3{ years ahead of schedule. The move was
aimed at working out a compromise with his foes, but they demanded
instead that Ershad step down and said elections held under him
wouldn't be fair.
   Election officials and some Jatiya Party said ballot boxes were
stuffed to favor the governing party and inflate the turnout.
   The independent Bangladesh Observer newspaper reported on
polling in nine cities and did not list any with heavy voting. The
descriptions it used for turnout in various cities were ``very
negligible ... very meager ... 1 percent to 2 percent'' of the 47.8
million eligible voters.
   Home Minister Abdul Matin claimed there was a good turnout.
   He told reporters that on the basis of 12 voting centers he
visited in Dhaka, he estimated voter turnout at 50 percent.
</TEXT>
