<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua-Contras     03-04 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Contras,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Calls for Reagan-Ortega Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua called for direct talks
between President Reagan and President Daniel Ortega and said
Congress' rejection of aid to the Contras would help peace in
Central America.
   The lefist Sandinista government Thursday also urged the Reagan
administration not to interfere in cease-fire talks between it and
the Contras, the U.S.-backed group that has been fighting to
overthrow it.
   A statement released by government spokesman Manuel Espinoza
said the U.S. House of Representatives' rejection of aid for the
Nicaraguan rebels ``must contribute to the peace efforts taken by
the presidents of the Central American countries.''
   The House voted 216-210 to kill the $30 million package of
``humanitarian'' aid.
   The Contras, meanwhile, accepted Ortega's proposal to resume
negotiations in Nicaragua March 9-11, but said Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo must be kept on as mediator.
   Ortega said the talks should go on without the Roman Catholic
archbishop of Managua, who mediated two previous rounds.
   The president proposed that the new talks be held in the town of
Sapoa near the Costa Rican border. The government also reiterated
its call for direct talks between Ortega and Reagan.
   ``The government of Nicaragua urges one more time that the
president of the United States undertake direct negotiations with
the president of Nicaragua that take into account security aspects
(and) the normalization of relations'' between the two countries,
the statement said.
   The United States has insisted on talks between the Contras and
Sandinistas and has refused to talk to the Nicaraguan government.
   The Nicaraguan talks are being held in line with a peace plan
signed by five Central American presidents on Aug. 7.
</TEXT>
