<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0909EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-JapaneseBid     03-04 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japanese Bid,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transit Authority Rejects Low Bid From Consortium Including
Japanese Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Washington Metropolitan Area Transit
Authority has rejected a $49.2 million low bid from a construction
consortium that included a Japanese firm, citing a congressional
ban on awarding federally funded contracts to Japanese companies.
   The provision, signed by President Reagan in December, bars the
awarding of contracts to firms of any country that discriminates
against foreign bidders in its own public works projects.
   It was aimed at Japan, which has prohibited foreign
participation in more than $60 billion worth of public works
projects it plans during the next 10 years.
   The Metro board made its decision Thursday as U.S. and Japanese
negotiators were meeting at the State Department in an attempt to
resolve the construction dispute, a major source of contention
between the two countries.
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, who co-authored the provision
with Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, hailed Metro's decision.
   ``The Japanese private sector needed to know that America is
ready to use the leverage at our disposal to open their market. If
they didn't think we meant business before, they know it now,''
Murkowskiaid.
   ``No one is going to take a chance of using a Japanese firm in
any capacity for any project,'' said Metro deputy general counsel
Robert Polk. The law ``will have the desired congressional
effect,'' he said.
   The low bid came from a joint venture between Kiewit
Construction of Omaha, Neb., and the Kajima Construction Company of
Japan to work on tunnels and rails for a new subway line, which is
to run beneath an existing station in northeast Washington. Kajima
was a 30 percent partner in the plan, and Kiewit 70 percent.
   John F. McElhenny, Metro's assistant general manager for design,
said bidding on the project will be reopened. He said rejection of
the contract is not likely to delay construction, which is
scheduled for completion in 1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
