<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MercyKilling     03-04 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mercy Killing,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused Of Killing Wife Receives Reassurances At Her Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 77-year-old man accused in the mercy
killing of his ailing wife received reassurances from family
members as he attended her funeral in the company of the county
sheriff.
   ``You know I really loved her, don't you?'' a weeping Oscar
Carlson asked his daughter, Marcene Cole, as he reached to hug her
after the service Thursday at Faith Lutheran Church.
   ``Of course,'' Mrs. Cole said through her tears as they embraced.
   Carlson, described as a kind man and a regular churchgoer, was
escorted to the funeral by Douglas County Sheriff Terry Eilers and
three deputies. The frail former farmer did not wear handcuffs or
leg chains.
   Asked if Carlson's family had forgiven him, nephew Gordon
Johnson said, ``Right after it happened.''
   ``Look at what Oscar was going through,'' Johnson said. ``You
live with someone for 40-some years ... they were always together
... and then it all falls apart. I think there's a lot of sympathy
for Oscar.''
   Carlson was charged with first- and second-degree murder after
authorities said he used a .22-caliber weapon to shoot his
71-year-old wife, Agnes, four times Monday at a nursing home.
   Carlson said he killed his wife of 47 years to spare her from
the agony of Alzheimer's disease, a debilitating ailment that
leaves its victims disoriented and often unable to care for
themselves. Agnes Carlson exhibited the first signs of the disease
four years ago.
   Just before the service Thursday, Carlson was allowed a moment
alone at the open casket. He held his wife's hand for a time and
then relatives came up to embrace him.
   Pastor George Larson did not mention the circumstances of Mrs.
Carlson's death. Instead, he urged the family to take comfort in
the biblical promise of life after death.
   ``Agnes believed in the Lord,'' Larson told the approximately
120 mourners. ``When we believe in the Lord Jesus Christ we have
already begun our eternal life and death is just a passing.''
   Carlson was returned to jail in Alexandria after the service to
await a Monday hearing, at which his attorney plans to request that
Carlson's $100,000 bail be reduced and he be allowed to use his
house as collateral.
</TEXT>
