<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Missing 3rdLd-Writethru   03-04 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Missing, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0576,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Briton Kidnapped in Sidon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with details. Pick up 10th graf
pvs: `On Wednesday...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British official of the Oxfam relief
organization was kidnapped with a Syrian colleague in the southern
port city of Sidon, Oxfam headquarters said today.
   Peter Coleridge, 44, and Omar Traboulsi, 31, were seized
Thursday night, Oxfam spokesman John Magrath said in Oxford,
England. Coleridge is the organization's Middle East coordinator
and Traboulsi is its Lebanon representative, he said.
   ``We've had conflicting reports as to whether they are still
being held or not,'' Magrath said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the abductions, which brought
the number of foreigners missing and believed kidnapped in Lebanon
to 24.
   There were no eyewitnesses confirming the abduction, said
Nissrine Rawda, an official at Oxfam's Beirut office.
   Oxfam is a British charity that aids refugees and poor people
around the world.
   Ms. Rawda said Coleridge went to Sidon Thursday accompanied by
at least two local Oxfam staff members and had been expected back
in Beirut later today. Sidon is 25 miles south of Beirut.
   She said Coleridge arrived in Lebanon two days ago on his first
visit in three years to inspect Oxfam's operations. He lives in
Oxford with his wife and two daughters.
   Magrath said he could not give any other details of the
abduction. A police spokesman said Lebanese authorities had no
information about a missing Briton.
   ``We have ideas about who might have done it, but we don't want
to speculate,'' Magrath said.
   ``The people we work with on the ground have told us not to
panic. We know they're making contacts in Sidon to find out exactly
what's happened and see that Peter and Omar are released.''
   The Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon radio station earlier
reported in Beirut that Coleridge and Trabousli were missing
shortly after their arrival in Sidon.
   A British embassy official termed the report at that time ``a
false alarm.''
   Sidon is Lebanon's third largest city with a predominantly Sunni
Moslem population of about 250,000.
   On Wednesday, pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem militants released a
West German captive, Ralph Schray, 30, in Beirut five weeks after
he was kidnapped.
   Two U.N. Relief and Works agency officials, Jan Stening, 44, of
Sweden and William Jorgensen, 58, of Norway, were kidnapped near
Sidon Feb. 5, apparently by Palestinians acting independently of
guerrilla groups.
   Their abductors handed the two over to the Palestine Liberation
Organization on Tuesday after 25 days in captivity.
   Twenty-two other foreigners are missing and believed kidnapped
in Lebanon. They include nine Americans, four Frenchmen, three
Britons, a West German, an Italian, an Irishman, an Indian and two
unidentified men.
   The hostage held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was seized
March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
