<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0411 03-04 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0411,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unemployment Falls to Lowest Level Since 1979</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with February unemployment
figures. Picks up in 3rd graf, ``Productivity among.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment slipped 0.1 percent to 5.7 percent last month as
half a million new jobs were created, the government said today.
   The February decline brought unemployment to its lowest level
since the summer of 1979 and followed no change in jobless levels
in January, the Labor Department said.
   Employment grew by 280,000, with the number of jobless Americans
falling by 108,000 to 6.9 million, the department said in its
survey of households.
   A separate survey of business payrolls showed a net increase of
531,000 jobs in February, 40 percent of which were in service
industries.
   On Thursday, the department said the nation's productivity rose
just 0.9 percent last year, only slightly more than earlier
estimates and the lowest since the last recession, the government
says.
   Meanwhile, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks slipped
7.80 points to 2,063.49, the dollar was mixed in foreign exchange
and bond prices barely budged in lethargic trading.
   Productivity among non-farm businesses that are responsible for
three-fourths of the nation's economic activity rose at an annual
rate of 0.3 percent in the fourth quarter, the Labor Department
said. That contrasted with a 0.2 percent deterioration reported in
preliminary figures last month.
   Productivity is a measure of the amount of labor required to
produce goods and services.
   The revisions raised the productivity improvement for the entire
year from 0.8 percent to 0.9 percent, slightly more than half the
1.6 percent gain of 1986.
   The efficiency improvements for the year were the smallest since
1982, when an economic recession depressed output so much that
productivity actually declined 0.6 percent from 1981.
   ``Anything less than 1 percent is a disappointing number,'' said
Roger Brinner, an economist for Data Resources Inc. of Lexington,
Mass. ``It gives you very little room to buffer pay increases and
not much leeway to improve the standard of living.''
   The revised figures on productivity showed output of goods and
services by non-farm businesses rising by an annual rate of 5.6
percent in the fourth quarter.
   That was the greatest increase in nearly two years and compared
with a rise of 5.1 percent in the preliminary figures before the
gross national product was revised upward last week by the Commerce
Department.
   But in achieving that higher output, businesses increased the
total hours worked by their employees by 5.3 percent.
   ``Frankly, we don't foresee much improvement in productivity
this year,'' said Donald Straszheim, chief economist for Merrill
Lynch. ``Productivity improvements require rapid growth and we
haven't been experiencing much of that lately.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
