<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Protest     03-04 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Protest,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Demonostration; Political Parties Work on
Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today dragged away dozens of
protesters demanding the release of political prisoners and trying
to march into the presidential mansion.
   About 30 family members of imprisoned dissidents gathered in
front of the Blue House, the presidential residence, demanding an
interview with President Roh Tae-woo.
   Riot police took away the protesters, who shouted
anti-government slogans and tried to march into the residence.
   At Seoul National University, about 200 students called for the
release of political prisoners and denounced a recent government
amnesty as insufficient.
   The government released about 130 political prisoners last
Saturday, saying only dissidents guilty of violent crimes or
subversion remained in prison.
   The Joong-ang Ilbo, an influential Seoul newspaper, said the
freed dissidents are under surveillance and that their daily
activities were reported to security authorities.
   Also today, the governing and opposition parties resolved their
differences over electoral rules and other issues, clearing the way
for National Assembly elections expected in mid-April.
   In addition, senior officials of the two main opposition
parties, controlled by Kim Young-sam and Kim Dae-jung, agreed on
basic rules for their merger before the balloting.
   In December's presidential election, the two Kims split the
opposition vote. Roh won with 36.6 percent of the vote.
   The officials said after a three-hour meeting that they would
propose the elections be held under a system picking one lawmaker
instead of two in each district.
   The governing Democratic Justice Party welcomed the opposition
proposal.
   The governing party, which had favored a system electing one to
three members in each district depending on the size of population,
changed its position today on the order of the president.
   Before today's meeting, the opposition camp was itself divided
over the election formula, forcing a delay in adopting the new laws
needed before balloting can be held.
   The proposed reform would increase the overall number of
legislators from 271 to 300 by increasing the number of districts.
</TEXT>
