<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0944EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Tobacco     03-04 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Tobacco,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Decrees Smoking Ban, Industry Accepts Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today decreed a ban on
smoking in public places and launched a campaign to try to convince
this nation of smokers to give up the habit.
   The government of Socialist Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez also
outlawed the selling of tobacco to anyone under 16.
   The ban will take effect in July, three months after its
publication in the official state bulletin. It was in keeping with
directives issued by the European Economic Community.
   Representatives of Spain's tobacco industry agreed to accept a
complete ban on television advertising and restrictions limiting
outdoor advertising to the name of their brand.
   According to EEC statistics, 41 percent of Spain's 38.8 million
people smoke, the second highest figure in the 12-nation community
after Greece.
   The same statistics indicate about 60,000 Spaniards die each
year from smoking-related diseases.
   The decree requires cigarette and cigar packages to carry the
warning that smoking causes cancer and endangers the life of the
smoker as well as unborn babies.
   It bans smoking in hospitals, department stores, elevators and
places where pregnant women work and prohibits the sale of tobacco
products to minors under 16.
   The decree says that the rights of non-smokers over those of
smokers will take priority in all legal questions. It carries fines
on infractions ranging from $4,400 to $880,000, but its enforcement
mechanism remains unclear.
   Spanish explorers who traveled to Central and South America in
the 16th century returned with string-tied rolls of tobacco leaves
that became the rage among their wealthy countrymen under the name
``cigar.''
   Etymologists believe the word comes from ``sik'ar,'' the term
the Mayan Indians of Central America used for smoking.
   ``Cigarillos'' or ``little cigars'' were devised by street
beggars in Seville from the butts of cast-off cigars and are the
forerunners of today's cigarettes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
