<DOCNO> AP880304-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan-Opposition     03-04 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Opposition,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Break In Talks Brings Extraordinary Political Contact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will hold an
unprecedented meeting with its political opposition to discuss
whether Pakistan should sign a peace accord with Afghanistan,
officials said today.
   Saturday's meeting will mark the first time the Pakistan
government has sought direct contact with the opposition since
before July 1977, when President Gen. Mohammad Zia Ul-haq seized
power and imposed martial law.
   Officials said nearly all 19 parties have accepted an invitation
to meet with Prime Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo.
   The chief of the Pakistani delegation to the U.N. Afghanistan
talks in Geneva, Foreign State Minister Zain Noorani, was to return
to Islamabad today, after the third day of indirect negotiations
with the communist Afghan government.
   Pakistani officials said Junejo wanted to discuss whether
Pakistan should link an accord over a Soviet troop withdrawal from
Afghanistan with the formation of an interim coalition government
in Kabul.
   About 115,000 Soviet troops are in Afghanistan. The Soviets have
been fighting Afghan rebels since 1979 when they entered the
country and replaced the existing communist government with another
one.
   Almost all opposition leaders pledged to attend the
extraordinary meeting except Pakistan People's Party leader Benazir
Bhutto, who was reported ill with influenza. Her Karachi office
said she would at least fly to Islamabad to consult with her
representatives.
   Ms. Bhutto's father, ousted Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto,
was hanged in 1979 after he was convicted of plotting a political
murder.
   Zia lifted martial law on Dec. 30, 1985, after the installation
of Junejo's Muslim League government the previous March.
   Most opposition parties boycotted the election that brought
Junejo to power and still refuse to recognize his government.
   Pakistan's largest opposition alliance, the nine-party Movement
for the Restoration of Democracy, decided to accept the
government's gesture because it was not founded in protest over
foreign policy, said Sheikh Rafiq Ahmed, an official in Mrs.
Bhutto's party.
   Not all opposition parties have declared their stand on
Afghanistan but most have urged the government to sign a Soviet
pullout accord, then worry about a political settlement later.
   In a recent turnabout, Pakistan has threatened not to sign a
Geneva accord that does not provide a safe environment for the
return of the 5 million Afghan refugees living in Pakistan and Iran.
   Islamabad has said it fears that the Soviets' absence will clear
the way for a new bloody internecine struggle between the
pro-Moscow government of President Najib and Afghan Moslem
guerrillas, based in Pakistan.
   Saturday's meeting could give the Pakistanis a face-saving
pretext to soften their controversial stance at Geneva. It also
could serve to enhance the Muslim League government's own
legitimacy at home.
</TEXT>
