<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EMSProtest     03-04 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EMS Protest,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Half City's Ambulance Workers Call In Sick</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half the city's ambulance workers
scheduled for the day shift called in sick today, but police and
supervisory employees were helping fill gaps in service, the city
said.
   The Emergency Medical Service instituted a contingency plan to
meet the job action, which had been announced in advance as a
demonstration for higher pay.
   Sick calls were received from 176 of 347 workers on the day
shift, said Suzanne Halpin of the Health and Hospitals Corp.,
parent of EMS and operator of the municipal hospitals system.
   ``The employees calling in are being told they may be violating
a court order and the Taylor Law,'' she said. Penalties ranging
from loss of two days' pay to dismissal were possible. The Taylor
Law is a state law that prohibits strikes by public employees.
   Some of the gaps in ambulance service were being filled by
police and other EMS employees, including supervisors, Halpin said.
   The sickout, which was announced as a one-day protest, was
barred Thursday afternoon by Supreme Court Justice Edward Lehner,
who ruled that EMS workers could not stage ``any kind of concerted
job action.''
   The decision to stage a sickout was made by about 400 workers in
a vote taken Wednesday night while union leaders were kept out of
the meeting.
   The 2,000-member union, without a contract since July, has
demanded salary and benefits comparable to police and firefighters,
whose starting pay is $26,000, said Richard Burstein, the union
secretary-treasurer.
   The union has asked that EMS starting pay of $21,500 be raised
by $6,000 over three years; the city is offering $600.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
