<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NRC-GaTech     03-04 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NRC-Ga Tech,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Investigating Handling Of Tech Reactor Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is
investigating its own offices in Atlanta because NRC internal
documents involving an investigation of Georgia Tech's reactor
program were found at Tech, a newspaper reported today.
   Leaks from the NRC may have tipped Tech to the identities of
employees at the school's Neely Nuclear Research Center who had
complained about lax safety procedures, The Atlanta Constitution
said, quoting unidentified sources with Congress and the NRC.
   The two employees, members of the physics staff responsible for
safety of nuclear materials, were dismissed and then rehired and
given other jobs by Tech three weeks ago. They claim they were
fired because they complained to the NRC about reactor safety.
   NRC officials in Washington declined to comment.
   Dr. Nelson Grace, administrator of NRC's Southeast regional
office in Atlanta, acknowledged he had asked the agency's office of
inspector-auditor to ``investigate to determine whether or not
internal NRC documents may have come into the possession of'' a
reactor manager.
   Grace declined to name the reactor, but the Constitution quoted
other unidentified sources as confirming that it was the now-idled
five-megawatt reactor at Tech.
   Georgia Tech President John P. Crecine ordered the reactor out
of service until the NRC investigation is completed.
</TEXT>
