<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1037EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugBeepers     03-04 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Beepers,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Board Bans Beepers In Effort To Stop Drug Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Baltimore City School Board has banned
telephone beepers because school officials said they were being
used by students acting as go-betweens in drug deals.
   Effective March 14, students found carrying a beeper face
suspension, under the new policy adopted by the board Thursday.
   School officials say the telephone pagers are a status symbol in
the drug world, and are also used by students who want to portray
the image of being involved in narcotics.
   ``When I see a beeper I assume the worst,'' said Arthur Pierce,
principal of Francis M. Wood High School. ``At the high school and
middle school level, if a child is in possession of an operational
beeper, they are usually dealing drugs.
   `At the elementary level, kids are wearing inoperative beepers
to appear tough or macho and mimic the older kids. And that's not
something to encourage,'' said Pierce, who has been confiscating
the pagers at his school for the past three years.
   Beepers also were banned from schools in Nashville, Tenn., in
December. Similar problems have been reported from Florida to
Michigan.
   Virtually all drug possession arrests in Baltimore schools
involve marijuana, said Larry Burgan, school police chief, with a
few instances of cocaine or cocaine derivatives.
   ``From my standpoint, I don't see any time a student would need
to carry a beeper,'' said Burgan. ``It's basically a disruptive
influence, whether the kids are carrying them to traffic drugs or
just to project that image, it's no good.''
   Pierce said it is hard to determine the scope of the problem
because most beepers go undetected.
   New beepers no longer emit the three short beeps from which
their name was derived.
   ``The more sophisticated ones vibrate against the body or are
fitted with a silencer that keeps them from being detected,''
Pierce said.
   Burgan said the drug problem is kept under control largely
because city high schools have officers patrolling the halls.
</TEXT>
