<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1045EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-CovertAction 1stLd-Writethru a0444 03-04 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Covert Action, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,560</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new to udpate with today's vote, picks up 5th
graf pvs, Cohen suggested.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, kept in the dark by the Reagan
administration during the Iran-Contra affair, today rejected an
effort to let the White House withhold details about covert actions
from Congress.
   The 65-23 vote came as the chamber worked on a bill requiring
that Congress be notified of all covert actions within 48 hours.
   The decision came on an amendment by Sen. James McClure,
R-Idaho, that would have allowed a president simply to tell
Congress that a covert action was underway but withhold details and
specifics until later.
   ``This is a compromise. It gives the president some
flexibility,'' said McClure.
   But Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, chief author of the bill,
opposed McClure, telling his colleagues, ``This is not a
compromise; it's a capitulation. ... This lets the president play
`I've got a secret' but not tell.''
   ``This cannot guarantee that future abuses such as Iran-Contra
will not occur, but it will certainly minimize them,'' Cohen,
vice-chairman of the Intelligence Committee, said late Thursday as
debate began.
   The bill overhauls procedures for notifying Congress about
intelligence activites. The central feature would require that
Congress be notified within 48 hours of the time a covert, or
secret, action begins.
   Cohen suggested that the requirement could have helped expose
the Iran-Contra affair, in which U.S. weapons were sold to Iran and
some of the profits were diverted to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   Reagan's approval of the Iranian arms deal was withheld from
Congress for 10 months in 1986, until it was revealed by a Beirut
publication.
   CIA Director William Webster, testifying last month to the House
Intelligence Committee, said the 48-hour notification requirement
``will not be acceptable to the president.'' But Webster did not
say whether Reagan would veto the bill.
   Cohen noted that presidents normally have notified Congress of
most covert actions ever since congressional review committees were
created 14 years ago in the wake of revelations about a series of
abuses by the CIA.
   He said it is time to close the last loophole by requiring
notification of all such actions.
   ``The Iran-Contra affair shows what happens when a president
seeks to circumvent Congress,'' Cohen said.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., chairman of the Intelligence
Committee, called the measure ``landmark legislation.''
   Reagan has promised to notify Congress about future covert
actions, but Boren said, ``We feel a need to put these changes into
statute'' to make sure a president does not go back on his word.
   ``We do not want our country ever again to go through what it
did these last few months because of the Iran-Contra affair,''
Boren said.
   ``There's an old saying that two heads are better than one''
said Boren. ``In the Intelligence Committee, we try to give those
in the intelligence community our best judgment.''
   Sen. James McClure, R-Idaho, opposed the bill because he said
the notification provision ``could endanger American lives and the
lives of others who have taken the risk of assisting the United
States.''
   Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., agreed with McClure. ``This bill
will cost lives,'' he said.
   The bill was approved by the Senate Intelligence Committee last
December on a 13-2 vote. If passed by the full Senate, it will need
House approval before it would go to Reagan's desk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1103EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan     03-04 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nationalist Lawmakers Call for Contact with China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Nationalist legislators today
asked the Taiwan government to drop its 40-year-old policy of
having no contact with the communist government in Beijing.
   Huang Shu-wek, one of the 12 lawmakers questioning the
no-contact policy during a Legislative Yuan session, proposed a
``temporary two-China policy'' to precede eventual reunification.
   Huang said the Taipei and Beijing governments must ``compete on
an equal footing so we can show all Chinese people the achievements
of Taiwan's development and let them accept our system.''
   Huang proposed that the Nationalist government provide financial
and technological aid for China's modernization and discuss
bilateral trade and other relations with Beijing.
   The two countries already have a secret trade estimated at more
than $1 billion a year through third parties such as Hong Kong and
Singapore. Taiwan recently began allowing its citizens to visit
their families on the mainland.
   The Nationalists have refused official contacts with China since
1949 when they fled to Taiwan after losing a civil war on the
mainland to the communists. Both governments claim to be the
rightful government of the mainland and Taiwan.
   Premier Yu Kuo-hwa said in response that ``communist China has
never treated us equally and the time has not yet come for peaceful
competition'' between the two governments.
   Yao Chia-wen, chairman of the opposition Democratic Progressive
Party, said, ``We don't care too much about the Nationalists' claim
to represent China.''
   Dozens of political activists held a torch-light run today
through downtown Taipei echoing the demands of President Lee
Tung-hi that elderly Nationalist Chinese legislators elected on the
mainland four decades ago should retire.
   ``This is the time for our elderly legislators to step down.
Most of those who voted for them 40 years ago on the mainland have
already died,'' opposition legislator You Ching told about 100
people outside the National Assembly after the run.
   Led by legislator Chu Kao-cheng of the opposition Democratic
Progressive Party, about 60 runners began at the Legislative Yuan
building and finished an hour later outside the National Assembly,
where opposition leaders delivered speeches from a pickup truck.
   Many elderly members of the Legislative Yuan, Taiwan's highest
lawmaking body, and the National Assembly, the electoral college,
have rejected a proposal for them to retire voluntarily.
   Last Saturday Lee urged the elderly legislators to resign in
accordance with the government's plans to reform Taiwan's political
system.
   ``We must place national interests and public welfare above our
personal opinions,'' Lee told the National Assembly.
   Lawmakers elected on Taiwan now account for 73 members of the
312-seat Legislative Yuan and 106 members of the 934-seat National
Assembly.
   The other seats are either empty or held by aging Nationalists.
   Opposition leaders said the elderly legislators, who have been
frozen in office to support the Nationalists' claim to be the
legitimate government of mainland China, should yield their seats
so all lawmakers can be elected in Taiwan.
   During the run, some activists distributed flyers listing
telephone numbers of 120 aging assemblymen. Chu has urged Taiwanese
to call elderly lawmakers and ask them to retire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
