<DOCNO> AP880304-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaSuit     03-04 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Suit,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Presents Videotape Recreation of Flight's Last Minutes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engineer testifying in Delta Air
Lines suit against the government used an animated videotape
recreating the final two minutes of Delta Flight 191 in an attempt
to disprove government claims that the flight crew could have
escaped a violent wind shear.
   Charles Bautz, a performance engineering manager for the
Atlanta-based airline, testified Thursday that the pilots reacted
properly to the turbulent winds during their approach to
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport on Aug. 2, 1985.
   In a non-jury trial being heard by U.S. District Judge David O.
Belew Jr. of Fort Worth, Delta contends that the federal government
should bear legal responsibility for the crash and pay all or part
of more than $90 million in death, injury and damage claims Delta
has paid in connection with the crash.
   Bautz, who worked as a member of a government technical team
investigating the crash, presented the videotape recreation based
on recorded flight data, which he said shows the crew encountered a
second, fatal wind shear seconds after pulling out of the first
downdraft.
   The co-pilot applied maximum power and attempted to abandon the
landing, Bautz said.
   A National Transportation Safety Board investigation said the
crash that killed 137 people and injured 25 others was caused, in
part, by the sudden downdrafts of wind.
   The airline claims government air traffic controllers and
weather forecasters failed to warn the flight crew of the storm.
   Testimony in the trial could last several more weeks, attorneys
said.
</TEXT>
