<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ClevelandTeachers     03-04 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cleveland Teachers,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Recommends Acceptance of Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cleveland Teachers Union has recommended
that its 5,100 members ratify a tentative agreement reached after a
weeklong strike that closed city schools for most of the district's
73,000 students.
   Schools were closed today but probably will reopen Monday,
Superintendent Alfred Tutela said.
   The school board scheduled a meeting for Saturday night to
consider ratifying the agreement and discuss plans for reopening
the schools, he said.
   Eugene Kolach, president of the teachers union, said the union's
executive board voted Thursday night to endorse the pact, which was
reached earlier after nearly 24 hours of negotiations.
   ``Our executive board has voted to suspend our strike beginning
Monday,'' Kolach said. ``It's not a case of being happy with the
pact, it's a case of understanding when we've gotten the best
possible situation.''
   Both sides declined to discuss the terms of the agreement until
after teachers vote on it. Kolach said the union planned a five-day
voting period for its 5,093 members following an information
meeting Sunday.
   Teachers walked off their jobs Feb. 25, but district officials
canceled classes that day because of snow. Cleveland schools have
been closed since then because of the strike, except for classes
that began Wednesday for some of the district's 3,600 high school
seniors.
   At least some of the missed school days will have to be made up
to meet state requirements.
   The union's contract expired in September, but union members
continued working. The district's teacher salaries range from
$17,600 to $37,450, based on education and experience. The average
annual salary is $29,500.
   The last teachers' strike in Cleveland, Ohio's largest school
district and the 30th largest school system in the United States,
was an 11-week walkout in 1979.
</TEXT>
