<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab 2ndLd-Writethru a0603 03-04 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0603,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Extremists Kill 34; Sikh High Priests Freed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS graf after 13th pvs, `Punjab security...' to ADD
background. Pick up 14th pvs, `Among the...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARI SARI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant Sikhs burst into a courtyard
and opened fire on a crowd celebrating a Hindu holiday, killing at
least 34 people and wounding about 45, police said today.
   The attack in the northern state of Punjab was one of the
bloodiest since Sikh extremists launched their guerrilla war for an
independent homeland there in 1982. It occurred shortly before
midnight.
   A. Siddiqui, a deputy inspector general of police, said most of
the victims were Hindus, but nine Sikhs were among those killed.
   About 900 Hindus, Sikhs and Christians had gathered outside a
Hindu temple to celebrate Holi, the festival of color. The national
holiday commemorates the triumph of the Hindu god Lord Krishna over
evil.
   The attack brought to more than 370 the number of people killed
this year in attacks blamed on Sikh extremists. Sikhs are a
religious minority in India and claim they are discriminated
against by the majority Hindus.
   In an apparent peace overture today, the government freed four
Sikh high priests. The release of 40 Sikh militants was also
planned, the United News of India reported from the Punjab state
capital of Chandigarh.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack in
Kari Sari, which is about 80 miles east of the Sikh holy city of
Amritsar. Police blamed the Kalistan Commando Force. Kalistan is
the name Sikh militants would given to their envisioned nation.
   Mahavir Prashad, who was inside a building and escaped injury,
said:, ``People ran helter-skelter. There were bodies on the
ground, and the injured were crying.
   ``I tried to save some of the injured by giving them water, but
most of them died in my arms.''
   Siddiqui, addressing a news conference in the nearby town of
Hoshiarpur, said the shooting lasted about 20 minutes. He said six
to eight gunmen participated.
   Brij Kishore, deputy superintendent of police at Chandigarh, the
state capital, said villagers had gathered around two bonfires and
were singing songs when the gunmen drove up in three cars, opened
fire with AK-47 assault rifles and machine guns, and fled.
   Police said 23 people were killed on the spot and 11 others
taken to hospitals died later of their injuries.
   Punjab security forces and New Delhi police were put on alert
after the killing to prevent any backlash.
   The attack was the worst in Punjab since last July, when Sikh
gunmen waylaid three buses and slaughtered 72 people, most of them
Hindus. Thirty-eight Hindu pilgrims were killed and 24 injured July
6 when a bus was attacked near Chandigarh. The next day, 34 people
died in attacks on two buses in neighboring Haryana state.
   Among the priests released today was Jasbir Singh Rode, a nephew
of the late Sikh radical leader Jarnail Singh Bhindranwale.
   The other three are Jaswant Singh, Kashmir Singh and Savinder
Singh, who were arrested in October.
   Rode was the chief priest at the Golden Temple in Amritsar when
he was arrested during a June 1984 army raid that drove militants
out of the temple, the Sikh's holiest shrine. Bhindranwale was
among the 1,200 killed in the raid.
   Indian Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, who ordered the raid, was
assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards four months later. Her
son and successor, Rajiv Gandhi, signed a peace accord with Sikh
leaders in July 1985 to try to end the hostility. The accord later
fell apart.
   On Thursday night, Punjab representatives from Parliament met
with leaders of Gandhi's party and urged freedom for the priests
``so they can use their high position to restore normalcy'' in
Punjab, UNI reported.
</TEXT>
