<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RemakingCities 1stLdd-Writethru a0467 03-04 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Remaking Cities, 1st Ldd-Writethru, a0467,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Urban Planners Look To Prince As Catalyst For Change</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to UPDATE with arrival of Prince Charles.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Urban planners eager to revitalize aging
industrial centers are urging city dwellers to take charge of their
own future, and are looking to Britain's Prince Charles to drive
that message home.
   Charles arrived today in cold and rainy to take part in an
international architectural symposium and get a first-hand look at
the despair and disrepair of once-mighty U.S. steel towns.
   ``We see him as somewhat of a catalyst'' for urban renewal
efforts from within, said Volker Hartkopf, an architecture
professor at Carnegie Mellon University here.
   The Prince of Wales has emerged as an outspoken advocate of
community architecture and inner-city rehabilitation over the past
few years.
   He made worldwide headlines in December when he accused
architects of wreaking more havoc on London than German bombers did
in World War II, and said postwar planners were artless, mediocre
and contemptuous of public opinion.
   ``More than anyone else in his position, he has tried to find
out for himself exactly what it (urban decay) is because he is
concerned,'' said Roger Tillotson, lecturer at the University of
Newcastle upon Tyne in England.
   Prince Charles is honorary chairman of the four-day Remaking
Cities Conference, which is exploring ways to bring prosperity back
to depressed communities in the United States and Britain.
   This afternoon, he plans to visit a new jobs center for the
region's blue-collar unemployed and a high school computer training
classroom.
   On the conference's last day Saturday, he is to address about
350 people attending the symposium sponsored by the American
Institute of Architects and Royal Institute of British Architects.
   In his speech, the 39-year-old heir to the British throne is
expected to comment on recommendations made by conference delegates
for helping cities move from single-industry to more diversified
economies.
   ``Before, like it or not, companies took care of life. You may
not have liked everything they did. But they were there. It was
secure,'' said John Clarke, a Trenton, N.J., architect.
   ``But when that goes away, suddenly you turn around and say,
`Gee, the leadership used to be the company.' Now the leadership
has to be you,'' said Clarke, who led a 17-member study of the
region's depressed steel towns.
   In its 120-page report presented Monday, the team stressed the
need for public participation in replacing the darkened factories
dominating the Monongahela River banks parks, gardens, marinas and
shops.
   ``That valley is a gold mine, and I think these people would be
fools not to take up the opportunity,'' said team member Tony
McGann, a planner from Liverpool, England. ``It's a golden
opportunity that might not come again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1210EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0456 03-04 0898</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Senate vote; picks up 6th graf pvs, For
Noriega. Removes last 3 grafs pvs to shorten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted
unanimously today for a resolution urging the Reagan administration
to end all contacts with Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and to
consider imposing economic sanctions against his military regime in
Panama.
   But the committee took no action on legislation introduced on
Thursday and co-sponsored by 25 senators which would impose a total
trade embargo on Panama in an effort to break Noriega's hold on the
country.
   The 15-0 committee vote approving the non-binding resolution
came after administration officials, seeking to avoid passage of
trade embargo legislation, proposed a set of milder alternatives
that still would penalize the Noriega regime.
   National Security Adviser Colin Powell told reporters Thursday
night that several economic and financial measures were being
prepared for consideration by President Reagan, but he refused to
be more specific.
   Other officials, insisting on anonymity, said the administration
believes a bipartisan congressional proposal for a trade, air,
travel and currency embargo against Panama would be unwise.
   The administration believes U.S. interests would be better
served if Noriega were ousted primarily by Panamanian _ and not
American _ pressure.
   The officials said displays of American heavy-handedness could
be used by Noriega to his advantage and could produce resentment
elsewhere in Latin America, where U.S. intervention has long been a
popular anti-American rallying cry.
   The committee resolution declares that Eric Arturo Devalle, who
was ousted by the Panamanian parliament after trying to fire
Noriega as commander of Panama's armed forces, remains the
country's legitimate head of state and should reeceive ``the full
moral, political and diplomatic support of the government of the
United States.''
   It called on the White House to ``formally terminate any and all
contacts with Gen. Noriega.''
   ``The government of the United States should consider further
measures to support democracy (in Panama), including economic
sanctions, in the event Gen. Noriega continues to defy President
Devalle's lawful order,'' the resolution declared.
   It also called on the White House to study the impact on U.S.
energy supplies if Noriega reacts to possible economic sanctions by
shutting down the trans-Panama petroleum pipeline used to transport
Alaskan oil to the east coast of the United States.
   For Noriega, Panamanian independence from the United States has
been his principal line of defense in his struggle to survive. It
was a recurring theme at a pro-government demonstration in Panama
earlier this week when a crowd of 3,000 turned out to cheer Noriega.
   Shortly before Powell made his comments to reporters while
returning with Reagan from the NATO summit in Brussels, Belgium,
six Republicans and Democrats introduced the embargo bill.
   It would prohibit all trade and air travel between the two
countries and bar U.S. banks from transferring any funds to Panama
and its banking system.
   ``By stopping the transfer of funds from U.S. banks to Panama,
we go for the jugular,'' said Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., a
principal sponsor of the embargo plan.
   ``Because of Panama's heavy reliance on its economic ties with
the United States, the impact of a U.S. trade embargo would be
immediate, dramatic and devastating to Noriega and his cohorts,''
D'Amato said.
   A ban on Panamanian goods would paralyze a $412 million market
representing 60 percent of Panama's total exports, D'Amato said. A
ban on U.S. exports to Panama would affect a 30 percent slice of
all Panamanian imports, he said.
   Other sponsors of the embargo bill are Sens. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass.; David Durenberger, R-Minn.; Bob Graham, D-Fla.; John
Kerry, D-Mass.; and Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
   The administration has been sending mixed signals about the
degree to which it is willing to pressure Noriega, who is under
federal indictment on drug smuggling charges and who forced out the
constitutionally elected president last week.
   Some officials are sensitive to charges that the administration
has not done enough to oppose Noriega while others believe broader
U.S. interests require a cautious approach.
   In any case, there appears to be a consensus within the
administration that a trade embargo is too ambitious a step. The
administration is hopeful a combination of other pressures will
force an end to Noriega's rule.
   The issue of whether to withhold a $7 million U.S. payment due
in mid-March to Panama for canal-related fees and services has
underscored the split in the administration.
   Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams has said that the
administration will refuse to deliver the funds if such a request
is received from ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   But on Thursday, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
said no final decision has been made on that issue even though the
administration has had the request in hand since earlier in the
week.
   She acknowledged, however, that the request probably will be
honored.
   With an assist from the administration, Panamanian authorities
apparently have been denied access to official funds on deposit in
U.S. banks.
   At a news conference Thursday night at the Panamanian Embassy,
an attorney for Delvalle said federal courts in New York and Boston
have issued temporary restraining orders to prevent withdrawal of
the funds.
   ``We believe that whatever funds are in those institutions are
at this point frozen and cannot be transmitted to the Noriega
regime,'' said Daniel Resnick, a Washington attorney.
</TEXT>
