<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0462 03-04 0974</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt, Dukakis Duel Over Campaign Money; SC Poll Puts Bush
Ahead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush, Dukakis comments, Robertson court motion,
topping with 11 grafs, picking up in 6th graf pvs, Kemp battered,
and subbing 14th graf pvs, In the; cuts last 5 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the presidential candidates campaigned hard in the South
today, four days before the region's Super Tuesday primaries, but
Albert Gore Jr. detoured to Connecticut to raise money for a
Southern campaign that he said was turning in his direction.
   In Washington, meanwhile, attorneys for former Rep. Paul
McCloskey filed notice in court that they oppose Pat Robertson's
effort to drop a libel suit filed after McCloskey questioned his
war record.
   Unless a federal judge dismisses the case, as Robertson has
asked, a legal matter that has become a clear distraction for
Robertson could tie him up even further beginning on Tuesday when
the trial is scheduled to begin.
   In appearances today:
   _Vice President George Bush, campaigning in a state that votes
on Saturday, told a cheering crowd of 1,500 students in West
Columbia, S.C., ``Your state is going to have a mobilizing effect.
If we're successful in South Carolina, I think you'll be able to
say, the next president of the United States was here in our
school.''
   _Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, in Lubbock, Texas, told
voters in the biggest Super Tuesday state, he would to pursue
economic and energy policies to help Texas ``come back and come
back strong.''
   _Gore, in New Haven, Conn., raised an estimated $50,000 for his
campaign during a breakfast with state Democrats. He said there is
a shift going on to his advantage in Southern states, and ``the
undecided vote, which has been very large, is now breaking in our
direction.''
   Elsewhere, Richard Gephardt was gunning for Democratic rival
Dukakis over special-interest campaign contributions. And Robertson
lashed out Thursday night at what he called ``the real fanatics''
opposed to prayer in public schools.
   A poll published today gave Bush a big lead over Republican
opponent Bob Dole in South Carolina, whose GOP primary on Saturday
rings the opening bell on Tuesday's 20-state punchup.
   The Super Tuesday contests, with a prize of 1,307 Democratic
delegates and 712 Republican ones, are concentrated in the South.
   In South Carolina, Bush had the support of 49 percent of likely
voters to Dole's 26 percent, Robertson's 14 percent and Rep. Jack
Kemp's 7 percent, the Washington Post poll indicated.
   Kemp, battered by weak results in early contests, insisted he
has a shot at a respectable showing in South Carolina.
   ``I don't throw `Hail Mary' passes,'' said the former pro
football player as he campaigned Thursday in Columbia, S.C.
   Dole, who picked up the endorsement Thursday of former U.N.
ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick, conceded he was running behind Bush
in South Carolina, but pointed to bright spots that day _ a caucus
in Wyoming, and the election of 14 national GOP delegates in
Kansas, Dole's home state.
   All four Republicans were campaigning in South Carolina today.
   Robertson bought half an hour of television time on stations
around the state Thursday night, saying he wanted to ``set the
record straight'' about religious issues.
   The former television evangelist said he believes in the
separation of church and state but added: ``The real fanatics in
America today are those who try to tell us ... that we should tear
down the crosses and the manger scenes at Christmas time, that our
children should be denied the right to pray in school and that
traditional moral values are out of style.''
   Meanwhile, more polls today pointed to a strong Southern lead
for Bush, while Dukakis and Jesse Jackson dueled for support among
Democrats.
   A CBS-New York Times survey gave Bush a better than 2-1 lead
over Dole in 14 Southern and border states. A survey by Cable News
Network and USA Today had similar findings.
   In the CBS-Times poll, Jackson led Dukakis and Tennessee Sen.
Gore in the South. The CNN-USA Today survey suggested Dukakis and
Jackson were neck-in-neck in the region.
   Dukakis, in Texas, attacked Gephardt's plan for mandatory
retaliation against countries whose trade practices are judged
unfair.
   ``There's always somebody who suggests that: throw up the walls,
hunker down,'' the Massachusetts governor said.
   Gephardt, for his part, sought to turn the tables on Dukakis,
who has been running ads excoriating the Missouri congressman for
accepting campaign contributions from the political action
committees of banks, defense contractors, utilities and other big
businesses.
   ``I'll give back every penny of money that I've gotten from
political action funds if he will return the money to all the
people who have given him money who do business with or are
licensed by the state of Massachusetts,'' Gephardt said.
   Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach said the campaign has taken no
money from any corporate PACs or registered lobbyists in
Massachusetts.
   Gephardt told reporters at a news conference at the
Baltimore-Washington airport that he would unveil today ``a partial
list of some of the interests that have given money to his
campaign.''
   ``He's got appointees of his own state government who are
awarding contracts to many of the people who have given money to
his campaign. Is that a conflict of interest?'' he said.
   Gephardt said his votes in the House have not been dictated by
special interests.
   The Missouri congressman, who had the House's worst attendance
record for roll call votes last year, was absent Thursday night as
the House, by a 216-208 vote, rejected a package of $30 million in
``humanitarian'' aid for Nicaragua's Contras.
   When the House voted on Contra aid last month, just prior to the
Iowa caucuses, Gephardt delivered the weekly Democratic radio
address on the subject a few days beforehand and made himself a
prominent figure in the House debate.
</TEXT>
