<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Pottery     03-04 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe-Pottery,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Pottery Discovered at Historic Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British archaeologists discovered
fragments of 16th century Chinese porcelain at Iron Age ruins in
southeastern Zimbabwe, a newspaper reported Friday.
   The porcelain was unearthed by a 12-member research team at
Great Zimbabwe stone ruins of the 13th century tribal settlement
from which modern Zimbabwe draws its name. The find shows for the
first time that the site was occupied in the 16th century,
according to the newspaper, The Herald.
   Previous research indicated the ancestors of Zimbabwe's majority
Shona tribe abandoned the stone-built settlement by the year 1450.
   The Herald quoted archaeologists David Collett and Gwilyn Hughes
as saying the Chinese porcelain was probably brought to the African
interior by traders from Arab trading posts along the East African
coast.
   It proved that parts of the 1,720 acre ancient settlement, the
onetime capital of a vast tribal empire, were still occupied after
the year 1500, the expedition members said.
</TEXT>
