<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiquorStore-Alcoholics     03-04 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liquor Store-Alcoholics,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liquor Store To Open Near Home For Recovering Alcoholics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alabama Beverage Control Board is
making a mistake by planning to open a liquor store near a halfway
house for recovering alcoholics, say officials of the halfway
operation.
   The store, to open next month in downtown Tuscaloosa, is one
door away from the Phoenix House, which houses up to 17 men who are
trying to get off alcohol.
   ``I'm an alcoholic, and I went through the house eight years
ago,'' said Ted Jones, now its acting director. ``Looking back on
it, during that first year, if something had been that convenient,
I would have patronized it.''
   Most of the residents have been sober ``for only about six weeks
when they get here. And like I said, that first year of sobriety is
a volatile one,'' Jones said.
   The ABC board said that by the time it learned the Phoenix House
was so close to the store site it was too late because a 10-year
lease had been signed for the store.
   ``Had the board known about this previously, they never would
have approved the location,'' said Lucricia Foster, the ABC's
alcohol awareness coordinator. ``But now we're entered into a legal
contract with the builder, and we can't break it.''
   She said an ABC employee scouted the location when it was being
considered.
   ``In this instance, he was just not aware that the halfway house
was there. I know there are some signs marking it, but apparently
they weren't very noticeable,'' Miss Foster said.
   ``That sounds like some of the excuses we come up with for
drinking,'' said Alice McLean Stewart, chairwoman of the Phoenix
House board. ``It's raining, so I'm drinking, that kind of thing.
</TEXT>
