<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--DinosaurEgg     03-04 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Dinosaur Egg,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Enhanced Images Don't Prove Egg Contains Embryo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enhanced images of a 150 million-year-old,
fist-sized dinosaur egg did not establish whether there's an embryo
inside.
   Columbia Scientific Inc., a Maryland software company, enhanced
CAT-scan images of the egg, and the high-tech pictures revealed a
small piece of shell inside the egg, in addition to a polliwog-like
image of a possible embryo, said Brent Harker, a spokesman for
Brigham Young University.
   ``The polliwog image looks very lifelike, much more so than on
the unenhanced film,'' Harker said.
   But it would require cracking the egg to be sure, and that
``would destroy it. We're not going to do that,'' he said.
   The egg will soon be displayed at the university's Earth
Sciences Museum.
   Paleontologist Wade Miller announced last week the egg may
contain the oldest dinosaur embryo ever found, dating from the
Jurassic period, which ended about 145 million years ago. The egg
was unearthed last summer from a quarry in Utah.
   ``I think the chances are good we have an embryo inside,''
Miller said Wednesday, after studying the enhanced images.
</TEXT>
