<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     03-04 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humphrey Claims U.S. Aid To Afghan Rebels Is Dropping Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey claimed Friday that there
has been a sharp decline in the movement of U.S. aid to the
Afghanistan resistance fighters battling Soviet troops.
   The New Hampshire Republican, one of Capitol Hill's strongest
supporters of the Afghan rebels, told a news conference: ``I want
to know if this is negligence or a sell-out of the Afghan
resistance.''
   Last week, a top State Department official denied a similar
charge by members of the Afghan resistance.
   ``We will not abandon the Afghan resistance,'' said Robert Peck,
deputy assistanct secretary of state. He said U.S. support would go
ahead ``until that support is no longer needed.''
   Humphrey spoke a day after Afghanistan and Pakistan, which
represents the guerrillas, agreed on the main elements of a
U.N.-mediated peace accord that includes provisions for the
withdrawal of some 115,000 Soviet troops from Afghanistan within
nine months.
   That agreement ``makes it all the more imperative that we get
some airlifts under way,'' Humphrey said.
   Humphrey said one of his staff members, Michael Pillsbury, spent
four days in Peshawar last week talking to Afghan resistance
leaders and came back with the conclusions that ``the flow of
weapons has decreased markedly and suddenly.''
   Humphrey said Pillsbury ``was shown warehouses which he and I
had visited a year ago, which were bulging then, but which are all
but empty now.''
   The United States provides weapons such as Stinger anti-aircraft
missiles to the guerrillas, but the amount of military aid is
classified. However, government sources have said Congress
increased the level to $630 million this year.
   Rep. William H. Gray, D-Pa., asked the congressional General
Accounting Office last month to investigate reports that more than
$1 billion in covert CIA aid to the Afghan rebels has been diverted
to corrupt Pakistani officials or to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels,
congressional sources told The Associated Press.
   However, the GAO said it had no authority to subpoena material
from the CIA.
</TEXT>
