<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Appointments     03-04 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Appointments,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Announces Personnel Changes at Commerce, Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan plans to nominate Donna F.
Tuttle as deputy secretary of commerce, succeeding Clarence J.
Brown, the White House said Friday.
   Mrs. Tuttle, 40, has been undersecretary for travel and tourism
since 1983. Before that she was active in a number of Republican
political campaigns in California.
   The president also plans to nominate W. Allen Moore as
undersecretary of commerce for international trade administration,
succeeding S. Bruce Smart, the White House said.
   Moore, 43, has been chief of staff of the Senate Commerce
Committee since 1985 and before that was director of legislation
for Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo.
   In addition, the White House said, the president will nominate
Jan. W. Mares to be assistant secretary of commerce for import
administration, succeeding Paul Freedenberg.
   Mares, 51, has been senior policy analyst for the White House
Office of Policy Development since 1985 and before that was
assistant secretary of energy for international affairs and for
policy.
   The White House also said Reagan will nominate Edward R.
Hamberger, 37, a Washington lawyer, as assistant secretary of
transportation for governmental affairs. He succeeds Rebecca Range,
now director of the White House Office of Public Liaison.
   Gordon A. Smith, 53, will be nominated as assistant secretary of
defense for command, control, communications and intelligence,
succeeding Donald C. Latham. Smith has been deputy director of the
Strategic Defense Initiative Organization at the Pentagon since
1986.
</TEXT>
