<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0670 03-04 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michael Jackson Tour Thrills Madison Square Garden</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores time element to lead; no AMs separate planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Madison Square Garden audience Thursday
night forgot the Elephant Man's bones, plastic surgery and other
controversies and sat, mesmerized by Michael Jackson the performer.
   His high voice, with its controlled vibrato, was enthralling,
especially on ``She's Out of My Life,'' which followed a duet of
``I Just Can't Stop (Loving You).'' Video screens amplified
Jackson's stricken expression as the duet ended, with the female
singer walking away.
   The girlish face of Jackson, 29, often was shown large on the
screens that flanked the stage. But he made no attempt to maintain
a ``pretty'' expression, adopting a tearful, grieving pose several
times at the end of songs.
   Unlike his 1984 tour, in which Jackson was by far the most
graceful, dancing in a line with his brothers, this time he was
among equals, surrounded most of the time by four men obviously
well trained in dance.
   Jackson's kicks and spins were so fast the eye only registered
them after they were over. His pelvic thrusts, like different
jackets he donned, conveyed little sexual suggestion and much
childlike ``dressing up'' like grownups.
   The stagecraft looked simple but probably was far from it. There
were no giant structures, just the smooth front half of the stage
where Jackson sang and danced and a lower-level back of the stage
for four backup singers, seven musicians and modern music's mounds
of equipment.
   Much use was made of spotlights, sometimes on four sides of the
singer, each filled with his silhouette, and laser beams stabbed
the air. Once, Jackson ended a song and a circle of green lights
surrounded his feet.
   There were tricks, in which he seemed magically to move from one
place to another, as in 1984. In one, Jackson he stood on a ladder
and a cylinder drape dropped over him from above. His next
appearance was on the other side of the stage, where a
``gangplank'' lifted up and swung him out over the audience.
   Near the beginning of the evening, a man walked out on stage,
shook hands with Jackson and began to dance opposite him. Briefly,
it seemed part of the show, then a couple of large bodyguards
walked the intruder offstage, fairly unobtrusively. No abrupt moves
were made and the show's pacing wasn't dented.
   Spontaneity was in short supply but the well-planned
entertainment being offered was so fascinating that a viewer didn't
mind.
   Jackson's dancing and just trotting around stage is grace
itself. A couple times he did a robot sequence, but obviously is
playing down his ``signatures'' of one jeweled glove and the moon
walk. He used both only once, during ``Billie Jean.''
   Jackson's solo tour began in September in Japan. In America it
began Feb. 23 in Kansas City, Mo., and will run till mid-May. This
first of three shows at Madison Square Garden was a benefit for the
United Negro College Fund, to whose president Jackson presented a
check for $600,000 on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1250EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Media Bjt   03-04 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Media, Bjt,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Blocks Journalists From Major Troublespots</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel blocked journalists from major trouble
spots in the occupied territories Friday in an effort to limit news
reports of explosive Palestinian protests following weekly Moslem
prayers.
   The media clampdown came after complaints from politicians,
soldiers and settlers that the presence of journalists often
inflamed Arab protests in the West Bank and Gaza and caused more
violence.
   Despite the absence of cameras and notepads, Palestinian revolts
occurred Friday in most of the West Bank's major cities.
   Friday also marked the first time since the start of Arab unrest
on Dec. 8 that Israeli soldiers had blocked major roads and turned
back journalists from cities and refugee camps that typically are
the sites of post-prayer protests.
   Brig. Gen. Ephraim Lapid, the army's spokesman in Tel Aviv, told
The Associated Press the barricades did not represent an official
change in military policy.
   ``There are a few localities that are closed according to
existing policy which allows local commanders to shut an area based
on operational needs,'' Lapid said.
   The army declined to say how many cities and refugee camps were
off-limits to journalists. But in the West Bank, soldiers barred
reporters from more than half a dozen major cities. Only Bethlehem,
the traditional birthplace of Jesus, was open.
   ``This is a closed military area,'' one soldier told an AP
photographer outside Nablus, 40 miles north of Jerusalem. ``If you
don't leave now, we will arrest you.''
   An army jeep then followed the photographer's car for about
three miles, apparently to make sure it was headed toward Jerusalem.
   Journalists were permitted to enter the Gaza Strip, but kept
from the area around Gaza City's main mosque and the major
commercial street.
   The decision to bar journalists from the occupied territories
drew mixed reviews from Israelis.
   ``The right to see bang-bang is not protected by the First
Amendment,'' said Zeev Chafets, a former director of the Government
Press Office and a native of Pontiac, Mich.
   ``I would support closing off the West Bank to the world press
in a minute, but keeping it open to the Israeli press,'' Chafets
said in an interview. ``The world press is only an asterisk here.
To me, what's important is my press.''
   But Israel Peleg, also a former director of the Government Press
Office, disagreed.
   ``It is better to let the media operate freely and without any
obstacles than to be depicted in the world as a country that
restricts journalists,'' Peleg told The AP.
   ``Israel's image may be immediately harmed by these pictures (of
protests), but in the long run, the fact that these pictures can be
circulated speaks for Israel's democracy,'' he said.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of the right-wing Likud bloc twice
this week publicly referred to the possibility of restricting media
access and accused journalists of bias against Israel.
   Some soldiers serving in the West Bank also have said
journalists make their jobs more difficult. Angry settlers in
Hebron attacked foreign photographers Thursday, accusing them of
impeding troops' efforts to arrest an Arab who stabbed a
15-year-old settler.
   Four soldiers were arrested after a CBS News crew photographed
them beating Palestinians with rocks last week.
   But Foreign Minister Shimon Peres of the left-leaning Labor
Party has warned that barring media access to the occupied
territories will simply spark rumors of atrocities that journalists
will be unable to refute from on-the-scene reporting.
   Other Israeli officials have warned that denying media access
could lead to unfavorable comparisons between Israel and South
Africa, which the government has been sensitive about.
   In South Africa, police can declare areas off-limits to
journalists on the spot and demand that all reporters leave. In
Israel, local commanders also are permitted to declare an area
closed if they deem the presence of journalists will make the
army's job more difficult.
   In addition to limiting access, Israel has military censors who,
in an effort to prevent what they consider to be incitement,
carefully control Arabic-language newspapers based in Jerusalem
which circulate in the occupied territories.
   But the censorship controls on foreign press coverage of the
occupied territories have been less stringent.
   Robert Slater, chairman of the Foreign Press Association, said
he was ``appalled but not surprised'' by Israel's decision to bar
journalists from large portions of the territories Friday.
   ``From the prime minister's statements and comments by Cabinet
members, it appeared increasingly likely the government would do
something to keep us away from this story,'' Slater said in an
interview. ``We have fought it for three months, and we will
continue to fight it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1254EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w US-EuropePoll     03-04 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>US-Europe Poll,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Indicates Americans View Ties with Europe as Important</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vast majority of Americans view ties with
Europe as very important for the United States, but at the same
time they recognize that trans-Atlantic links have waned over the
past 10 years, a poll commissioned by the European Economic
Community shows.
   The Gallup Poll of ``national opinion leaders'' and the general
public, published in the March edition of the EEC magazine,
``Europe,'' also shows the majority of respondents believe U.S.
troops must be stationed in Europe to prevent a Soviet attack.
   Of those polled, 86 percent said U.S. ties with Europe ``matter
a great deal,'' compared with 65 percent who answered the same way
in a 1973 poll commissioned by the magazine.
   Asked how today's ties compare with those of 10 years ago, 33
percent of the respondents said they were closer, but 53 percent
said they were ``not as close.''
   The United States should strengthen its links with Europe,
according to 53 percent of those polled. Thirty-one percent favor
the level of current ties and 11 percent support reduced ties with
the continent.
   Although about one-third of the respondents said West European
countries engage in unfair trading practices, both the general
public and national opinion leaders _ which the magazine defined as
business and academic leaders and policy makers _ cited Japan as an
unfair trading partner more than twice as often as the countries of
Western Europe.
   For example, 30 percent of the public said they view Europe as
an unfair partner, while 65 percent cited Japan.
   Respondents are more likely to know about the U.S. trade deficit
with Japan than about the one with Western Europe, according to the
poll. The 1987 deficit with Japan was $59.8 billion _ the largest
chunk of the $171.2 billion overall deficit _ while the deficit
with Europe was $30.2 billion.
   Of those polled, 47 percent said they ``mostly agree'' that
Europe is a good market for the United States, while 31 percent
said they ``completely agree.''
   Those polled generally said they respect European achievements
in arts, but gave higher credit to U.S. achievements in science,
encouragement of individual creativity and equal opportunity.
   Among the general public, 54 percent said the United States
provides an excellent education for its citizens, while 21 percent
said Europe has a good educational system. But among the opinion
leaders, 33 percent said the United States provides an excellent
education and 34 percent credited Europe with the same service.
   The poll, conducted late last year by telephone, surveyed 1,300
adult Americans and 387 opinion leaders. The poll results had a 3
percentage point margin of error.
</TEXT>
