<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DavisVerdict     03-04 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Davis Verdict,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Acquits Davis In Shootings Of Four Suspected Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man arrested after a 17-day manhunt was
acquitted in the execution-style murders of four suspected drug
dealers but was returned to jail to await trial next month on
charges of attempted murder of police officers.
   The jury returned its verdict against Larry Davis, 21, on
Thursday night after nine days of deliberations.
   Davis' attorneys, including William M. Kunstler, argued that he
was framed and police tried to kill him because he knew about
police corruption involving drugs in the South Bronx.
   Besides the trial stemming from the shootout with 27 police
officers, Davis also faces separate trials for two other murders.
   The Nov. 19, 1986 shoot-out, in which six police officers were
wounded but Davis escaped unharmed from a Bronx apartment, set off
the manhunt. Police said they had gone to the apartment to question
Davis about the deaths of the alleged drug dealers.
</TEXT>
