<DOCNO> AP880304-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TV-Sweeps     03-04 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Sweeps,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Wins February Sweeps With Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Winter Olympics won the February rating
sweeps for ABC, putting it into second place for the season and
breaking NBC's 11-sweeps win streak.
   Based on A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings for the 28-day sweeps period,
ABC won with an average prime-time rating of 17.3 and a 27 share,
thanks to the average 19.3 rating for the Olympics, which dominated
59 percent of prime time.
   NBC, which won each of the 12 nights that didn't include
Olympics coverage, came in second with a 15.9 and 25. CBS was third
with 13.8 and 21.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   Unless CBS beats ABC by 1.5 rating points each week for the
remaining seven weeks of the television season, it will end the
season in third place for the first time ever.
   February is one of four sweeps months each year when rating
companies measure local station audiences for use in negotiating
advertising rates. To help affiliates, the networks load their
schedules with special programming.
   NBC and CBS insist the February sweeps will have less impact on
local advertising rates than other sweeps, because stations can
refuse to negotiate based on ratings for the unusual Olympics
programming.
   Nevertheless, the win was a boost for ABC, which hasn't won a
sweeps since 1984. The games were also a boost for the networks in
general, since the three-network share of the viewing audience rose
to 75 percent from 71 percent.
   The Olympics also apparently helped ABC's ``World News Tonight''
take the top spot in the network evening news race for three weeks.
But the games didn't help ``Good Morning America'' out of the No. 2
position it has occupied behind NBC's ``Today'' show for 15 weeks
in a row.
   Of the four miniseries that aired during the month, ``Elvis and
Me'' on ABC was the highest-rated, with a 24.4. ``Windmills of the
Gods'' on CBS was second with an 18.2 and CBS' ``Bluegrass'' was
third with 18.0. NBC's ``Noble House'' was last with a 16.3. All
were two-part, four-hour miniseries, except ``Noble House,'' which
aired eight hours over four nights.
   The top-rated specials of the months, not counting the Olympics,
were: ``Super Bloopers'' on NBC with a rating of 21.3; the special
prime-time ``Late Night with David Letterman'' on NBC, with a
rating of 19.3; the premiere of the new NBC series ``Day by Day''
with 18.6; the ``Miss USA'' pageant on CBS with a 16.2; and ``The
Wizard of Oz'' on CBS with a 15.3.
   The top-rated movies of the sweeps were: ``Hostage'' on CBS with
a 19.4; ``Perry Mason'' on NBC with 17.4; ``Moving Target'' on NBC
with 17.2; ``Police Academy II'' on NBC with 16.7; and ``Return of
Desperado'' on NBC with 16.0.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TibetanMonk     03-04 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibetan Monk,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tibetan Leader Confirms Monk Died In Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking Tibetan official confirmed Friday
that a Buddhist monk jailed for advocating Tibetan independence had
died in prison, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   Xinhua said Gyamco, vice-chairman of the Tibetan Autonomous
Region government, told foreign reporters in Tibet that Lobsang
Wangchuk died last year of lung cancer while serving an 18-year
term.
   Tibetan exile groups in India said last year that Wangchuk died
Nov. 4 of injuries suffered in a beating after he refused to admit
he was wrong to support Tibetan independence. He was 74.
   At the time, Chinese authorities in Beijing dismissed the report
of Wangchuk's death as ``sheer fabrication.''
   Xinhua's report did not say why authorities initially denied the
report. However, his death came during a time of great tension in
the remote Himalayan region. One month earlier, three anti-Chinese
demonstrations were led by Buddhist monks and at least 14 people
were killed.
   ``In the People's Republic of China citizens can freely air
their views,'' the report quoted Gyamco as saying. ``But advocating
independence for any part of the nation is a crime.''
   Wangchuk was first arrested in 1959, nine years after Chinese
troops entered Tibet, for taking part in an uprising against
Chinese rule. Tibet's god-king, the Dalai Lama, fled to India
during that uprising.
   According to exiled Tibetan groups, Wangchuk was detained
without trial until 1962, when he was sentenced to a 10-year term.
He was released at the end of his term but was arrested again in
1981.
   Xinhua said Wangchuk ``renewed his splittist activities by
distributing leaflets advocating the independence of Tibet'' and
was sentenced to three years in jail. The term was extended to 18
years because he refused to change his views, the report said.
   Splittist is a term coined by the Chinese to refer to
individuals who advocate independence for regions in China.
   Xinhua also quoted Gyamco as saying last year's protests ``had
no impact at all'' on China's policy of allowing religious freedom
in Tibet.
   ``On the contrary, it (the policy) will be more effectively
implemented,'' it quoted him as saying.
   Tibetans traditionally are deeply religious, and before the
Chinese Red Army entered in 1950 were governed by a theocracy
headed by the Dalai Lama and the Buddhist monasteries.
   The Chinese smashed the temporal power of the monasteries and
for many years banned public worship. Thousands of monasteries were
destroyed and their monks forced to marry during the 1966-76
Cultural Revolution.
   Since then, public worship has been restored and some
monasteries have been rebuilt. However, most monks and many lay
Tibetans remain hostile to Chinese rule.
   An eight-day Great Prayer Festival that ended this week in
Lhasa, Tibet's capital, was boycotted by many monks because of the
heavy Chinese police presence. Attendance by pilgrims also was
sharply down, according to Tibetan sources and Westerners who
observed the festival this year and in the past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0141 </DOCNO>
