<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Australia-Weinberger     03-04 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Weinberger,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weinberger, Wife To Represent U.S. at Australian Bicentennial
Events</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger
will serve as President Reagan's official representative in
Australia this month during the country's bicentennial celebration,
it was announced Friday.
   He will be accompanied by his wife Jane, visiting Canberra,
Melbourne, Brisbane and Sydney from March 16-22.
   The Weinbergers were married in Australia in 1942 while both
were serving in the U.S. Army.
   A White House statement said the couple will participate in ``a
wide range of activities underscoring U.S. admiration and
appreciation of Australia at this historic time.''
   While in Australia, Weinberger will meet with Prime Minister Bob
Hawke and other government leaders.
   In connection with the bicentennial, the United States has made
a $5 million gift to the Australian National Maritime Museum. In
addition, the U.S. Coast Guard's sailing vessel, Eagle, will
participate in the parade of tall ships in Sydney Harbor on
Australia Day. A U.S. pavilion will operate at Brisbane's World
Expo '88, which will run from April through October.
</TEXT>
