<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Panama-FlaGuard     03-04 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Fla Guard,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Army National Guard Heading To Panama For Training</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six hundred Florida National Guard
troops will go to Panama for a two-week ``Total Warrior'' training
exercise despite riots and a general strike there, officials
announced.
   ``The political turmoil has no effect on the training there,''
Florida Guard spokesman Maj. Ken Forrester said Thursday. ``This
has been scheduled a year in advance, and we see no reason to
change it.''
   U.S. Army Maj. Gen. Bernard Loeffke in Panama sent assurances
Wednesday that troops training in the Canal Zone would be safe,
said Forrester from Guard headquarters in St. Augustine.
   ``And with 10,000 regular Army troops down there, I can't see us
doing anything but the training we have scheduled,'' said Forrester.
   Troops from the 3rd Battalion, 124th Infantry based in Panama
City, Fla., won't be allowed off U.S. bases during the jungle
training, he said.
   ``There's been some concern, but I haven't had any hysterical
moms saying their son or husband isn't going,'' Lt. Charles Boss
said.
   During Total Warrior _ 12 days of mock raids and ambushes _
troops would have little time for sightseeing, he said.
   ``We're going to fly into Howard Air Force Base and go directly
into the jungle,'' Boss said. ``After 12 days ... they'll only be
interested in a shower, a cold beer and getting back to sleep.''
   Two Florida Guard battalions have trained in Panama for each of
the last three years, Forrester said.
   The battalion troops are to leave Tyndall Air Force Base near
this Gulf Coast resort area March 12 and return March 27.
   The unit will be the first U.S. troops sent to Panama for
training since then-President Eric Arturo Delvalle's failed Feb. 25
effort to oust strongman Gen. Manuel Noriega. Panama's de facto
leader was indicted last month by Tampa and Miami federal grand
juries which accused Noriega of involvement with drug dealing.
</TEXT>
