<HEAD>Odom To Head NASA's Space Station Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James B. Odom, a veteran engineer with the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration, has been appointed
head of the agency's most ambitious program in the next decade:
putting a manned space station into Earth orbit.
   Odom, currently director of science and engineering at the
Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala., will succeed
Andrew J. Stofan, who is leaving NASA on April 1.
   Odom headed NASA's space telescope project, was actively
involved in developing Earth satellites and unmanned space probes
and guided the external tank project for the first space shuttle.
