<2ND_LINE>AM-Commerce Anniversary,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commerce Department Celebrates 75th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department celebrated its 75th
anniversary Friday as Commerce Secretary C. William Verity cut a
10-foot-by-6-foot cake and President Reagan issued a special
proclamation.
   ``This moment is an historic snapshot in time of the development
of our government which goes back over 200 years,'' Verity said at
a celebration attended by an estimated 1,600 agency employees.
   Reagan issued a proclamation declaring Friday as Department of
Commerce Day.
   ``The employees of the Department of Commerce have always
reflected the finest traditions of public service. That was surely
true of the department's late secretary, Malcolm Baldrige, and our
present secretary, C. William Verity Jr,'' Reagan said in the
proclamation.
   Verity, who became commerce secretary in 1987 after the death of
Baldrige in a freak horse-riding accident, was joined by one of his
secretaries, Willa Petty, in leading the audience in a rendition of
``Happy Birthday'' before cutting the cake, a replica of the
Commerce Department headquarters.
   Ms. Petty was a stand-in for singer Pearl Bailey, who had been
scheduled to preside over the proceedings but who canceled at the
last minute.
</TEXT>
