<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1342EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TimberProbe     03-04 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Probe,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Six In Timber Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six men have been indicted on 23 felony counts of
fraud and conspiracy, alleging they stole timber worth ``hundreds
of thousands of dollars'' from the Olympic National Forest.
   Among those indicted late Thursday are the former owner and crew
chief of one of the most powerful independent logging operations on
the Olympic Peninsula, Glenn T. Anderson Inc.
   After a four-year investigation, the government accused the six
of stealing Forest Service timber from the national forest,
conspiracy to steal, filing false statements and conflict of
interest.
   Federal court documents filed last October allege the thefts to
be in the range of ``hundreds of thousands of dollars.''
   Court files accuse five of the men of devising scams to cheat
the Forest Service of revenue on logs harvested off public land.
The alleged scams included forging log brands, sawing up unscaled
logs, and recycling log-truck load identifier tickets, the
documents say.
   The documents also say one defendant, Gregory B. Maurer, 43, of
Aberdeen, former U.S. Forest Service timber sale administrator on
the Olympic Forest's Quinault Ranger District, allegedly looked the
other way to allow the scams.
   The indictment also says Maurer ran a secret forest cleanup
company that catered to the logging operators he was supposed to
regulate as timber sale administrator.
   The charges carry maximum penalties of up to 10 years in prison
and fines of up to $250,000.
</TEXT>
