<DOCNO> AP880304-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SubwayRevolt Bjt   03-04 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Subway Revolt, Bjt,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Called to Quell Second Commuter Revolt This Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were summoned to quell a revolt by angry
commuters who vandalized and jammed the doors of a delayed subway
train, and refused to get off in protest, authorities said Friday.
   It was the second such mutiny in the Underground this week.
   ``We got the message the first time. This is only making things
worse,'' said David Morris, a spokesman for London Regional
Transport, which operates the massive system.
   The spectacle of rebellion by London's usually reserved and
mild-mannered commuters is making headline news in the capital, and
a member of Parliament says he will raise the issue in the House of
Commons.
   Morris said the latest incident was ``pretty close to an
out-of-control act of vandalism,'' while one of the passengers
involved said commuters had grown fed up with delays and shoddy
stations.
   The first whiff of trouble came Tuesday night when, in what
London Regional Transport called unprecedented behavior, passengers
at Finchley Central station on the Northern Line refused a request
to get off the train prematurely and forced the driver to take them
to their destination.
   The second incident occurred at the same station. In both cases,
the trains had been delayed by track defects and passengers were
told to get off and catch the next train.
   The first incident ended in peaceful victory for the commuters
without police intervention. The second incident, by all accounts,
was nastier.
   ``Passengers ripped off pieces of the train and used them to jam
the doors,'' said Morris. ``Apparently there was much jubilation.
Undoubtedly it was inspired by what happened on Tuesday. The staff
called the Transport Police who ordered the passengers off the
train, and they obeyed.''
   London's Evening Standard newspaper quoted passenger Faz Razeen,
34, a leader of the revolt, as saying: ``People were really worked
up and annoyed.'' Some had waited more than half an hour for their
train, he said.
   Morris conceded that half-hour waits were not unusual. ``We are
trying to do something. But if people don't use their common sense
the whole line will come to a stop. Whatever sympathy they got over
the first incident will soon be lost.''
   Morris insisted that in both incidents, the passengers behaved
selfishly because by trying to force their trains to take them to
their destinations, they made passengers at other stations wait
longer.
   But the Standard said this response ``betrays an arrogance which
ought to be replaced at once by better management on the Misery
Line.''
   John Marshall, a Conservative Party lawmaker and Northern Line
commuter, said the Northern Line ``is the nearest thing to hell on
Earth,'' and promised to raise the matter in Parliament.
   Replied Morris: ``When you're running 460 trains a day for 2.5
million passengers, something always goes wrong.'' He said
Thursday's delays were caused by a beer can that was thrown onto
the line, jamming a track mechanism.
   Meanwhile, the Standard tracked down the man said to have
started Tuesday night's rebellion by quietly declaring his refusal
to get off the train.
   Described by fellow-passengers as a mild-mannered, well-dressed
man, he turned out to be 49-year-old civil servant Barry Blain.
   ``I am not a natural rebel,'' the Standard quoted him as saying,
``but like a lot of my fellow commuters I am fed up with our
treatment on the Northern Line.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1333EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Violence 2ndLd-Writethru a0678 03-04 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Violence, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0678, a0692,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Says 31 Killed in Azerbaijan Rioting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines previous and adds background. RESTORES byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-one people were killed in ethnic rioting in
the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait, the state-run news agency Tass
reported today.
   It was the first time the official media reported deaths in
ethnic violence between Azeris and Armenians in the two southern
Soviet republics. Dissident sources had reported that as many as 20
people died in the Sumgait riots.
   The rioting erupted Sunday in the industrial city 19 miles
northwest of the Azerbaijani capital of Baku. Government spokesmen
had previously acknowledged people were killed in the rioting, but
refused to say how many. A television worker in Baku had said one
or two people were killed.
   The Tass dispatch blamed the Sunday killings on ``hooligan
elements provoked by disorder.''
   Trouble between the Azeris, who are predominantly Shiite
Moslems, and Armenians, who are Christian, began early last month
with a dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh, a region in Azerbaijan just
north of Iran and east of Turkey. More than three-quarters of the
population is Armenian, but it was made part of Azerbaijan in 1923.
   Armenians are demanding that the region be made part of the
republic of Armenia. Azeris opposed the move and violence has
ensued.
   Earlier today, an Armenian nationalist said his sister and at
least two other people were killed in ethnic violence in Armenia.
   ``Unstable, immature people, falling under the influence of
false rumors about the events in Nagorno-Karabakh and Armenia,
involved themselves in lawsless actions,'' Tass said. ``Criminal
elements took part in violent activities and looting. From their
hands, 31 people perished.''
   An English version of the Tass story said the dead included
``members of various nationalities, old men and women.''
   On Thursday Gennady I. Gerasimov, chief spokesman for the Soviet
Foreign Ministry in Moscow, gave the first official confirmation of
deaths during the riots in Azerbaijan, but would not say how many
people were killed.
   On Tuesday, he said he could not confirm reports from Armenian
activists that up to 20 people were killed in Sumgait, in
Azerbaijan. But he added, ``There was hooliganism, and there can be
deaths in such cases.''
   The first official hint of deaths in the ethnic unrest came Feb.
24, when non-voting Politburo member Vladimir I. Dolgikh said on
Armenian television that ``in Nagorno-Karabakh, the matter has gone
so far as confrontations between Armenians and Azerbaijanis, and
there have been casualties.''
   Street rallies began Feb. 13 in Nagorno-Karabakh and later
spread to Yerevan, the capital of Armenia, where dissidents said
more than 1 million people demonstrated. On Feb. 19 rioting spread
to Sumgait.
   Mosef Gorgisyan telephoned The Associated Press in Moscow to say
his sister, Avetik Gorgisyan, 32, was stabbed today and two other
people were shot in their homes in the Armenian city of Kirovakan.
He said the three were killed by Azeris.
   He said six people, all ethnic Azeris, were arrested in the
killings.
   Gerasimov said he could neither confirm nor deny the report
because he had no information about renewed violence in the region.
   Gorgisyan, 26, is a member of an unsanctioned Armenian
organization called the Alliance for National Self-Determination.
   Gorgisyan said his sister was killed today, but the telephone
was cut off before he could say when the two shootings reportedly
occurred. He said demonstrations had been held in Kirovakan earlier.
   He said he saw the aftermath of three slayings in Kirovakan. He
said he had heard 13 other people were killed but could not confirm
those reports.
   Gorgisyan said his grandmother and other relatives were in his
sister's house when the stabbing occurred.
   An official at the Ministry of Internal Affairs in Yerevan said,
``There were no deaths anywhere in the republic.'' The ministry
includes the police forces of the region. The official refused to
give his name.
   An official answering the telephone at police headquarters in
Kirovakan refused comment. ``I am not obligated to say anything to
foreigners about what happens here,'' said the official, who
declined to give his name.
   Kirovakan is a city of 137,000 people about 35 miles north of
the Armenian capital of Yerevan. Western reporters have not been
allowed to travel to the region.
   Since Mikhail S. Gorbachev became Communist Party chief, the
most deaths previously reported in ethnic unrest occurred in Alma
Ata, the capital of the Central Asian republic of Kazakhstan.
   Up to 3,000 people rioted in that city Dec. 17-18, 1986, to
protest the appointment of a Russian to replace an ethnic Kazakh as
local party chief. Soviet media reported that two people were
killed, 200 injured and dozens arrested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
