<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   03-04 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlement Seems Emerging, But Questions Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A settlement aimed at ending the war in
Afghanistan appeared to be taking shape Friday, and the latest
round of peace talks were recessed while Pakistan decided if it was
willing to deal with the Soviet-backed Afghan government.
   Still open, too, was the question of whether Afghanistan's
Moslem resistance groups would drop their fierce opposition to
future power-sharing with Afghan President Najib.
   After a short session of the U.N.-sponsored talks Friday,
Pakistan's chief negotiator, acting Foreign Minister Zain Noorani,
flew back to Islamabad for a rare meeting between the government
and leaders of the political opposition.
   Pakistan represents the Afghan guerrillas in the negotiations.
   The meeting in Pakistan was convened by Prime Minister Mohammad
Khan Junejo to try to reach a consensus on whether a settlement
should be signed with Najib's government.
   It was the first time the government sought such direct contact
with the opposition since President Mohammad Zia-Ul Haq seized
power in a 1977 coup.
   Before leaving, Noorani reaffirmed Pakistan's position that a
settlement must include formation of a transitional government
replacing Najib's.
   Pakistan does not recognize Najib's government and has said it
must be replaced if 5 million Afghan refugees living in Pakistan
and Iran are to return safely home.
   Most of Pakistan's opposition parties have urged the government
to sign an accord clearing the way for the withdrawal of Soviet
troops from Afghanistan, then worry about a political settlement
later.
   Diego Cordovez, the U.N. mediator who has been the go-between in
the nearly 6-year-old talks, told reporters that Thursday's
agreement on a nine-month timetable for the withdrawal of the
Soviet troops represented a ``significant step'' toward a final
political settlement.
   He stopped short of saying it was complete but exuded confidence
that remaining issues would be resolved, noting that all sides
showed ``determination and political will.''
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has said that if an accord is
signed by March 15, the estimated 115,000 Red Army troops would
begin leaving Afghanistan in mid-May. The Soviets intervened in
1979.
   Afghanistan has accused Pakistan of ``undermining'' peace
prospects by linking the withdrawal to formation of a transitional
government.
   The head of the Afghan delegation, Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil,
told a U.N. Human Rights Commission on Friday that his nation's
concept of a multiparty government of ``national reconciliation''
has the ``vigorous support of our people.''
   Opponents say that concept is designed to cement the leading
role of Najib's governing People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   Wakil said ``political hysteria'' made the opposition reject all
attempts by Kabul to launch a ``constructive dialogue.'' Instead,
he said, ``extremist bands'' relying on mounting supplies of
American and British arms had stepped up their ``destructive and
terrorist deeds.''
   The United States has been largely non-committal on the issue
and some sources close to the talks said there is a growing feeling
in Pakistan that Washington's prime interest is in sealing a deal
before the Moscow summit.
   Cordovez indicated Friday he is increasingly confident that
there will be an eventual compromise on the future shape of the
Kabul government.
   He said he was in ``close contact'' with superpower
representatives on the problem and was confident the Afghan
resistance will ``change its attitude once a settlement is signed.''
</TEXT>
