<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh     03-04 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Plans New Action Following Ershad Win in Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad's
Jatiya Party gained a lopsided majority in Parliament in an
election that brought new calls for protests Friday from opposition
leaders.
   An opposition coalition of 21 parties scheduled rallies for a
``day of protest'' Saturday and denounced Thursday's balloting,
which they boycotted.
   At least 13 people were reported killed and more than 300 were
injured in election violence, and reporters who visited polling
places found evidence of a low voter turnout and widespread vote
rigging.
   With results announced Friday for 218 of the 299 Parliament
seats up for grabs, the president's party had won 194.
   A coalition of 73 small factions known as the Combined
Opposition Parties won 12, two other small parties had one each,
and independents won seven. Voting was canceled in one district
where a candidate was slain. The other 30 seats in the 330-seat
Parliament are reserved for women, who will be chosen later.
   In the 1986 elections, Jatiya won 157 seats, but its majority
rose to 210 after wheeling and dealing with independents and the
addition of the 30 seats for women. Those traditionally go to the
governing party.
   The vote did not end the stalemate between Ershad and his
leading opponents, Sheik Hasina of the Awami League and Khaleda Zia
of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party.
   The women vowed to persist in their campaign against Ershad, and
Ms. Hasina declared, ``We will topple this corrupt government.''
They have been organizing anti-Ershad demonstrations and strikes
since Nov. 10.
   Bangladesh journalists decided to stop work for a night to
protest government restrictions on the press that were imposed
under a national state of emergency in November.
   Reazuddin Ahmed, president of the Bangladesh Federal Union of
Journalists representing about 1,500 journalists across the
country, said government officials had been phoning newspapers each
night and telling them not to publish news of anti-government
activities.
   He said they were told not to publish news of a low voter
turnout or election violence.
   Most newspapers seemed to have kept low profile about reporting
violence or election fraud.
   The action will result in non-publication of about 15
Dhaka-based dailies and half a dozen more outside Dhaka on
Saturday. Two national news agencies will also be affected.
   Ershad said he expected the new Parliament to serve out its full
five-year term.
   Ershad dissolved the Parliament last December, 3{ years early,
in a move to compromise with the opposition. The opposition
declared a boycott of the election.
   The former lieutenant took power in a bloodless coup in 1982 and
was elected president in 1986.
</TEXT>
