<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Palau-Heroin     03-04 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palau-Heroin,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Probing Corruption Chargers in Pacific Trust Territory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Interior Committee is investigating
possible government corruption in the U.S. trust territory of
Palau, including allegations that senior Palau officials may be
involved in heroin smuggling.
   The probe was disclosed this week by Chairman Morris Udall,
D-Ariz., and Del. Ron de Lugo, D-Virgin Islands, chairman of the
Interior subcommittee on insular and international affairs.
   The lawmakers, in statements not disputed by Palauan or U.S.
officials, quoted the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration as
saying that the Pacific islands ``are being used to transship
heroin from Southeast Asia to the U.S.''
   In a letter sent Wednesday to Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla.,
chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Committee, Udall and de Lugo
said ``several senior Palauan government officials have been
identified to us as being connected to this drug trade.''
   The letter cited no basis for the accusation against the
unidentified officials. Jeff Farrow, staff director for de Lugo's
subcommittee, said: ``It's coming from our investigation. That's
all we can say at this point.''
   Haruo Willter, Palau's acting Washington representative,
acknowledged that his country has a drug problem, ``the same as the
United States.'' As for the involvement of senior officials, he
said: ``These allegations are made by individuals. I have seen no
specific accusations with names.''
   Howard Hills, counsel for interagency affairs at the State
Department, said: ``We've been aware of allegations of drug
trafficking _ including allegations of officials being involved _
for years, and we don't understand why the Interior Committee is
treating them as new.''
   The letter said the committee investigation also involves
allegations of corruption and bribery among high-ranking Palau
officials, misappropriation of federal and local funds and violence
against Palauans opposed to a long-term compact linking the United
States and Palau.
   Palau and the Reagan administration are pressing Congress to
approve a resolution to implement the compact, leading to the end
of a U.N.-sanctioned trusteeship the United States has exercised
over Palau for 40 years. Palau is the world's last United Nations
trust territory.
   Under the arrangement, the United States would provide economic
assistance and military protection for Palau, which the Pentagon
sees as a backup location in case this country loses its military
bases in the Philippines.
   The Interior Committee has made no move toward voting on the
resolution, which was endorsed Thursday by two subcommittees of the
Foreign Affairs Committee. There was no mention of the drug
allegations before their votes.
   About 14,000 people live on the eight permanently inhabited
islands of Palau, which comprises more than 200 islands in the
Caroline chain. Most of the inhabitants live in Koror, the capital,
some 4,450 miles southwest of Honolulu and 720 miles south of Guam.
   In a letter last October to de Lugo, DEA Administrator John Lawn
said ``it appears that Palau's primary involvement in international
drug trafficking is as a transshipment point for Southeast Asian
heroin being smuggled to the United States.''
   Lawn said ``marijuana is grown freely throughout'' Palau and
that there may be more than 400 heroin addicts in Palau _ far
higher than the percentage of addicts in the United States.
   Hills said Palau, with help requested from the DEA and Interior
and State departments, is trying to combat the problem. He said
that 25 marijuana and heroin suspects were arrested in ``a major
bust'' Tuesday in Palau.
   About the accusation that senior officials could be involved
with heroin smuggling, Hills said, ``The issue of who's involved is
not going to be commented on because it's under investigation by
the government of Palau.''
   He said Congress should move to sever the trusteeship because
Palauan independence and increased U.S. aid would give the islands'
government more resources to combat its problems.
   Udall and de Lugo also cited last summer's violence in Palau
surrounding a plebiscite in which a majority of Palauans voted to
change their constitution's strong prohibition on nuclear weapons
in their country.
   Palauan dissidents have questioned the legality of the
plebiscite. A lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of the vote
was withdrawn because of government-fostered intimidation,
dissidents have told Congress.
   Udall and de Lugo said they won't act on the resolution until
Palau's judiciary rules on the plebiscite's legality or the
dissidents say they won't renew the lawsuit.
   The resolution approved by the Foreign Affairs subcommittees
says the Reagan administration can implement the compact with Palau
unless a legal challenge to the plebiscite is pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
