<DOCNO> AP880304-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1413EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CitrusTour     03-04 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citrus Tour,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials From 3 States Inspect Florida's Canker-Treatment Methods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture officials from Arizona, Texas
and Louisiana came to see for themselves whether Florida was doing
all it can to prevent citrus canker from traveling in fruit
shipments to their states.
   ``We are trying to assess the level of confidence we can place
on the procedures being taken so that we can determine what
inspection methods we need in our state,'' said Arizona's director
of agriculture and horticulture, Ivan J. Shields.
   Shields joined Florida Agriculture Commissioner Doyle Conner and
regulatory and technical officials from the two other states in a
tour of Florida citrus nurseries, groves and packinghouse
facilities in the Indian River and interior areas of Florida's
citrus belt.
   ``Florida fruit presents no threat to their citrus industries,
and we want to assure them of that,'' Conner said in Orlando prior
to their departure in three small airplanes to Fort Pierce, Winter
Haven, Frostproof and Lake Wales.
   Conner invited the representatives from the three states and
California as a partial answer to embargoes on Florida fresh fruit
shipments imposed by Texas and Louisiana shortly after the U.S.
Department of Agriculture last month lifted a 3-year-old ban on
Florida shipments to other citrus-growing areas.
   Florida Citrus Mutual, an organization representing 12,000
growers, and Tuxedo Fruit Co. of Fort Pierce went into federal
court and obtained a temporary injunction against the Texas
embargo. The first Florida truckloads of fruit were expected to
reach Texas this weekend.
   Conner said Florida also was prepared to challenge a Louisiana
ban from the southern part of the state, where about 1,000 acres of
fruit is grown.
   California, which did not send a representative to Florida on
Friday, and Arizona have not interfered with Florida shipments.
   The USDA ban was lifted after a joint state-federal scientific
task force determined that there was little threat to other
citrus-growing states by the Florida nursery strain of the tree and
fruit disease, which resulted in the voluntary destruction of 20
million young trees in the last three years.
   John W. Impson, state entomologist for the Louisiana Department
of Agriculture, said there was little worry about Florida's
procedures. ``Our concern is monitoring, in our state in
particular,'' by the USDA, he said.
   Florida, which is the largest domestic producer, has almost
600,000 acres of commercial citrus. Most of it is processed into
juice, but its fresh-fruit exports to other citrus-growing states
constitute an annual market of about $25 million.
   California has traditionally been the second-largest producer,
with Texas third, followed by Arizona, Louisiana and Hawaii. A 1983
freeze in Texas dropped its annual production to about 115,000 tons
on 22,000 acres of groves, however. Arizona has 35,500 acres
yielding about 485,000 tons.
   Citrus canker threatens commercial citrus groves because it is
easily spread. It mars leaves and fruit, making it unmarketable,
and can damage stems and twigs, causing a general decline of trees.
The fruit is edible, however.
   Florida's juice-processing industry has not been affected
because, except for the small Gulf Coast region, the disease has
not spread into commercial groves.
   Canker does not affect humans.
</TEXT>
