<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--DrugBeepers     03-04 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Drug Beepers,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Drug Dealing Students Can't Carry Beepers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The School Board has prohibited students from
carrying electronic telephone beepers, following administrators'
complaints that students were using them to arrange drug deals.
   When the ban vote Thursday takes effect, March 14, students
found carrying a beeper face suspension.
   ``At the high school and middle school level, if a child is in
possession of an operational beeper, they are usually dealing
drugs,'' said Arthur Pierce, principal of Francis M. Wood High
School. ``At the elementary level, kids are wearing inoperative
beepers to appear tough or macho and mimic the older kids. And
that's not something to encourage.''
   Pierce and other principals said they don't have figures, but
Pierce said the number of beepers showing up in schools is
alarming. Pierce said he has been confiscating pagers at his school
for three years.
   Virtually all drug possession arrests in city schools involve
marijuana, police said.
</TEXT>
