<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Bomb 2ndLd-Writethru a0552 03-04 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Bomb, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0552,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Discover, Dismantle Car Bomb Near Shultz's Hotel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Fatah claiming
responsibility. Pick up 9th pvs, `It was...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb was discovered today about 300 yards
from U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz's hotel and police said
the explosives were dismantled safely.
   In Beirut, Yasser Arafat's mainstream Palestine Liberation
Organization guerrilla group, Fatah, claimed responsibility said
Shultz was the target.
   The car had been driven into a wall and abandoned. A passing
officer thought the vehicle looked suspicious and discovered the
bomb, Jerusalem police commander Yosef Yehudai said.
   A U.S. Embassy spokewoman said the car bomb was nowhere near the
route Shultz was scheduled to travel today between the hotel and
Israeli government offices.
   Fatah, in a communique telephoned to The Associated Press office
in west Beirut, said its military command ``instructed the Limassol
martyrs group to park a bomb-laden car in front of the Hilton Hotel
in Jerusalem targeting Shultz, the messenger of imperialism.''
   Three PLO officials were killed in a car bomb explosion in the
Cypriot port of Limassol Feb. 14. The PLO blamed Israel's Mossad
secret service for the bombing.
   The Fatah communique identified the vehicle in Jerusalem as a
French-designed Renault-4 and said it was ``packed with 35
kilograms (77 pounds) of TNT.''
   ``The driver had an accident and the car crashed into a power
pole about 30 minutes before the time set for the bomb to
explode,'' the communique said. ``The driver deserted the vehicle
and managed to escape.''
   It said the attack was meant to be ``a response to the Zionists'
(Israelis') brutality against our people in the occupied
territories.''
   ``We warn Shultz and all agents of imperialism against reaching
out for the PLO, the sole legitimate representative of the
Palestinian people,'' the communique added.
   The vehicle was abandoned near a shopping mall and close to the
city's central bus station. It was northwest of the Hilton Hotel,
where Shultz spent Thursday night.
   Yehudai told the radio 22 pounds of explosives, ``a quantity
that could have caused a great deal of damage,'' and a mechanism to
set it off was found inside the vehicle. No arrests were reported.
   It was the second day in a row that a car bomb was discovered in
Israel. On Thursday, a car bomb exploded outside the central bus
station in Kfar Saba, northeast of Tel Aviv. No injuries were
reported.
   ``During the night we received a report of a car involved in a
regular accident not involving other cars,'' Yehudai said on the
radio about today's car bomb.
   ``Later, the chief police explosives expert passed by and
through his own experience decided the car was indeed suspicious
... We found it was a car bomb.''
   He said the discovery happened by accident.
   ``Its discovery and dismantling prevented a damaging attack,''
Yehudai said of the car bomb. ``It looks like this is the new `hit'
tactic of the terrorists.''
   An additional police statement said the car was registered to
Israelis living in Tel Aviv and had not been reported stolen.
   The area around where the car was found was closed to all
traffic for more than an hour. The vehicle was towed to a police
laboratory for further tests, the statement said.
</TEXT>
