<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1424EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     03-04 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Separatists Massacre 34; Government Frees Sikh Priests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARI SARI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh separatists sprayed automatic rifle
fire into hundreds of people celebrating a Hindu religious holiday,
killing at least 34 people and wounding about 45, police said
Friday.
   The attackers burst into a courtyard where Hindus, Sikhs and
Christians had come together to celebrate Holi, the festival of
light, in the northern state of Punjab.
   ``People ran helter-skelter. There were bodies on the ground,
and the injured were crying,'' said Mahavir Prashad, who was inside
a building and escaped injury.
   ``I tried to save some of the injured by giving them water, but
most of them died in my arms,'' he said.
   Several hours after the killings, the Indian government released
five Sikh high priests and 40 Sikh militants in an apparent peace
overture. They included Jasbir Singh Rode, who was arrested in 1984
during an army raid on the Sikh's Golden Temple.
   Rode, the chief priest at the temple during the raid, returned
in triumph to the temple. Cheering Sikhs emerged and fired about
400 rounds into the air from their rifles.
   Sikhs are a religious minority in India and say they are
discriminated against by the majority Hindus. Sikh militants are
fighting for a separate homeland in Punjab.
   Asked whether his release would pave the way for talks with the
government, Rode said: ``We shall see how serious and sincere the
government is before deciding who will talk and on what basis.''
   About 900 people were in the courtyard when six to eight gunmen
opened fire with AK-47 rifles about 11:30 p.m. Thursday, a senior
police official said. The massacre occurred in Kari Sari, about 80
miles east of the Sikh holy city of Amritsar.
   For the past century, Sikhs and Christians have joined Hindus in
Kari Sari to celebrate Holi, a national holiday commemorating the
Hindu god Lord Krishna's triumph over evil.
   Bonfires had been lighted, the crowd was singing, and a troupe
of actors was performing a series of plays about the lives of Hindu
deities when the gunmen burst in.
   Deputy inspector general A. Siddiqui said at least nine Sikhs
were killed, but he said most victims were Hindus.
   The killings prompted police alerts in Punjab, Haryana and New
Delhi.
   Most of the people in the courtyard were men. Women and children
were sitting on the roof of the hostel. The victims' ages ranged
from 10 to 60. At least two children were among the dead.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but police
blamed the Kalistan Commando Force, one of several Sikh separatist
groups.
   Sohan Singh, a 22-year-old Sikh, was shot in the leg. Speaking
from his hospital bed, he said the gunmen spared his life when he
obeyed their command to shout ``Kalistan zindabad (Long live
Kalistan)!''
   Kalistan is the name of the nation Sikhs envision for themselves.
   More than 380 people have been killed by Sikh extremists in
Punjab so far this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
