<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz-Mideast 4thLd-Writethru a0601 03-04 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Mideast, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0601,0809</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz In Damascus, After Meeting Shamir, Peres</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf, `The intent ...,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
PLO claiming responsibility. PICKS up 18th graf, `According to ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz flew
in today to discuss American ideas for peace in the Middle East
with the pro-Soviet government of President Hafez Assad.
   Shultz, on his second stop in Damascus in less a week, arrived
from Jerusalem where he had met with Israeli leaders. But his
efforts to promote negotiations on a settlement in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip did not appear to have
made any significant progrees.
   Shultz was greeted at Damascus airport by Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Sharaa. The two drove immediately to the Muhajerine
presidential palace for a meeting with Assad.
   He planned to leave for Cairo after the talks with Assad, a
strong critic of Washington's Middle East policies.
   Shultz, on a second, unscheduled swing through the region in the
past week, did not indicate he had achieved any progress in a
statement before leaving Israel.
   ``The president sent me back to work at it some more and while
he told me he'd let me come home tonight, he made it clear that we
would keep pushing and working,'' Shultz said at Ben Gurion
International Airport.
   Israel radio reported that Shultz presented a written version of
his peace proposal to Israel's rival leaders, Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir of the right-wing Likud bloc and Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres of the leftist Labor Party.
   Peres is said to favor the proposal while Shamir is believed to
oppose it.
   The radio said Shultz expects Shamir to reply to the American
proposals when the prime minister visits Washington on March 14.
   The draft proposal also was given to Jordan's King Hussein in
London on Thursday, the radio said.
   The plan, which contained no surprises, called for beginning the
peace process with an ``international opening which will lead to
direct talks between Israel and a Jordanian-Palestinian
delegation,'' the radio said.
   It also called for implementing Palestinian self-rule in the
occupied territories this fall and then beginning talks on a
permanent settlement in December.
   Shamir described his 90-minute session with Shultz as ``very
friendly, very useful and promising.'' He said he was sure the
United States and Israel would continue efforts to start peace
talks in the area.
   Shultz then met for about 45 minutes with Peres, who described
Shultz's proposals as ``food for thought.''
   Shultz called the talks ``positive and constructive.''
   Also today, police discovered a car bomb set on a street about
300 yards from the Hilton Hotel where Shultz was staying, and
safely dismantled the explosives. No arrests were reported.
   In Beirut, Lebanon Yasser Arafat's mainstream Palestine
Liberation Organization guerrilla group, Fatah, claimed
responsibility for the car bomb and said Shultz was the target.
   Fatah, in a communique telephoned to The Associated Press office
in west Beirut, said its military command ordered commandos ``to
park a bomb-laden car in front of the Hilton Hotel in Jerusalem
targeting Shultz, the messenger of imperialism.''
   ``The driver had an accident and the car crashed into a power
pole about 30 minutes before the time set for the bomb to
explode,'' the communique said.
   ``The driver deserted the vehicle and managed to escape,'' the
communique said.
   According to U.N. figures, rioting since Dec. 8 in the occupied
lands has left at least 76 Palestinians dead, mostly by Israeli
gunfire.
   Palestinians have refused to meet Shultz without approval from
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Islamic fundamentalists circulated leaflets in the Gaza Strip
condemning the Shultz mission and referring to the U.S. official as
``the great evil envoy,'' the Jerusalem Post reported today.
   In Damascus, a leading government newspaper today said the
United States seeks to crush Palestinian protests in Israeli-held
territories rather than find a durable peace settlement.
   The Al-Baath daily, mouthpiece of the ruling Baath Arab
Socialist Party, said in a front-page editorial that the United
States ``was always determined to make Israel the only power in the
region.
   Shultz planned a whirlwind last day in the region. After meeting
with Assad, he was to go to Egypt to meet with President Hosni
Mubarak. On Saturday, he was scheduled to return to Washington.
   Shultz has urged Palestinians to form a joint delegation with
Jordan in peace talks, citing close ties betweeen Jordan and the
1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which
Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Hussein wants a separate seat for the PLO in peace talks, but
Israel refuses to negotiate with the PLO, saying it is a terrorist
organization.
</TEXT>
