<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz-Dove     03-04 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Dove,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Relies On Good Luck Charm To Make Mission Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz has invoked
the powers of a good luck charm during his Middle East shuttle: a
white peace dove in his Jerusalem hotel lobby.
   Whenever Shultz passed through the lobby of the Jerusalem
Hilton, he pulled a silver-and-white ribbon hanging from the dove,
sending the bird's wings flapping.
   ``When I came here about seven or eight days ago to start the
process, I went into the hotel and there, hanging from the ceiling,
was a bird _ a great big thing on a little rope you pull and the
wings go and the dove flies,'' Shultz said Friday.
   ``So I pulled it when I came in and everybody clapped and I keep
pulling it whenever I go through there in the hope that it will
bring us good fortune,'' Shultz said. He made his comments after
meeting with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres.
   ``And that is what I wish to the people of Israel, to the
Palestinians, to the people of all the neighboring countries that I
have visited, good fortune and peace,'' Shultz said.
   Shultz arrived in Jerusalem on Feb. 25 for a five-day Middle
East shuttle, and returned to the region Thursday night for a
second round of talks with Arab and Israeli leaders.
   The wooden dove measures 13 feet by 13 feet and has an aluminium
olive branch in its beak. Hotel spokesman Motti Verses said the
bird would remain hanging in the lobby because of rumors that
Shultz would return to the region by the end of March.
</TEXT>
