<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ChallengerProbe Bjt   03-04 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Challenger Probe, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Audit Panel Sees Nothing in Way of Resumed Shuttle Flights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outside committee that audited NASA's
recovery from the Challenger disaster for 14 months said Friday it
finds no safety flaws serious enough to delay the resumption of
space shuttle flights.
   The first mission, with the shuttle Discovery, is scheduled for
Aug. 4.
   ``We are all quite comfortable with what's been done to get
ready for the next flight,'' retired Gen. Alton Slay, chairman of
the National Research Council committee, told reporters.
   ``We find absolutely no show-stoppers,'' Slay said. ``Space
travel will always entail risks. It cannot be reduced to zero. The
key to minimizing those risks is to identify the most likely
hazards or failures and to take steps to eliminate them or control
them if they cannot be eliminated.''
   But coupled with the praise was a strong recommendation that the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration tighten the ways it
assesses and manages risks associated with the shuttle.
   ``No matter how good you are, you never reach Mecca,'' said
Slay. ``There is always room for improvement.''
   The committee's central finding, he said, is that NASA is able
to assess and manage risks associated with space flights, but uses
so many review boards and safety organizations that the result is
``a fragmented picture of the safety and reliability of the total
space transportation system.''
   Further, Slay said, those organizations rely on subjective
assessments of risk posed by thousands of individual space shuttle
components, rather than on engineering evaluations.
   ``Their procedures and their oganizations need policing up,''
Slay said. ``They need to do more to integrate their risk
assessment and risk management. They need more to take advantage of
all the data that does exist in their decision-making process.''
   Slay defined risk assessment as ``saying on any particular piece
of hardware, what is the likelihood this is going to cause a
problem if it is going to fail ... and if it fails, will it cascade
into some other system and cause a problem there?''
   Asked if better risk assessment might have stopped the ill-fated
launch of the Challenger on Jan. 28, 1986, Slay replied:
   ``No one can say that for sure. The only thing we can say for
sure is if these procedures had been in place, we would have had
more information at our fingertips. Whether the engineering
judgments that they made at the time would have bveen different,
who can say?''
   Challenger's seven-member crew was killed when the shuttle
exploded 73 seconds after launch.
   William Lenoir, a former astronaut who flew on the shuttle in
1982, said the bulk of the recommendations in the 144-page report
has already been put in effect by NASA and that the report
contained no surprises for the agency.
   NASA said it will carefully review the report. Agency
Administrator James C. Fletcher said NASA owes the National
Research Council a vote of thanks.
   ``I am particfdularly gratified that the council did not find
any show-stoppers that, in their opinion, should delay the next
launch of the space shuttle, now set for August,'' he said.
   Lenoir, whose planned spacewalk was scrubbed by a malfunctioning
space suit, said he is worried that the Challenger accident may
have made NASA personnel gun-shy.
   ``We need to be careful that we don't go overboard and keep
trying to make it safe enough, a little bit safer and a little bit
safer, and we may never fly again because we'll never make it 100
percent safe,'' he said. ``I believe the right processses are in
place.''
   The committee review was recommended by the presidential
commission that investigated the Challenger accident. The National
Research Council acts as a scientific advisory group to the federal
government and is administered by the National Academy of Sciences,
the National Academy of Engineering and the Institute of Medicine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
