<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Walesa     03-04 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walesa,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Accuses Australia of Meddling With Walesa Invitation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper Friday
accused Australia of interfering in Polish affairs by supporting an
invitation to Solidarity leader Lech Walesa to attend a trade union
congress in Melbourne.
   The government said Tuesday it would bar Walesa and three top
aides from traveling to Australia to attend the union congress.
Officials said they were acting to protect the state's ``basic
political interests.''
   Friday's commentary appeared in Trybuna Ludu, the official daily
of the party.
   The Australian Embassy in Warsaw said allowing Walesa to visit
Australia would improve relations between the two countries and
show that Poland was making progress in enacting reforms.
   It said Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke had ``presented the
argument that a country's standing is enhanced if it permits a
citizen, albeit a controversial one, to go abroad where he can
speak freely.''
   The Australian Council of Trade Unions invited the Poles to
attend the World Congress of the International Confederation of
Free Trade Unions from March 14-18.
   Trybuna Ludu said inviting members of an illegal organization
was ``a provocative action against Poland'' and ignored ``the real
fact of the existence in Poland of a ... reborn trade union
movement.''
   The newspaper was referring to the All-Poland Trade Union
Alliance, the official labor federation set up with government
backing after Solidarity was outlawed in October 1982 that claims
about 7 million members.
   Walesa, contacted by telephone at his Gdansk apartment, said
such personal attacks in Trybuna Ludu were not new. He added that
the article showed ``who is standing behind the allegedly
independent (official) trade unions.''
   He called it strange that the state should try to force
international recognition for the official trade unions by barring
him from traveling to Australia.
   Walesa has not traveled abroad since the December 1981 martial
law crackdown that suppressed Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's first
free trade union. The Gdansk shipyard worker helped found
Solidarity in 1980 and won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1983.
   Walesa has not yet received a formal refusal of his application,
said an aide. Also invited to Australia were Wroclaw Solidarity
leader Wladyslaw Frasyniuk, Gdansk leader Bogdan Lis and senior
adviser Bronislaw Geremek.
</TEXT>
