<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParamedicMom     03-04 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paramedic Mom,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paramedic Responds To Call, Saves Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paramedic says his heart pounded as he
responded to an emergency call, dashed into the home and found his
65-year-old mother unconscious on the floor.
   But Michael Flaherty said professional skills kicked in as he
delivered mouth-to-mouth resuscitation.
   ``He saved his mother's life,'' said Ronald Smith, chief
paramedic for the Chicago Fire Department. ``He brought her back.''
   ``You always wonder what would happen if it is somebody you
know,'' Flaherty said. ``You hope it isn't anything serious, but
you expect the worst.''
   Flaherty's parents were having breakfast Wednesday when his
mother, Theresa, collapsed. His father called for an ambulance.
   ``When I heard the address, I could have run there faster than
the ambulance, if that had been necessary,'' Flaherty said.
``Nobody was going to beat us to that address.''
   Flaherty's father, Peter, who is not trained in cardiopulmonary
resuscitation, applied chest compressions before the younger
Flaherty and his partner, Jake Willens, arrived.
   Mrs. Flaherty was rushed to St. Francis Hospital in Evanston
where she was reported in good condition Friday, said spokesman Bob
Olander. ``It's not a heart attack. It's a condition leading up to
a heart attack,'' he said.
   ``No paramedic or firefighter wants to resuscitate or work on
his own parents or children or friends,'' Flaherty said. ``But when
something happens and you have to do it, you react.''
   Flaherty said that after the emergency some people asked him,
``How could you treat your own mother?'
   ``How can you say I can't do it?'' he replied.
   ``The fact it was my mother didn't make any difference in the
way I treated her,'' he said. ``I would have done the same thing
for any other patient. There are 26 nursing homes in the area our
ambulance serves. I treat each of those patients like they were my
mother or father.''
</TEXT>
