<HEAD>Teen Arrested With Dead Civil War Officer's Bones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager was jailed Friday after police
found at his home the remains of Confederate Army Major John David
Walker, who has been dead for 125 years.
   Police Detective T.W. Carr said Walker's remains were stolen
last year from a private cemetery near Augusta College.
   James Bruce Meyer, 17, of Augusta, was arrested Thursday night
on a felony charge of wanton desecration of a grave, officials
said. Police recovered Walker's skull and pelvis, assorted other
bones and the handles from his casket at Meyer's home.
   A relative of the dead soldier, 61-year-old Adele Shearer, had
reported to police last October that his remains had been stolen.
   Meyer was being held on bond Friday at the Augusta-Richmond
County Law Enforcement Center, and the investigation was continuing.
   Walker was killed in the second Battle of Bull Run on Aug. 30,
1862.
