<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet     03-04 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Officials Complain to Soviets About Geneva Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American arms negotiators in Geneva have
complained ``very forcefully'' to their Soviet counterparts that
Moscow has failed to submit three key documents, slowing progress
on a plan to cut strategic nuclear arsenals by 50 percent, U.S.
officials said Friday.
   Phyllis Oakley, the State Department's deputy spokeswoman, said
the United States is still waiting for the Soviets to submit their
drafts of a memorandum of understanding and two protocols on
verification, which American negotiators have already provided.
   Both sides promised to submit the papers in time for a review by
Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze at a meeting scheduled for March 22 in
Washington, she said.
   ``If the ministers are to have the opportunity to review these
key documents at their next meeting, it's clear and imperative that
the Soviets supply their versions as soon as possible,'' Mrs.
Oakley said.
   ``We've set no deadlines, but obviously these issues are
complicated and complex and they need time for thorough study and
review,'' she added.
   Another official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said S.
Read Hanmer, the U.S. negotiator at the Strategic Arms Reduction
Talks in Geneva, ``very forcefully raised this issue with the
Soviets.''
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev agreed
at their Dec. 8-10 summit to work diligently toward a 50 percent
reduction in long-range weapons carried by bombers and missiles on
land and sea. The aim was to get an agreement in time for signature
at a summit meeting in Moscow, which is expected to be held in May
or June.
   One of the most difficult elements of the negotiation has been
figuring out a way to insure that neither side cheated in its
conversion or elimination of the weapons.
   As in past arms negotiations, the two sides said they would
submit drafts of how they thought a verification system should be
written and then begin work to eliminate the differences.
   Since October, the United States has provided its versions of
two protocols: one on how the conversion or elimination would take
place, and one on how the procedures would be monitored and
inspected. On Wednesday, the United States submitted the final
document, a 130-page draft of a memorandum of understanding
providing an extensive exchange of factual material.
   ``The Soviets have not tabled (proposed) their versions, so
there's nothing to work with, and they won't convene working groups
until they have submitted their versions,'' a U.S. official said.
   In a speech in St. Louis on Thursday, Edward L. Rowny, an arms
control adviser to Reagan, said vast amounts of work need to be
done on a strategic agreement before it can be ready for Reagan and
Gorbachev to sign.
   Verification is among the toughest problems, he said.
   ``In START, because of the many different systems on both sides,
spanning a wide variety of geographic deployments and operational
practices, it is important that the details be tackled now and
solved soon,'' he said.
   U.S. officials conceded on Friday that the three documents they
submitted contain omissions, reflecting the need for more work just
to refine the American position on these issues.
   ``The difference is that we've made the submissions anyway, so
that at least we can start the process,'' one official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
