<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Waldheim     03-04 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waldheim,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waldheim Controversy Triggers Resignation Of General</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Austria's five generals announced
Friday he was resigning because of a disagreement involving
President Kurt Waldheim and his service in the Nazi army during
World War II.
   Gen. Karl Schaffer said he asked to resign last month to protest
a directive from Defense Minister Robert Lichal, who ordered the
general not to edit an army film used for political education.
   Schaffer wanted to cut out a segment in the film that quoted a
historian as saying: ``Historians are no apostles of morals.''
   He said he wanted to do so to avoid a potential association with
a recent report by an international historians' commission that
questioned Waldheim's moral integrity during his service as a
lieutenant in the German army. The commission also said Waldheim
was in ``close proximity'' to wartime atrocities.
   But Lichal, a conservative backer of Waldheim, decreed the
segment must remain in the film.
   Schaffer, who is director of the prestigious national defense
academy, told The Associated Press he had tried to keep the dispute
over Waldheim out of the army.
   But since it had proved impossible, Schaffer said he was
resorting to the ``last means available to an officer'' and asking
for early retirement.
   Under the Austrian constitution, Waldheim is commander-in-chief
of the federal army.
   Word that the 58-year-old general was stepping down from the
officers' training academy drew calls from the Socialist Party and
the small Freedom Party for Lichal to back down.
   ``Party bickering over the president'' should be kept out of the
army, the Socialist and Freedom parties said.
   Soon after the historians' report was released Feb. 9, Socialist
officers in the army issued a statement calling on Waldheim to
resign.
   The defense minister told a news conference Friday that Schaffer
had asked to retire for health reasons, and rejected all other
suggestions about the general's departure.
   The Neue Arbeiterzeitung said several unidentified officers had
declared their solidarity with Schaffer and one brigadier _ one of
the 90 most senior army commanders _ had returned his membership
card to the conservative People's Party.
</TEXT>
