<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CopKilled     03-04 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cop Killed,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arrested, Third Suspect Questioned in Cop Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were arrested and a third was being
questioned Friday in the slaying of a rookie cop who was shot three
times in the head as he guarded a witness in a drug case, police
said.
   Todd Scott and Scott Cobb were charged with second-degree murder
and criminal possession of a weapon after their arrests late
Thursday, according to police. A third suspect surrendered Friday
and was being questioned, Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said at
a news conference.
   Officer Edward Byrne, 22, was shot early Feb. 26 while sitting
in a patrol car, guarding the house of a man who had complained to
police about crack dealers in the South Jamaica neighborhood of
Queens.
   The killing outraged Mayor Edward Koch, who called President
Reagan a ``wimp'' in the war on drugs; prompted a roundup of 294
suspected drug dealers and focused new attention on the city's drug
lords.
   A reward fund grew to $130,000 Thursday with a $25,000
contribution from some members of the New York Stock Exchange.
   City newspapers, quoting unidentified sources, said Scott
allegedly works for Howard ``Pappy'' Mason, an associate of reputed
drug kingpin Lorenzo ``Fat Cat'' Nichols.
   Nichols, 29, was sentenced Feb. 25 in Queens to 25 years to life
in prison on drug and gun charges and is awaiting trial on charges
he had his parole officer killed for revenge. Mason is awaiting
trial on charges he was one of the people who carried out that
killing.
   Police have speculated that Nichols may have ordered Byrne's
killing as retribution for his long sentence.
   New York Newsday reported Friday that the killing was planned
Feb. 24. The newspaper quoted police sources as saying that two men
were approached by men from a nearby housing project and offered
$10,000 to ``hit a cop.''
   ``This is from the Fat Cat,'' the men said, according to the
Newsday source, and the two drew straws to decide who would pull
the trigger.
   An unidentified detective on the case told Newsday that the
killers twice went past the guarded house and ``each time they saw
a black officer and they didn't kill.''
   ``They also passed by when a woman sat guard. They were waiting
for a cop like Edward Byrne,'' who was white, the detective daid.
   However, Ward said Friday, ``I don't think there was anything
racial about the assassination of Officer Eddie Byrne.''
   ``Officer Edward Byrne was killed because he wore a blue
uniform,'' said Ward.
   The Rev. Thomas DeVita, who presided at Byrne's funeral Monday,
said family members told him they plan to go to the home of the
witness Byrne was guarding to ``offer moral support.''
   ``I think I echo the feelings of others too, that justice should
be done,'' said De Vita.
   ``The community has been very helpful,'' Ward said Thursday,
adding he hoped the drug dealers learned a lesson.
   ``Shooting at cops, it's just bad for business. I think
experienced criminals know that; perhaps these inexperienced ones
will learn it,'' the commissioner said.
</TEXT>
