<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Prints,0123</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Capt. Cook Plant Prints Sold In Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A collection of 120 prints of plant drawings made
on Capt. James Cook's first voyage around the world was auctioned
in the Natural History Museum.
   Collectors gathered Thursday night in the front hall around the
feet of a skeleton of Diplodocus, a plant-eating dinosaur that
lived 150 million years ago.
   Sotheby's, which conducted the sale, said the prints fetched
$94,441.
   The plants were drawn by Sydney Parkinson, who sailed with Cook
and Sir Joseph Banks on a 1768-71 journey that included Australia,
New Zealand, Java, Argentina and Brazil.
   None of the buyers was identified. The top price was $2,816 for
a print of a portia tree.
