<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Carlucci     03-04 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Opposes Use of Troops as Drug Law-Enforcers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said
Friday he would strongly oppose any effort to carve out an active
law-enforcement role for the military in the war on drugs.
   ``That is not the function of the military. We are not the
front-line agency in the war on drugs,'' Carlucci said in an
interview with The Associated Press.
   Espousing the same approach as his predecessor, Caspar W.
Weinberger, Carlucci said he was ``very much against giving the
military arrest authority or getting them into law enforcement''
and did not foresee any change in administration policy.
   Carlucci also called Libyan strongman Col. Moammar Gadhafi a
``flyspeck'' who wasn't worth listening to and said he thought the
U.S. naval force in the Persian Gulf had been reduced to a proper
level
   He predicted that a Soviet pullout from Afghanistan, if it
occurs, would have little effect on the Kremlin's policies and its
support of countries such as Nicaragua.
   Carlucci also expressed hope that a meeting later this month
with his Soviet counterpart, Dmitri Yazov, would at the least
produce an agreement on steps to avoid small, but dangerous,
confrontations such a recent ship-bumping incident in the Black Sea
and interference with U.S. military observers in East Germany.
   Carlucci, who assumed his post in November after Weinberger
retired, was asked his views on drug enforcement after Education
Secretary William Bennett suggested the United States consider ``a
broader use of military force against both the production and
shipment of drugs.''
   Sen. Bob Dole, who is seeking the Republican presidential
nomination, adopted the same approach on Thursday, calling for use
of ``the full force of our military ...''
   The defense secretary countered the Pentagon should continue to
play only a supporting role in the war on drugs _ sharing equipment
and intelligence _ because otherwise it would lose sight of its
real mission.
   ``My own view is that ... the military should be supportive,''
he said. ``But I would be very much against giving the military
arrest authority or getting them into law enforcement.''
   Carlucci reserved his most pointed rhetoric for Libya's Gadhafi,
who earlier this week demanded once again the United States
recognize his claim to the Gulf of Sidra, off the Mediterranean Sea.
   The United States recognizes only the standard 12-mile
territorial limit in the gulf. U.S. and Libyan forces clashed in
March 1986 after the Navy ignored Gadhafi's ``line of death'' in
the gulf and a month later, U.S. jets bombed Libya in retaliation
for Libya's alleged involvement in international terrorism.
   ``I think Gadhafi's a flyspeck,'' Carlucci said. ``I don't think
he's worth paying attention to. We're certainly not dancing to his
tune.''
   Carlucci refused to say whether the United States was planning
any additional naval maneuvers in the gulf, but added: ``If your
question is, are we going ahead with the freedom of navigation
program, yeah, we're going ahead with that program around the world
based on our schedule ....''
   The defense secretary said he was satisfied with the state of
U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf, where American ships have been
protecting reflagged Kuwaiti tankers against Iranian attack since
last July. The Navy fleet was recently reduced in size, with a
battleship and helicopter carrier sailing for home.
   ``We are now on our 39th convoy, 38 of which have been without
incident,'' Carlucci said. ``And I think that record speaks for
itself. We've obviously got the capability over there that we
need.''
   Turning to his March 14 meeting with Yazov in Bern, Switzerland
_ the first such working session between the U.S. and Soviet
defense chiefs _ Carlucci predicted the talks would focus on
avoiding ``dangerous activities,'' or confrontations between small
military units; arms control and human rights; Soviet defense
doctrine, and planning for meetings of top-ranking military
officers.
   ``In the area of what we call dangerous activities, I would hope
that we can reach some meeting of the minds ... at least set up a
process so that they can be avoided,'' Carlucci said.
   The Soviets, he added, are unlikely to change any of their
military policies as a result of their setbacks in Afghanistan,
where they are fighting U.S.-supported rebels.
   ``I guess people have in mind the Vietnam analogy,'' Carlucci
said. ``I don't think it works the same way in their system ... the
Soviet military and the Soviet people don't have access to the same
amount of information that we have in our society.''
   Asked about the huge military buildup during President Reagan's
first term, when he was Weinberger's deputy, Carlucci said he
wouldn't second-guess the pace or manner in which those increases
were pursued.
   While political support for the buildup has evaporated _ forcing
budget cuts for three years running _ ``we could have well have
ended up with less'' if the spending hikes had been sought on a
more gradual basis, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
