<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     03-04 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0903</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY44, NY77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Harrison scoffs at reports that he and
fellow former Beatle Paul McCartney are having a tiff, saying
instead they are considering a reunion with Ringo Starr to ``write
a tune and play together.''
   During a recording Thursday for a television talk show,
Harrison, 45, denied a recent British press report of a rift with
McCartney.
   ``Maybe we will write a tune and play together. It won't be The
Beatles, of course, but it may happen and we are getting on with
Paul much better than we used to,'' Harrison said during the
recording for the ``Aspel and Company'' show.
   The British tabloid News of the World last Sunday reported that
``a bitter feud'' had erupted between Harrison and McCartney over a
recent pop music festival at San Remo in Italy.
   But Harrison countered: ``For the last 10 years I did not see
much of Paul at all. But recently we have been going out to dinner
and seeing each other socially quite a lot.''
   John Lennon, the fourth member of The Beatles, was shot dead
outside his New York apartment on Dec. 8, 1980.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive producer of Ironweed said the
movie almost went to the dogs when a pack of angry canines supposed
to be attacking another actor turned on Jack Nicholson.
   ``Normally, we do five or six takes... by the time we did the
fifth take, the dogs were starting to bite Jack,'' producer Denis
Blouin said recently.
   ``Nicholson was getting fed up. He said he was finished, he was
furious and said he was going home. It took us an hour to convince
him to come back. Then, after 15 takes, we finally got the scene
finished,'' he said.
   In the film Ironweed, Nicholson stars as Francis Phelan, a
former baseball star who returns to his hometown as a bum. His
co-star, Meryl Streep, is Helen Archer, an educated woman who
clings to her friendship with Francis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson will receive an honorary
doctor of humane letters degree from Fisk University for his
support of the United Negro College Fund.
   Angela Radcliffe, a spokeswoman for the black, private liberal
arts school, said the university trustees recently voted to award
him the degree. The singer has a current hit record, ``Man in the
Mirror,'' and a top album, ``Bad.'' He is now on a nationwide
concert tour.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane hunter Robert Sheets, who
has flown into the eye of more than 200 of the violent storms, has
been named director of the National Hurricane Center.
   The job makes him responsible for warning the 40 million coastal
residents from Texas to Maine about the onslaught of a tropical
storm, one of nature's most destructive and powerful weather
systems.
   His first-hand experience inside hurricanes, gained over 16
years as a researcher, will be a valuable, he said. ``I know as
much about hurricane structure and their variations as anyone.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An enthusiastic audience at the Berlin Opera
recently brought singer Luciano Pavarotti back to the stage for a
record 165 curtain calls after a performance of Gaetano Donizetti's
opera ``L'elisir d'amore.''
   Berlin Opera Spokeswoman Barbara Hering said Friday that the
number of curtain calls was a record for Pavarotti and for the
Berlin Opera house.
   ``It may have also been a world record, but we do not have
records on that here, so I can not say exactly,'' Hering said from
her office in West Berlin.
   Hering said Pavarotti sang the role on two nights in Berlin. He
returned to the stage for 165 curtain calls on Feb. 27, and for 115
curtain calls on Feb. 24.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu
will travel to Moscow in June to celebrate the 1,000th anniversary
of the Russian Orthodox Church, according to his spokesman.
   Tutu, winner of the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize for his fight against
apartheid, is leader of the Anglican church in southern Africa.
   He was arrested and briefly detained Monday when he and other
church leaders tried to march to Parliament with a petition
protesting the recent government crackdown on organizations
opposing the South African government's racial policies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $4 million restaurant and ``boutique''
brewery proposed by chef Wolfgang Puck met with dis-flavor when a
City Council committee recommended rejecting the plan.
   At a hearing before the three-member Planning and Environment
Committee this week, residents said the brewery and restaurant
would bring drunken drivers, traffic and noise to their
neighborhood on the city's Westside.
   City Council members Ruth Galanter and Michael Woo agreed, but
Councilman Hal Bernson, the committee chairman, withheld his vote
until he could visit the site.
   In a telephone interview at Spago's, Puck's West Hollywood
restaurant, the chef said he would not push the project against
strong local opposition.
   ``I want it to be a neighborhood restaurant,'' Puck said. ``If
the neighborhood doesn't want it, I don't want to spend years
fighting them.''
   Puck envisions building what he called a ``boutique,'' or
``micro brewery'' that would produce a quality beer.
</TEXT>
