<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chambers     03-04 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chambers Jury Visits Central Park</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 21-year-old defendant in what has been
dubbed the ``preppie murder'' trial peered through trees on a damp,
gray Friday morning as the jurors in his case tramped over the
Central Park ground where he left a young woman dead.
   Robert Chambers, 21, charged with second-degree murder in the
death of Jennifer Levin, sat in the back of a gray car about 40
yards from where her bruised, nearly naked body was found Aug. 26,
1986.
   It was a different vantage point from the low wall behind the
Metropolitan Museum of Art where he sat as police investigated the
death shortly after Miss Levin's body was discovered by a passing
bicyclist. Chambers admits killing her but says it was an accident
after she attacked him sexually and hurt him.
   The cold, damp ground around the tree where the body was found
was bare, and the tree was stripped of leaves, a contrast to the
green grass and foliage in the park on the warm summer morning when
Miss Levin was killed.
   The jurors walked over to examine the areas where the victim's
body and panties were found and where several police officers
testified they had seen a ground disturbance suggesting a body had
been dragged.
   Fifty reporters and photographers and a few onlookers watched
the proceeding from a distance, kept away by a yellow police ribbon.
   The trip came a day after a prosecutor testified he was not
trying to trick Chambers by saying police had not found Miss
Levin's underpants in the park when in fact they had.
   In a videotaped interview, Assistant District Attorney Stephen
Saracco is heard telling Chambers that his account of how he killed
Miss Levin does not make sense in part because no panties were
found.
   Chambers' lawyer, Jack Litman, has suggested that Saracco tried
to trick his client by lying to him.
   Chambers and Miss Levin, 18, went to the park after meeting in
an East Side bar frequented by children of privilege. Both had
attended prep schools; Miss Levin was college-bound while Chambers
was a college dropout.
   Chambers says the young woman tied his hands behind his back
with her panties, sat on his chest facing his feet and grabbed his
genitals painfully. He says he freed his hands, threw the panties
over his head and reached up with his left forearm and yanked
against her throat, flipping her off him.
   Detective Michael Sheehan testified early in the 9-week-old
trial that another investigator passed Saracco a note during the
videotaping to tell him the panties were found. He said they were
recovered some 45 feet from the body.
   ``Do you remember a note being put in front of you?'' defense
lawyer Jack Litman asked Saracco.
   ``I don't recall a note _ if there was one,'' Saracco said. ``I
don't know if there was a note.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1602EST</FILEID>
