<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Bomb, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0748,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Safely Dismantled In Jerusalem, PLO Claims Shultz Was
Target</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts throughout to raise reference to PLO claims, Fatah.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following dispatch was submitted to the
Israeli military censor, who ordered a deletion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO claimed responsibility for a car packed
with explosives that was found near a hotel where Secretary of
State George P. Shultz was staying. The guerrilla group said Shultz
was the target.
   Police, who defused the bomb safely, said the car had been found
accidentally after it was abandoned by its driver. There were no
reports of arrests.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said the bomb was well off the route
the secretary took from the hotel to Israeli government offices.
   But Yasser Arafat's mainstream Palestinian guerrilla group,
Fatah, said in a statement in Beirut that ``the driver had an
accident and the car crashed into a power pole about 30 minutes
before the time set for the bomb to explode.''
   ``The driver deserted the vehicle and managed to escape,'' the
communique said.
   In a communique telephoned to The Associated Press office in
west Beirut, Fatah said its military command ``instructed the
Limassol martyrs group to park a bomb-laden car in front of the
Hilton Hotel in Jerusalem targeting Shultz, the messenger of
imperial'' Yehudai said. ``Later
the chief police explosives expert passed by and through his own
experience decided the car was indeed suspicious ... We found it
was a car bomb.''
   The car carried Israeli license plates with a sticker reading:
``Contribute to security.''
   Israel Television quoted police officials as saying the car was
sold ``to an Arab who apparently used a fake identity (card).''
   The car was found less than a quarter-mile from the hotel, where
Shultz spent Thursday night.
   Three officials of Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization
were killed in a car bomb explosion in the Cypriot port of Limassol
Feb. 14.
   The PLO blamed Israel's Mossad secret service for the bombing.
   It said the attack was meant to be ``a response to the Zionists'
brutality against our people in the occupied territories.''
   ``We warn Shultz and all agents of imperialism against reaching
out for the PLO, the sole legitimate representative of the
Palestinian people,'' the communique added.
   It was the second report of a car bomb in two days. On Thursday,
one exploded outside the bus station of Kfar Saba, a town in
central Israel, causing no injuries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1559EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-Rate-at-a-Glance     03-04 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rate-at-a-Glance,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Postage Rate Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, is a rundown of some of the
new postage rates recommended Friday by the independent Postal Rate
Commission:
   _First Class (Letters):
   First ounce 25 cents, up from 22 cents. Additional ounces 20
cents, up from 17 cents.
