<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-04 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The best-liked commercials of 1987 included some
starring performances from animated characters such as dancing clay
raisins, a hamburger chain's moonman and a pizza company's dreaded
spoiler called a Noid.
   Few of the commercials mentioned most often by consumers polled
by Video Storyboard Tests Inc. featured traditional show business
celebrities, the head of the consumer research firm said Thursday.
   ``We seem to heading into a period when we see more created
celebrities, not necessarily human beings, in commercials,'' said
David Vadehra, president of Video Storyboard, in relasing the
results of the firm's 10th annual survey of more than 25,000 people.
   Leading the list was the campaign for California raisins, which
used clay models of raisins dancing to the sounds of Motown music.
The ads cost a relatively modest $5.4 million, compared to as much
as $344 million for McDonald's Corp. commercials.
   Second was Bud Light beer commercials, many of which featured
the English bull terrier Spuds MacKenzie while others offered
numerous variations of what can go wrong if you simply order a
``light'' without specifying the brand.
   The ad campaign for Pepsi soft drinks placed third, and Miller
Lite beer commercials were fourth. Ads for McDonald's restaurants
came in fifth.
   The Noid, the animated imp with the maniacal laugh who threatens
the freshness of home-delivered pizza in Domino's Pizza
commercials, was foiled again and wound up 10th.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One job title is just like any other _ or is it?
   How about ``terminal operator'' for mortician, or ``mobile
sanitatian engineer'' for garbage truck driver. Or ``vice
president, participation and residuals,'' the person in charge of
royalties?
   These are some of the titles personnel executives from about 100
companies reported in a survey by Personnel Journal, based in Costa
Mesa, Calif., which didn't identify any of the people or companies
it quoted.
   Whether humorous or obscure, job titles do serve a purpose,
personnel managers insist.
   ``Titles are accepted as a form of recognition and motivation,''
said an unidentified personnel manager of a Chicago-based
association management firm. ``They give the feeling of function
and stature.''
   ``People need structure and organization to provide a sense of
stability and belonging _ where do they fit in the organization?
Titles help them,'' says a personnel executive at a federal
hospital in Milwaukee.
   There are some negatives to titles, the personnel managers admit.
   ``They create a class distinction and enhance the we-versus-them
attitude,'' said an executive of a mining company in Missoula, Mont.
</TEXT>
