<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1602EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-EmbassyRadiation     03-04 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Embassy Radiation,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Seeks Protest Over Beams; State Dept. Plays Down
Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ranking Republican on the House Foreign
Affairs Committee on Friday called for a protest to the Soviet
Union, while the State Department sought to minimize the
significance of its statement on microwave beams aimed at the U.S.
Embassy in Moscow.
   Rep. William S. Broomfield of Michigan said Secretary of State
George P. Shultz should lodge an official protest over the
continuing presence of low-level microwave beams aimed at the
embassy.
   ``How can we trust the Soviets to honor sensitive arms reduction
agreements if they are technically attacking our embassy
building?'' Broomfield said. ``Trust is an essential part of
improving relations with the U.S.S.R. Harassing our diplomats there
is unacceptable.''
   He added: ``I want the State Department to play hardball this
time and protest this clear abuse of our fellow citizens'' serving
in Moscow.
   In a statement released Thursday in response to questions
submitted by The Associated Press, the State Department's Bureau of
Diplomatic Security said ``microwave signals in the 5-11 GHz
(gigahertz) range continue to be detected at the Moscow embassy
chancery.''
   ``The microwave signal power levels are typically 0.1 microwatt
per square centimeter external to the building,'' it said.
``Measurements internal to the building are typically less than
0.01 microwatt per square centimeter.''
   The current U.S. voluntary safety standard for exposure to
microwave radiation _ set by the American National Standards
Institute _ is 5,000 microwatts per square centimeter. By contrast,
the Soviet Union's official safety standard for the microwave
frequency range is much lower _ 10 microwatts per square centimeter.
   The statement Thursday said the department could shed no light
as to why microwaves have been aimed against the embassy for
perhaps as far back as October 1953. It said ``any response would
be speculation.''
   At a news briefing Friday, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley emphasized the low power levels of the Soviet signals
currently being detected at the embassy and denied that the
situation amounts to ``bombardment.''
   ``The Soviets have not resumed microwave bombardment,'' she
said. ``We have routinely detected some very low-level microwave
activity in our ongoing continuous microwave screening at the
embassy. ... There are no known risks from the type of low levels
of exposure in Moscow that have continued.
   ``We are, of course, concerned about this situation,'' Mrs.
Oakley continued. ``In the past, we've protested when levels have
exceeded those we consider safe. We're prepared to do so again,
should we determine that they pose any threat whatsoever to our
staff, however remote.''
   She added: ``What we're saying is that there is not a new
program of bombardment. We have watched the situation carefully. We
continue to watch it carefully. There have been low levels that we
have detected, but these pose no risk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
