<1ST_LINE>r w AM-VisaDenied 1stLd-Writethru a0814 03-04 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Visa Denied, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0814,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Dept. Denies Visa to President of Sinn Fein</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `The committee' with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with background on Noraid</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has denied a visa to
Gerry Adams, head of the Irish Republican Army's legal political
wing, based on the belief that he is involved in terrorist
activity, a spokeswoman said Thursday.
   ``He was ineligible under (the section) of the Immigration and
Nationality Act which excludes from admission to the U.S. people
who are personally involved with terrorist activities,'' said State
Department spokeswoman Donna Sherman.
   Asked to specify the activities, Sherman said: ``Our information
is that as president of the provisional Sinn Fein, Mr. Adams is
personally and publicly committed to and abets the armed struggle
in Northern Ireland, and it's on that basis he was denied a visa.''
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
is outlawed on both sides of the border, although Sinn Fein is
legal.
   Adams had said on his application that he wished to travel to
the United States for ``political work,'' Sherman said.
   Martin Galvin, a spokesman for the Irish Northern Aid Committee,
said in a mailgram to The Associated Press that his group was
``outraged'' by the State Department's action, and blamed it on
pressure from Britain.
   ``We regard the continuing denial of a visa to Mr. Adams as
censorship by visa denial,'' Galvin wrote.
   The committee, also known as Noraid, charged that the State
Department was refusing ``to comply with the spirit and letter of
the new visa provisions.''
   Noraid claims to aid the victims of strife between Protestants
and Roman Catholics, but the U.S., Irish and British governments
accuse it of helping finance IRA operations.
   Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y., and Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.,
introduced an amendment last year which overturned that portion of
the McCarran Walter Act which had allowed the U.S. government to
deny visas to aliens who participate in political activities in
their native countries which would be legal for U.S. citizens in
the United States.
   However, Sherman said Adams was denied a visa based on another
part of the law that, she said, ``explicitly preserves the
authority of the executive branch to deny a visa to someone who is
involved in terrorist activity.''
   This was at least the third time that Adams, who is also a
member of British Parliament, has been denied a visa to the United
States. Earlier rebuffs occurred in June 1986 and February 1985,
Sherman said.
   In July 1986, Canada denied Adams entry because he had been
convicted of attempting to escape from prison in 1974 after being
held for two years under emergency powers.
   Adams had been trying to reach Canada after being denied a U.S.
visa to address a conference of Irish-Americans in Buffalo, N.Y.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
