<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0040EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cops-Porn     03-04 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cops-Porn,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Lose Suit Over Sex Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers from Fairfax, Calif.,
weren't libeled by an X-rated film in which actors wore the
department's uniforms, a state appeals court ruled Thursday.
   Ten past or present Fairfax officers, including a policewoman,
had sued the filmmaker, distributor and a magazine that had carried
a publicity photo from the film for libel, invasion of privacy and
emotional distress. They sought $240 million.
   But the appeals court, upholding a lower-court decision, said in
a 3-0 ruling that there was no intent to portray actual Fairfax
police officers and no danger that the public would confuse the
actors with the real officers.
   The film, ``Nightlife,'' made in 1983 by a now-defunct
filmmaker, included a segment in which two policemen agree not to
arrest two prostitutes in exchange for sex.
   Actors wore surplus Fairfax, Calif., police uniforms from a
costume store in San Francisco, the appeals court said.
   The film did not identify the location of Fairfax at a time when
there were at least six Fairfax police departments in various
states, the court said.
   The court also noted that between 90 and 105 people had been
authorized to wear the shoulder patch of the Fairfax, Calif.,
police.
</TEXT>
