<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Henryk Szeryng</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henryk Szeryng, a virtuoso violinist known for his
refreshing and moving renditions of Bach and Brahms, died Thursday
in Kassel, West Germany, of a cerebral hemorrhage. He was 69.
   Szeryng took up the violin at age 7. In 1936, he studied at the
Paris Conservatory, winning the coveted first prize. Szeryng
studied composition with the legendary Nadia Boulanger and Gabriel
Bouillon and became friends with Jean Cocteau, Pablo Picasso and
Igor Stravinsky.
   At the outbreak of World War II, Szeryng, who spoke seven
languages fluently, was made Polish Prime Minister Wladislav
Sikorski's official translator and later became a personal
goverment liaison officer.
   Renowned worldwide for a vast repertoire which he executed with
great skill and feeling during a career that spanned more than 50
years, Szeryng was to have performed Wednesday in Brussels at a
concert to benefit AIDS research.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Louis Seaton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis G. Seaton, former chief labor negotiator at
General Motors Corp., died Thursday at age 81.
   Seaton joined GM as a graphic artist in 1928, transferring to
the industrial relationship department four years later. In 1946,
he was named director of labor relations, with responsibility for
day-to-day relations with the United Auto Workers and national
contract negotiations until his retirement. He became a vice
president in 1957.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Philip Alston</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Henry Alston Jr., a confidant of former
President Jimmy Carter's and a former ambassador to Australia, died
Wednesday. He was 76.
   Alston was campaign chairman of Carter's successful bid to
become governor in 1970 and was chairman of the Committee for Jimmy
Carter when Carter was elected president in 1976.
   Carter, as governor, appointed Alston to the Board of Regents
and, as president, ambassador to Australia. He was a co-founder of
the Georgia Foundation, which raised millions of dollars for the
University of Georgia, where he received his undergraduate degree
and was co-chairman of the Joint Tech-Georgia Development Fund.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Albert Fiala</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Fiala Sr., who shot his wife to
death in a highly publicized 1985 ``mercy killing,'' committed
suicide at the age of 85.
   Fiala shot his wife of 61 years, Anna Fiala, 79, as she
experienced a severe diabetic seizure on Aug. 10, 1985.
   Two months later he was charged with second-degree murder. He
pleaded guilty. Fiala was sentenced to a year's probation and 52
weeks of community service at a Bellevue food bank.
</TEXT>
