<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has killed its Democratic
leadership's proposal for a package of ``humanitarian'' aid for the
Nicaraguan Contras, leaving the vacillating U.S. policy toward
Central America once again in limbo and the rebels without support.
   The lawmakers voted 216-208 Thursday to reject the Democrats'
$30.5 million proposal that would have provided four months' worth
of food, clothing and medical supplies to the rebels and created a
new $14 million program to aid children who are victims of the
Nicaraguan civil war.
   Forty-five Democrats, mostly liberals who oppose any aid to the
Contras, joined with Republicans, who thought the aid proposal too
weak, to deal it a fatal blow. Only five of 176 GOP members present
voted for the measure on the final ballot.
