<TEXT>
   Organizers called off a general
strike as support faded, saying a money crunch in the next few days
will paralyze the nation and keep up pressure on the government
without their help.
   ``Checks are not clearing, there is no cash and businesses
without currency cannot work, so there will be a de facto strike,''
Aurelio Barria, president of the Panamanian Chamber of Commerce,
Industry and Agriculture, told reporters Thursday.
   The work stoppage, which began Monday and was called off
Thursday night, was aimed at forcing Gen. Manuel Noriega from power
after he was fired Feb. 25 by President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
Delvalle himself was promptly dismissed the following day by an
emergency meeting of Noriega loyalists in the National Assembly.
