   Federal researchers could find no new or unusual
pathways by which AIDS spread in a study of 2,059 people who
apparently contracted the deadly disease from unknown sources, says
a report published today.
   Another new study concluded that routine screening of surgical
patients for the AIDS virus is unwarranted because it would wrongly
identify as many as 130,000 people as having the virus for every
surgeon it saved from infection.
   ``Even though surgeons are very important people, somehow
changing the lives of 130,000 people to protect one of them doesn't
seem quite right to me,'' said one of the researchers, Dr. Stephen
G. Pauker.
