<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0853EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-AnotherLook:Aerosols Adv07   03-04 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Another Look: Aerosols, Adv 07,0986</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday PMs, March 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Despite Changes, Aerosol Propellants Still An Environmental
Concern</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Evelyne in 11th graf is CQ.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRAD KROHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years after the federal government forced a
change in the stuff that makes liquid spew out of aerosol cans,
some environmentalists are worrying that it was simply a matter of
swapping one evil for another.
   ``In a sense we did,'' said Lon Burnam, clean air consultant for
the Sierra Club in Dallas. ``But you can easily make the argument
that the one that we went to is less harmful than the one that we
left.''
   Most of today's aerosol products are pushed out of the can by
hydrocarbons, a propellant that gained wide use when a government
ban on chlorofluorocarbons went into effect in March 1978.
   The order to remove CFCs from most aerosols came after
scientists found the propellants might be reaching the upper
atmosphere and thinning the ozone layer that shields people and
plants from the sun's potentially harmful ultraviolet rays.
   The hydrocarbons that replaced CFCs help form ozone _ but close
to the ground, where it contributes to the smoggy haze that scores
of cities are struggling to combat. Extended exposure is known to
cause or aggravate respiratory problems.
   Although hydrocarbons are found in much greater concentrations
in vehicle exhaust and industrial emissions, some officials under
pressure to clear the air are looking at limiting the use of
aerosols.
   ``We're beginning to run out of things we can do in the
industrial sector. We've also already done quite a bit with the
automobile,'' said Les Montgomery, director of regulation
development for the Texas Air Control Board. ``Consumer areas are
getting to be the remaining area that we haven't done too much in.''
   New York City officials, for instance, are seeking the aerosol
industry's cooperation in reducing the hydrocarbons given off by
air fresheners and spray pesticides.
   ``We'll be asking manufacturers by a specified date to submit
their own plan for reducing the ozone-creating pollutants in their
products,'' said R.W. Groneman, a spokesman for the New York State
Department of Environmental Conservation.
   New York officials expect to propose the regulations by early
April. New Jersey officials are keeping tabs on the effort,
Groneman said.
   But the aerosol industry has been opposed to further regulation
after its experience with the fluorocarbon ban _ ``the biggest
thing to hit the industry in the 1970s,'' according to Evelyne
McFeaters of the Chemical Specialties Manufacturers Association.
   The group represents about 400 makers of household products.
   ``The ban cost the industry $1 billion to retool,'' Ms.
McFeaters said. ``With this proposal, we'd be seeing an even
greater cost. They're talking about potentially billions of
dollars. The hydrocarbon propellants are the major propellants in
use.''
   Last fall, the Texas Air Control Board proposed a ban on most
aerosols in Dallas and neighboring Fort Worth, one of 14
metropolitan areas trying to develop air quality regulations
acceptable to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency.
   The 14 metro areas have been found by EPA to be in violation of
Clean Air Act standards, but they won reprieves from federal
sanctions. Now, their plans for reducing levels of ozone and other
pollutants are to take effect Aug. 31.
   Under the proposed Dallas-Fort Worth ban, state officials wanted
different propellants used or wanted stores to clear their shelves
of the hydrocarbon aerosol products, ranging from hair spray to
insecticides and paint.
   The ban on so-called Volatile Organic Compounds eventually was
scrapped because of opposition from consumers, retailers and the
aerosol industry. The industry association estimated the ban could
have cost the area more than $77 million annually in sales.
   Besides, consumers probably would have skirted the ban by
driving to neighboring counties to buy aerosols, said Ralph Engel,
president of the Chemical Specialties Manufacturing Association.
   Aerosol manufacturers are skeptical about substitute propellants
suggested to take the place of hydrocarbons.
   ``Many of the possible substitutes could actually increase the
amount of VOC (Volatile Organic Compounds) in the air,'' Ms.
McFeaters said.
   One non-aerosol alternative is the pump spray.
   ``I would think people prefer aerosols to pump sprays because of
the extra effort involved in using a pump,'' said Jim May, a
spokesman for S.C. Johnson and Co. But the Racine, Wis.-based
company had no research on consumer acceptance of pump-spray
products.
   The company, known for its Johnson's Wax products, uses
hydrocarbons _ most often propane and butane _ in more than 90
percent of its products, May said.
   Montgomery of the Texas Air Control Board says he recognizes an
aerosol ban would be difficult to enforce.
   ``It would need to be a national thing,'' he said. ``It's
unlikely to expect that a major corporation with a national or
international market is going to reformulate its propellant just
for the Dallas-Fort Worth market.''
   But Burnam noted that automakers have accommodated California's
stricter air pollution laws by offering cleaner-operating versions
of their cars in that state.
   ``It's not only practical, but a reasonable thing to do,'' he
said of banning aerosols. ``There's a whole range of products that
are a waste of the consumer's dollar and are counterproductive to
healthy living.''
   Besides aerosol air fresheners and cleaning products, the
proposed Texas ban also would have limited solvents used in house
and car paints, as well as other products that give off fumes.
   Montgomery expected similar proposed limits on consumer products
may become more widespread.
   ``If the current federal clean-air act requirements keep driving
areas to try to work on this ozone problem and, as we run out of
other things, I guess it's a type of control that other areas may
look at.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, March 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
