<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BusinessMirror Adv07   03-04 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 07,0700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday March 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>Coming Up, A Serving of Hot Potato</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House, business groups and some
political office seekers, such as George Bush, just won't let go of
the matter, and so it is seems destined to grow into a major issue.
   Issues are created by differences of opinion strongly held, and
on this there are many opinions. It is controversial, debatable,
emotional. It can be construed as a battle of haves versus
have-nots, rich vs. poor.
   The question: Should the capital gains tax, which was raised in
the Tax Reform Act of 1986, be reduced _ perhaps to a rate even
lower than before?
   Central to the issue is another question: Can revenues be raised
by cutting the capital gains tax, as the White House and Bush
suggest?
   Backers of a cut cite the U.S. Treasury's own statistics in
support of their view. They point to steady increases in revenues
since the tax was cut from 49 percent to 28 percent in 1979, and
then to 20 percent in 1981.
   In 1978, when the 49 percent maximum rate was still in effect,
tax revenue amounted to $9.1 billion. In 1984, latest year for
which figures are available, the total was $19.6 billion.
   Sharp as these statistical differences are, some critics
maintain they are not as significant as they seem. Stock market
prices, they point out, have risen sharply over the years. They say
it is this that accounts for the rise.
   Why should lower taxes raise revenues? Because, say defenders of
a lower tax, those taxpayers with capital gains wouldn't be afraid
to take them. Until those gains are realized, they observe, Uncle
Sam gets nothing at all.
   The crux of their argument is that those with big gains in
securities or other investments, including housing, decline to sell
because of the 28 percent tax liability. If it were half that, they
say, sellers would be more active.
   They contend that while this added activity would be taxed at a
relatively lower rate, the government would earn more revenue
because of the greater volume. Estimates vary, but conceivably
these gains could be sizable.
   David Burton of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce estimates a
reduction to 15 percent would produce at least $3.5 billion more
each year. Harvard economist Lawrence Lindsey puts the added
revenue at $31 billion over three years.
   One of the most formidable arguments against the reduction is
that it might produce a spurt of selling in the first couple of
years, but that the benefits to Uncle Sam would be decidedly less
dramatic after that.
   In short, say these critics, the cut itself rather than the rate
of tax is the important thing. They agree that many taxpayers would
take advantage of the cut to take postponed capital gains, but that
afterward the impact would erode.
   Defenders also contend that the country _ not just those with
capital gains _ needs lower rates in order to spur investment in
new businesses, new jobs and new technology _ which, of course,
would enlarge the revenue-producing sector.
   They indicate that as matters stand a goodly amount of potential
venture capital is tied up in old enterprises, left there by owners
who cannot afford to pay _ or who choose to defer paying _ the
taxes that would become due.
   Potentially the hottest dispute of all is the contention that a
lower capital gains tax benefits the rich and does very little, at
least immediately, for the poor. It could be a dispute loaded with
more passion than content.
   Prof. Lindsey states that 80 percent of the $31 billion he
refers to would be paid by taxpayers with incomes greater than
$100,000. Inherent in that statement, however, is that most of the
tax benefits would go to them also.
   The subject is at the heart of at least two bills in Congress.
Over the next few months, it could become a political hot potato.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday March 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Hungary-Austerity Adv10   03-04 0921</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Austerity, Adv 10,0950</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, March 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mood is Bleak in Hungary as Austerity Program Takes Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just when the winds blowing from the
Soviet Union bring the refreshing possibility of greater openness
and reform, Hungarians find their once-vaunted economy faltering.
   The government is warning them to expect a decline in living
standards, regarded as the best in the East bloc.
   All that combined with uncertainty over the tenure of the
75-year-old Communist Party leader Janos Kadar is leaving
Hungarians in a bleak and wary mood.
   Yet, the outward signs of economic trouble are few in this
lovely capital on the Danube. Shops along the glittering Vaci
pedestrian mall are well-stocked and bustling, traffic clamors
along the old Chain Bridge with BMWs and Hondas vying with
Soviet-made Fiats and Czech Skodas, and women are dressed in
stylish furs.
   ``It's only in the windows,'' said a Budapest businessman.
   Scratch beneath the surface, he added, and it becomes apparent
that times are getting harder.
   A government austerity program took effect Jan. 1, imposing the
East bloc's first personal income tax and value-added tax. In
addition, the government says inflation could rise from last year's
8 to 9 percent to 15 percent this year, which would make it the
worst in the country's postwar history.
   Compared to some nations in Eastern Europe, Hungary remains an
island of prosperity and economic stability. Poland is expecting
inflation of 40 to 45 percent this year. Inflation in Yugoslavia
reached 170 percent this past fall.
   But Hungary's economic woes arose over the last few years with
``breathtaking suddenness,'' one party member said. ``Therefore we
are bitter.''
   The three-year ``program of consolidation,'' as the austerity
measures are called, is intended to raise revenues to bridge
yawning government deficits, caused largely by huge subsidies to
money-losing industries.
   The government plans to phase out unprofitable factories,
raising fears of increasing unemployment. Some analysts say the
jobless total could rise from 10,000 (0.2 percent) today to 200,000
(3.3 percent) of the 6-million-member work force.
   Hungary borrowed in the 1970s to build heavy industry. Now, its
10.6 million people are burdened with a gross hard currency debt of
$16 billion, the highest per capita in the Soviet bloc.
   On the positive side, exports to the West in 1987 were up 13
percent to $5.08 billion and tourism boomed, with more than 18
million people visiting the country. Hungary's state-dominated
agriculture continues to produce more than the country can consume.
   The austerity program is the work of 57-year-old Prime Minister
Karoly Grosz, who took over government administration in July.
Since then, he has discussed Hungary's problems with a frankness
that surprised many of his countrymen.
   Acknowledging calls for greater democratization, a Communist
Party committee has promulgated a set of theses on political
reforms and the party's ``leading role'' which has been presented
to basic party cells and is to be put before a Central Committee
meeting.
   If approved, the proposals would probably be forwarded to the
first national party conference since 1957, which a party source
said is expected early in June.
   The theses generally endorse greater consultation between the
party and the population, more open debate in the party and a
retreat from day-to-day party involvement in the government.
   Diplomats said the theses appear to generate little enthusiasm.
Members of the unofficial opposition said they are disappointed by
the proposals, calling them too vague to bring substantial change.
   ``There are many words about the necessity of political reform,
but I am afraid that the speeches are not so sincere,'' said Gyorgy
Gado, an opposition writer. ``I am afraid they haven't the courage
to make the necessary changes.''
   Meanwhile, the question on everybody's mind is whether Kadar
will retire and who will take his place as head of the party, a
senior Western diplomat said.
   Behind-the-scenes jockeying for position is practically
paralyzing the government, the diplomat added. ``Nobody does
anything except politics right now.''
   Grosz is considered the leading candidate and the favorite of
the Soviets, even though his relations with party regulars and the
coterie around Kadar appear strained, said the diplomat, speaking
only on condition of anonymity.
   Also mentioned as possible successors are chief party ideologist
Janos Berecz and, as a darkhorse, Imre Pozsgay, the leader of the
national unity People's Patriotic Front, who advocates more
dialogue with groups outside the party.
   Kadar has been at the helm of the party since the Soviet
suppression of the 1956 Hungarian Revolution. Described variously
by diplomats in Budapest as ``a wily old fox'' and ``a declining
king surrounded by courtiers,'' he has given no known indication
that he will step aside.
   But sources in and outside the party said Kadar increasingly is
out of touch with economic problems and is an obstacle to political
reform.
   ``He has not been a bad dictator. Even if you disagreed with him
you could work,'' said a party member. ``Now people want results.''
   ``People feel as long as he's in power no real changes can
happen,'' said Ferenc Koszeg, editor of the illegal magazine
Beszelo (Talker).
   And the public mood?
   ``Very gloomy,'' said the diplomat. ``Compared to a year ago,
the situation is closer to instability, although I still believe
it's less than a 50-50 chance.''
   Said Koszeg: ``People are so disappointed that they don't
believe anybody any longer. This is an important handicap both for
the government and the opposition.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, March 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Ford Adv09   03-04 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Ford, Adv 09,0667</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, March 9 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Indiana Jones Finds More Mature Roles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BEARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Star Wars'' and ``Raiders of the Lost Ark''
made Harrison Ford one of America's top box office draws, but the
actor says both he and his audience are maturing.
   ``I'm not an ingenue anymore,'' the 45-year-old actor said.
   His most recent effort leaves Han Solo and Indiana Jones in
hyperspace. In the just-released Roman Polanski thriller,
``Frantic,'' Ford's cocksure quality disappears as he portrays a
bespectacled father and husband caught in a situation beyond his
control.
   It follows ``Witness'' and ``The Mosquito Coast,'' two other
movies where Ford shucked invulnerability for more complex and
sensitive roles. In his next film, the Mike Nichols comedy
``Working Girls,'' he has a Cary Grant-type part.
   ``I'm not trying to make a transition into a different kind of
persona; I do whatever I think is appropriate for that character to
tell the story,'' he said during a recent interview.
   ``But this is also related to growing older,'' he said,
fingering his reading glasses in his right hand. ``I mean, `Star
Wars' was almost 15 years ago. I am 15 years older. There's no
sense denying it. In fact, I revel in it. I've been more interested
in those characters that are more mature.''
   In ``Frantic,'' Ford grows more uncomfortable in every scene. He
plays a California heart surgeon at a medical conference in Paris.
Terrorists kidnap his wife, but police and U.S. officials believe
she willingly left him. He meets a sensuous young French woman who
provides clues to the abduction and joins him in a struggle to find
his wife.
   ``The whole thing depends on this doctor, this fish out of
water, reaching this emotional exhaustion, where he does things
that are well outside of his nature and experience,'' said Ford.
   A concern for his real-life wife's safety led Ford to Paris,
Polanski and the part. He accompanied his pregnant wife,
screenwriter Melissa Mathison (``E.T.''), to meetings in Paris on
an another project with Polanski, the director of ``Tess,''
``Chinatown'' and ``Rosemary's Baby.''
   ``After the first few days, Roman described the film to me and
it sounded interesting,'' Ford said.
   The script was in French, a language the actor does not speak.
``Roman stood up and for two hours _ he told me the movie,'' Ford
said. ``He played all the parts, and he was great. When it was
over, I said, `If you'll right that down in English, I'll do it.'''
   Ford calls himself ``mono-maniacal'' during filming, but always
returns to his ranch in Wyoming to ``go grocery shopping, pick up
the laundry, work on the fence, plow the snow, read a little, fish
a little and go cross-country skiing.''
   Wyoming is now home for Ford. He was raised in a suburban
Chicago, went to school at Ripon College in Wisconsin and struggled
as an actor and carpenter in southern California. ``Star Wars''
gave him the success and security to buy the ranch and spend some
time there.
   ``I wouldn't be able to do it (acting) if I wasn't able to get
back when it was over,'' he said.
   His current project is ``Working Girls,'' a comedy set in New
York about a secretary who fights to retrieve an idea from a boss
who has claimed credit for it.
   ``One of the pleasures of this comedy is that it's a relatively
smaller part,'' said Ford, who called the last two pictures
``killers.'' In ``Working Girls,'' he plays the boyfriend of
Melanie Griffith and Sigourney Weaver.
   This fall, production begins on a third ``Raiders'' movie. When
that's over, Ford will head back to his wife, his 10-month-old son,
Malcolm, and the ranch.
   And then?
   ``I'm planning to take the next year off,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed, March 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1449EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:CelebrityActivists Adv10   03-04 1027</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Celebrity Activists, Adv 10,1057</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, March 10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Brat Packers and Glamour Girls _ The New Hollywood Politicos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Rob Lowe is best known for his ``Brat
Pack'' movie roles and romances with actress Melissa Gilbert and
Princess Stephanie of Monaco.
   But the heartthrob of the teeny-bopper set also is an active
crusader against toxic wastes.
   He and other young screen actors, such as Ally Sheedy, Judd
Nelson, Daphne Zuniga and Alexandra Paul, are just a few of
Hollywood's new breed of celebrity political activists.
   ``They represent a new generation of artists who have, like
athletes, a tremendous effect at being role models for young
people,'' said California Assemblyman Tom Hayden.
   ``They're taken more seriously with Americans than politicians
because people know them. ... It's a very healthy tonic for an
apathetic generation.''
   Hayden was a founder of Students for a Democratic Society, one
of the most visible student radical organizations of the 1960s, and
is the husband of actress Jane Fonda, another celebrity activist.
   In 1985, the Haydens became curious about the true interests of
the so-called Brat Packers, who had been labeled selfish and
self-centered by critics. They invited a few to their Santa Monica
home, including Tom Cruise, Kelly McGillis, Demi Moore, Emilio
Estevez, Gilbert, Nelson and Lowe.
   Once the Haydens saw an interest was there, they formed Network,
an educational group that explains political issues to actors and
introduces them to politicians.
   ``They are incredibly effective at motivating and opening up
your minds,'' Sheedy said of the couple. ``It's not something where
they're trying to brainwash you in any way. There's no pressure at
all.''
   Her involvement in Network prompted the young star of ``War
Games'' and ``The Breakfast Club'' to throw a mixer with Sen. Alan
Cranston (D-Calif.) for her actor friends.
   ``It was so much fun. It was so exciting,'' Sheedy said.
   Another Hollywood activist group, Young Artists United, was
formed two years ago by Paul, who starred in ``Dragnet,'' and
filmmaker Daniel Sladek. YAU involves young people in such social
issues as teen suicide and drug and alcohol abuse, rather than
political issues.
   Some YAU members include Sarah Jessica Parker, star of TV's ``A
Year in the Life,'' Eric Stoltz of ``Mask'' and most of the Network
members.
   YAU plans to put about 30 of the young actors on a bus caravan
this April and cruise the Southern California beach communities,
urging young people to register to vote.
   ``I think there's a major transformation going on in the people
of this generation from the `me' generation to the `we' generation.
They realize they can accomplish a lot united,'' said the
23-year-old Sladek.
   For fear of alienating their fans, actors generally remained
aloof from politics until the 1930s, when Hollywood threw its
support behind President Roosevelt and his social policies.
   Hollywood staged massive support for World War II, with war bond
rallies and entertaining the troops abroad. Some notables,
especially Charlie Chaplin, supported the Soviet cause, and their
activities would haunt them later.
   The postwar period brought McCarthyism, when many careers were
harmed or ruined through ``blacklisting'' by association with
leftist causes. The reaction caused many actors to eschew support
of any issues or candidates, and continued into the 1960s.
   However, the Civil Rights Movement brought out such actors as
Marlon Brando on marches, sit-ins and rallies. The Vietnam War,
environmental issues and women's rights also rekindled Hollywood's
social consciousness.
   This will be a busy year for Network, said spokesman Patrick
Lippert. Members will start meeting presidential candidates at
private meetings in the spring and will probably become active in
the 1988 elections.
   Last September, members of both groups worked against Robert
Bork's confirmation to the U.S. Supreme Court by staging a
post-card writing campaign with their peers.
   In October, Nelson (``Billionaire Boys Club,'' ``The Breakfast
Club''), Helen Slater (``Supergirl''), Esai Morales (``La Bamba'')
and Mary Stuart Masterson (``At Close Range'') traveled to the
Soviet Union to film a documentary for the National Committee for a
Sane Nuclear Policy.
   Zuniga (``Spaceballs'') and Paul visited Nicaragua, where Paul
rode in a Soviet-made helicopter with Sandinistas.
   ``Everyone was saying two years ago this is the most
self-centered, selfish generation in years,'' Lippert said. ``But
what you see is the most idealistic group of young people. You see
them getting involved in so many things, and reaching out to their
generation.''
   However, not all Hollywood observers are jumping with praise for
the political meanderings of brat packers.
   ``It's striking that not one of these stars has a dissenting
view other than what's the norm in Hollywood,'' said Michael Medved
of PBS' ``Sneak Previews.''
   ``It's absolutely nonsensical that Alan Cranston should follow
Rob Lowe's advice to vote against Robert Bork for the Supreme
Court,'' he continued. ``Rob Lowe, Daphne Zuniga and Gregory Peck
(who did an anti-Bork commercial) _ we take their position
seriously because they're pretty. It's scary.
   ``I think they are sincerely interested in the issues. But part
of burnishing your image is not to be written off as a pretty-face
airhead. So you become politically involved.''
   Also dabbling in politics are such Hollywood glamour girls as
Morgan Fairchild, Donna Mills and Sally Field.
   Field, a two-time Academy Award winner, was host of a poolside
party at her home that featured Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
a presidential contender. Mills, the scheming vixen of CBS-TV's
``Knots Landing,'' talked politics with Sen. Paul Simon (D-Ill.),
another presidential hopeful, at a gathering at her home.
   Fairchild, who has testified before both the House and Senate on
environmental issues, has given up needlepoint and instead spends
her free time reading such weighty material as ``Abu Nidal: Master
Terrorist'' or hefty medical reports on the deadly AIDS virus.
   ``I know that going in, a lot of people didn't take me
seriously,'' said Fairchild, who has no intention of giving up her
sexy image. ``But I have a deceptively high I.Q. and so when people
sat down and started talking to me about some of these things, they
started to take me seriously.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, March 10</NOTE>
