<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 07,0609</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, March 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Some Market Analysts Still Leery of `Bear Trap'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the stock market has rallied in recent
months from its drastic drop last year, some wary analysts caution
that it is still following the pattern set in 1929 and 1930.
   After the Great Crash in October 1929, the market regained its
balance and recovered nearly 50 percent of its losses. But that
rise turned out to be a deadly trap.
   By the time stock prices finally bottomed out in 1932, they were
down about 90 percent from their peaks. A drop of the same
magnitude today would put the Dow Jones industrial average at about
275.
   No market analyst with a wide following on Wall Street is
currently predicting anything close to that. Along with the
similarities, most observers say, there are many differences in the
world of the 1980s from the situation that prevailed nearly 60
years ago.
   Furthermore, they say, if history were prone to repeating itself
with any reliability in the market, the pursuit of making money in
stocks would be a lot easier than it is.
   Still, a good many people in the business of giving financial
advice are very mindful these days of what is now known as the
``sucker rally'' of early 1930.
   ``The entire price action of the past few years has tracked the
1928-1930 span like clockwork,'' says Martin Zweig, a New York
investment adviser, in the current issue of his letter The Zweig
Forecast.
   ``The odds that this is the start of a new bull market are
remote at the moment,'' he argues.
   Eric Miller, chief investment officer at Donaldson, Lufkin &
Jenrette Securities, says stocks at their recent prices reflect
some hopes about the economic outlook that may go unfulfilled.
   ``We think the probability of a recession, and perhaps a severe
one, is fairly high,'' he observes, ``and we also think that the
current level of stock prices does not discount a recession.''
   Optimists on the market outlook, whose numbers have been growing
lately, describe the recent behavior of stocks as healthy-looking.
   One distinct positive, they say, is that many smaller stocks
have been rising faster lately than the blue chips that make up the
Dow Jones industrial average, after lagging behind through the
latter stages of the 1982-87 bull market. In theory at least, that
betokens broad support for stocks.
   Zweig says he is well aware of this view, but questions its
validity. In the first three months of 1930, he says, a broad
measure of stock prices he calculated rose 24.9 percent, while the
Dow was up 15.3 percent.
   ```Positive' divergence, as most call it, is normal after
crashes which lead to continuing bear markets,'' he says.
   Both Zweig and Miller acknowledge the possibility that they are
wrong, and both hold some stocks in their recommended portfolios.
   As Zweig put it: ``If this turns out to be a bull market, which
I doubt, then fine. We own stocks now. If it's a bear rally, I'll
look for exit signs as we go.''
   Should the advance turn out to be a ``sucker rally'' like the
one in 1930, Zweig concedes it will be a tricky mission to pluck
the bait out before the trap snaps shut.
   ``I suspect that the rally, which looks OK on the tape, will
continue to look good. Why? To trap the maximum number of people
for the next decline.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday editions, March 7</NOTE>
