<1ST_LINE>s i BC-PanamainCrisis Adv06-2Takes   03-04 1085</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Panama in Crisis, Adv 06 - 2 Takes,1112</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nine Months Of Civil Strife Bring Panama to The Brink</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   First El Salvador, then Nicaragua, now Panama.
Like chain reactions, crises spread through Central America.
Despite protests, despite U.S. pressure, Panama's military leader,
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the real boss of the country, remains
in power, surviving charges of drug dealing, illicit money
laundering, election fraud and violations of human rights. Here is
a look at how it all came about in a country the United States
deems vital to its security.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Panamanians have lived for years
with the belief, if not the sure knowledge, that their government
is corrupt, their elections are unfair and their leaders lust for
money and power.
   There were protests from time to time, but they seldom lasted
more than a few days. Then the nation would sink back into a
tropical lethargy abetted by prosperity. The voices of opposition
were few.
   Now the lethargy seems to be gone.
   The country is in turmoil over the military rule of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, who has been indicted in the United States on drug
charges. Prosperity is threatened by a large foreign debt, U.S.
economic pressure and the freezing of Panamanian funds abroad.
   In recent years, money poured in from the Panama Canal, the new
offshore banking center, an oil pipeline that helped carry Alaskan
crude to Atlantic Coast markets, a thriving re-export industry and
a large U.S. military presence.
   It all helped an economy traditionally based on bananas, sugar
and coffee weather the ups and downs of unstable agricultural
markets, and made Panama by far the wealthiest country on the
Central American isthmus.
   ``They were years of indulgence and indifference,'' says Roberto
Brenes, a Panama City investment banker and a leader of the broad
new opposition movement that took firm root only nine months ago.
   ``The rich were getting richer, the middle class was growing and
the lot of the poor was improving,'' said a diplomat with long
experience in Central America. ``It's always been a tolerant
society, and few people saw any need to rock to the boat.''
   Neither did the United States, which saw in Panama enough
stability to make a treaty in 1977 that will deliver control of the
vital canal between the Atlantic and Pacific to the Panamanian
government at the turn of the century.
   Omar Torrijos Herrera, a charismatic army colonel, seized the
government in 1968, broke the traditional rule of wealthy merchants
and land barons and began a costly series of reforms.
   He built schools, schools, hospitals, health clinics,
farm-to-market roads and other public works. With fervent
nationalism, Torrijos brought a new sense of pride and identity to
the country, even its wealthiest citizens.
   Much of his popularity came from his ability to tweak Uncle
Sam's nose while maintaining relations with Washington. Few
Panamanian leaders had risked the slightest impertinance with the
United States.
   His ideology became known as ``Torrijismo'' and survived his
death in an airplane crash in 1981, four years after he signed the
canal treaty with President Jimmy Carter and fulfilled one of the
fondest dreams of the Panamanian people.
   Although the country maintained the fiction of a president,
Torrijos ruled supreme as ``chief of government'' and commander of
the National Guard. He had no real opposition and the nation
prospered from economic growth and public spending financed with
money borrowed abroad.
   Noriega came to power in 1983, four years after Torrijos was
killed, and the first presidential election since the 1968 coup was
held the following year.
   Nicolas Ardito Barletta, a respected economist, was elected
president despite the fact that he had spent years with the World
Bank in Washington and was little known at home.
   His election, by a margin of fewer than 2,000 votes, was tainted
by charges of fraud. Opponents held marches and auto caravans,
honking horns, waving white banners and banging pots and pans in a
traditional Panamanian form of protest.
   Like those before them, the demonstrations died within a week.
   The United States and the rest of the world recognized Ardito
Barletta, as they had six other figurehead presidents installed and
removed by the military since 1968. The first vice president was
Eric Arturo Delvalle, in his first elective office.
   Less than a year later, in September 1985, it became Ardito
Barletta's turn to go.
   He was summoned to military headquarters and held for 12 hours
after calling for an impartial investigation into the murder of
Hugo Spadafora, one of Noriega's chief opponents. Ardito Barletta
announced his resignation and Delvalle was sworn in to replace him.
   Once again, government upheaval was greeted largely by public
apathy.
   Noriega kept building his power, increasing the size of the
military with the help of the United States.
   Washington poured millions of dollars into the general's newly
renamed Panama Defense Forces, a single command encompassing 15,000
members of the army, air force, navy, police forces and state
security agency in this nation of 2.2 million people.
   The canal treaty gives Panama primary responsibility for the
security of the waterway beginning with the year 2000. The Carter
administration, then President Reagan, wanted the Defense Forces to
be up to the task.
   Rumors of military corruption recurred. Then Col. Roberto Diaz
Herrera, one of Noriega's top aides, told reporters last June after
his forced resignation that his former boss had rigged the 1984
elections, was engaged in the illegal selling of visas and had
engineered the Spadafora murder.
   Spadafora's headless, mutilated body was found in August 1985,
stuffed in a canvas U.S. Mail bag just across the border in Costa
Rica. He had threatened to offer proof of Noriega's involvement in
drug trafficking, and his family and friends insisted the general
ordered the brutal murder.
   Until Diaz Herrera began talking, however, no one in the
military's tight inner circle had accused Noriega of so much as
fixing a traffic ticket.
   The former aide's frequent press interviews caused a sensation
They also spawned the National Civic Crusade, a movement begun by a
few wealthy businessmen whose disgust and anger at the military's
increasingly heavy-handed interference in the government and
economy had been building for some time.
   Within weeks, the Crusade grew to an umbrella organization
covering about 200 professional, business, labor and political
groups and had gained support from Panamanians of the middle and
lower classes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1409EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-PanamainCrisis Adv06-1stAdd   03-04 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Panama in Crisis, Adv 06-1st Add,0539</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>PANAMA CITY: lower classes.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Crusade called its first strike June 10. It had little
success but was followed by others and a series of mass protests,
despite a state of emergency decree that forbade public gatherings
and closed opposition newspapers and broadcast stations.
   By July 10, Noriega had enough. He sent soldiers and riot police
to break up a mass rally. More than 100 people were injured, many
peppered by birdshot, and up to 600 were arrested and detained for
four days.
   The movement appeared to lose heart, but bounced back with a
successful strike in late July and a rally Aug. 6 that attracted
30,000 anti-Noriega demonstrators, despite the threat of
repression. Leaders of the Civic Crusade began seeking foreign
support.
   Delvalle's government responded with pro-Noriega rallies and
increasingly virulent attacks on the United States in speeches and
government-owned newspapers.
   It all was done under the cloak of ``Torrijismo,'' but the
garment did not fit Noriega well. In late August, a Gallup poll
indicated three of four Panamanians wanted him to step down.
   After an attack on the U.S. Embassy in June, the Reagan
administration had suspended all military and economic aid, which
would have totaled $21 million this year. That brought howls of
``economic aggression'' from Delvalle and other Panamanian leaders.
   Loss of the aid was particularly painful because Panama faced a
fiscal crisis, brought on by years of deficit spending that piled
up a $4.5 billion foreign debt and capital flight caused by the
civil unrest.
   Early in February, two federal grand juries in Florida indicted
Noriega on charges of drug trafficking, money laundering and
racketeering.
   Among other things, he is accused of helping Colombia's
notorious Medellin Cartel by providing safe airstrips for its
cocaine shipments and safe haven for its hired killers.
   ``What he did was utilize his position to sell the country of
Panama to the traffickers,'' said U.S. Atty. Leon Kellner of Miami,
who led the investigation for one indictment.
   Events began unfolding rapidly Feb. 25 when Delvalle, scorned by
the opposition as a puppet, decided he had had enough and ordered
Noriega's dismissal. The United States said it knew of his
intentions, and continued to recognize him as president through the
ensuing trouble.
   Noriega arranged for the Legislative Assembly to remove Delvalle
the next day _ the special session lasted 10 minutes _ and hours
later Devalle went into hiding.
   The Civic Crusade called another strike, its sixth, last Monday
but acknowledged it would not be enough to drive Noriega from
office even the country closed down completely.
   Opposition leaders said only the United States, with or without
the support of the rest of Latin America, had the financial clout
to depose him.
   At week's end, Roberto Aleman, a lawyer and Civic Crusade
leader, summed up the alliance's hopes:
   ``The government will find itself besieged by economic and
diplomatic measures taken in the United States and Latin America.
The measures will oblige the regime to take extremely unpopular
measures such as raising taxes and firing public employees.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
