<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-ArtSleuth Adv06   03-04 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Art Sleuth, Adv 06,0629</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>City Detective Makes Art Theft His Full-Time Job, Passion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Art Theft, b0359</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUD S. BEELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Moscardini talks of Manet and Warhol in
the same breath as undercover stings and doing time.
   For the New York City police detective, the two are as
inextricably linked as oil and canvas.
   Moscardini, an art history student and former undercover
narcotics agent, works full time on recovering the stolen art of
galleries, museums and patrons. His contacts are Interpol, the U.S.
Customs Service, art associations and the art underworld, along
with an unspecified number of paid informants.
   He's part of an elite fraternity of full-time art sleuths, who
range in number to perhaps a half-dozen, depending on the criteria
used to define them.
   Since moving more than four years ago from the dim back alleys
of undercover drugs to the grand halls and cozy galleries of the
art world, the 42-year-old detective has created something of a
name for himself.
   Among the artworks he's recovered was a $500,000 Joan Miro. ``My
best piece was a $1 million Renoir,'' he says.
   ``He's great,'' says Elizabeth Hayt-Atkins, director of art
theft archives at the New York-based International Foundation for
Art Research. ``He plays the part of the knowledgeable art person
very well. He knows the lingo. He knows the artists. So I imagine
when he goes undercover he's perfectly plausible.''
   Moscardini looks the part: trim, impeccably groomed down to his
manicured nails, articulate and art-wise. The only give-away that
he's anything but a connoisseur is the 9mm semi-automatic that
hangs from his lizard-skin belt.
   ``The same gun as James Bond used,'' he quips.
   And he knows the role.
   A frequent weekend visitor to New York's Metropolitan Museum of
Art, because it's ``one of those places you have to go to quite
often,'' Moscardini himself dabbles in oils and acrylics. He also
is studying for an art history degree and has lectured on museum
security the last three years at the Smithsonian Institution.
   Moscardini at one time wanted to be a commercial artist. He went
into police work more than 19 years ago, he says, because he needed
a job.
   When the department went looking for a savvy investigator with
an art background, the computer search turned up Moscardini among
the possibilities.
   The detective is full of tales of mostly all-purpose thieves,
sometimes ignorant of the art they steal or the art world, who've
been snared in one of his traps, usually set up in an obliging
gallery staffed with undercover officers.
   Moscardini's own undercover work is probably over now, he says.
``I am known out there. My photo's been around.''
   He estimates only 10 percent to 14 percent of stolen art
worldwide is recovered.
   Although he figures he's recovered $8 million worth of works
over the years, there are millions, too, in unresolved mysteries.
The most recent is the $6 million heist last month from the
Colnaghi Art Gallery, New York's biggest art steal.
   His small office is filled with his work and passion: file
cabinets stuffed with artists' and gallery names, folders each for
missing oil paintings, water colors, folk art, photography; auction
books from Sotheby's and Christie's. Breaking the monotony of the
institutional-white walls, he has hung an Andy Warhol silk-screen
print, a Claude Monet impression and an Erte art deco poster. A
family heirloom Chinese brass vase sits on a file cabinet.
   ``I don't consider myself just a cop. I consider myself a part
of the art world,'' Moscardini said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
