<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-04 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0548</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales by the nation's largest general retailers were
unexpectedly slow in February, prompting worries that year-old
sluggishness in the retail sector has yet to run its course.
   The nation's largest retailer, Sears, Roebuck and Co., said
Thursday its sales rose 2.5 percent from February 1987. K mart said
its overall sales were up 0.8 percent, but sales at stores open at
least a year fell 1.6 percent.
   ``The results do not bode well for the economy,'' said Fred
Wintzer, a retail industry analyst for the investment firm Alex.
Brown & Sons Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Led by industry-leader General Motors Corp.,
automakers sold 25 percent more domestic cars and light trucks in
late February than a year ago, the car companies have reported.
   GM said Thursday its sales during the last third of February
were the highest for late February since 1972.
   In the seven selling days from Feb. 21-29, GM sold 127,549
domestic cars, up 33.4 percent from a year ago, and 59,709 domestic
light trucks, up 46.2 percent from a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Motors Corp. has decided not to sell its
Acustar Inc. parts-making subsidiary but says it will close or sell
four plants within the next 18 months.
   The No. 3 automaker said Thursday that the four plants _ Amplex
Van Wert in Van Wert, Ohio, Trenton Chemical in suburban Detroit,
Detroit Forge and Detroit Trim _ employ about 2,000 workers.
   The United Auto Workers union said it was pleased by the
decision but urged Chrysler to find ways not to close the four
plants.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Improvements in the nation's efficiency in
churning out goods and services slowed by almost half last year
despite revised figures showing higher output in the the fourth
quarter, the government said.
   The Labor Department said Thursday that productivity among
non-farm businesses responsible for three-fourths of the nation's
economic activity rose at an annual rate of 0.3 percent in the
fourth quarter in contrast to a deterioration of 0.2 percent
reported in preliminary figures last month.
   The revisions raised the productivity improvement for the entire
year from 0.8 percent to 0.9 percent, slightly more than half the
1.6 percent gain of 1986, despite the lowest hourly labor cost
increases in more than four decades.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled House labor
standards subcommittee has voted along party lines to increase the
minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.65 an hour over the next three years.
   The 6-3 vote Thursday came on a measure to raise the minimum
wage 50 cents an hour on Jan. 1, 1989 and 40 cents an hour each of
the following years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's sanctions against Japanese
electronics imports have halted computer chip ``dumping'' but have
failed to boost sales of U.S. chips in Japan, according to an
industry group.
   The Semiconductor Industry Association said Thursday that by the
end of 1987, the U.S. share of the Japanese chip market was 10
percent, up only slightly from the 9 percent share that existed
when the sanctions were announced last April.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
