<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0535</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. has raised its hostile bid for
controlling interest in Farmers Group Inc., coming up with a $4.5
billion offer for the nation's seventh largest insurer.
   The $63-per-share proposal was made Thursday as a tender offer
to Farmers' shareholders instead of to the board of directors
because the board ``has regrettably refused to talk to us so far,''
said Batus Chairman Patrick Sheehy.
   The Los Angeles-based insurance concern had rejected the
Louisville company's initially proposed $60-a-share, or $4.2
billion, buyout offer on Jan. 20.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by a British construction firm has
launched an unsolicited tender offer for Koppers Co. Inc. that
values the construction and chemicals company at about $1.3 billion.
   The Pittsburgh-based Koppers declined to comment on Thursday's
offer, but traders on Wall Street speculated the bidding might go
higher by sending the price of Koppers' stock well above the $45 a
share offer to $51.75 a share.
   The bid was made by a concern called BNS Inc., whose biggest
shareholder is Beazer PLC, a London-based general construction
company that owns 49 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major airlines have raised fares for the second
time in about two weeks, reflecting unexpected strength in
passenger traffic despite the usually slow winter season.
   The latest move was initiated Thursday by Continental Airlines,
which boosted one-way regular coach fares in amounts ranging from
$7 for short flights to $45 for longer trips.
   American, United and Northwest airlines immediately announced
they would match Continental's regular coach-fare increases in
markets where they compete.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department has proposed a
wide range of drug tests for more than a half million airline
employees from pilots to mechanics, although officials said they
have no clear evidence of a drug problem in the industry.
   Thursday's announcement of the drug testing program, which would
go into effect after what may be a lengthy rulemaking process, came
amid conflicting court cases on whether such tests are legal. A
federal judge earlier this week declared random drug tests of
civilian Army employees as unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir says it has agreed to buy 50 Boeing 737
jetliners with options for 30 additional aircraft, a deal worth
$2.4 billion if all the options are exercised.
   Delivery of the new jets will begin in April 1989 and continue
through December 1991, the airline said Thursday.
   The twin-engine, short-to-medium range aircraft is the most
popular jet ever sold by Seattle-based Boeing Co. The deal with
USAir brings to 2,001 Boeing 737s on order.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mixed Thursday in an
inconclusive session marked by intense takeover speculation and
some selling of blue chips. The Dow Jones average of 30 big-name
industrials slipped 7.80 to 2,063.49.
   Bond prices barely budged in lethargic trading.
   The dollar ended mixed against most key currencies, while gold
prices fell. Some cattle futures prices plunged the 1{-cent limit
allowed for daily trading, and grain and soybean futures and energy
futures also fell.
</TEXT>
