<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PopularAds     03-04 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Popular Ads,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Survey Rates California Raisin Ads as Most Popular in
1987</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The best-liked commercials of 1987 included some
starring performances from animated characters such as dancing clay
raisins, a hamburger chain's moonman and a pizza company's dreaded
foil called a Noid.
   Few of the commercials mentioned most often by consumers polled
by Video Storyboard Tests Inc. featured traditional show business
celebrities, the head of the consumer research firm said Thursday.
   ``We seem to heading into a period when we see more created
celebrities, not necessarily human beings, in commercials,'' said
David Vadehra, president of Video Storyboard, in relasing the
results of the firm's 10th annual survey.
   He said that may be partly due to growing dissatisfaction with
the costs and risks associated with using celebrities. The trend
occurs even as admakers for some cars, office phone systems,
computers and insurance products have tried to replicate realistic
situations and dialogue in their commercials.
   Video Storyboard, which is based in New York, interviewed more
than 25,000 people about what commercials they liked best last year.
   Leading the list was the campaign for California raisins, which
used clay models of raisins dancing to the sounds of Motown music
in a construction worker's lunchbox and across the kitchen counter.
   The ads took top billing despite relatively modest spending of
$5.4 million to put them on television. The survey said makers of
other well-liked ads spent as much as $344 million (McDonald's
Corp.) on television placements.
   Second was Bud Light beer commercials, many of which featured
the English bull terrier Spuds MacKenzie while others offered
numerous variations of what can go wrong if you simply order a
``light'' without specifying the brand.
   The ad campaign for Pepsi soft drinks placed third, and Miller
Lite beer commercials were fourth.
   Ads for McDonald's restaurants came in fifth. The campaign
included some commercials that featured a piano-playing character
shaped like a moon crescent who extolled dinner at McDonald's to
the tune from ``Mac the Knife.''
   The stars of sixth-ranked Bartles & Jaymes wine cooler ads are a
pair of non-actors who were persuaded to pose as the brand's owners.
   Ads for Coca-Cola soft drinks, which placed seventh, include
some with the computer-generated character Max Headroom.
   Rounding out the Top 10 were ads for Isuzu automobiles, DuPont
carpeting and Domino's Pizza, which features an animated clay
character called the Noid.
   Consumers didn't turn completely sour on celebrity-filled ads.
Jell-O dessert ads with actor Bill Cosby placed 11th. But Cosby
couldn't keep Kodak film from dropping off the list of the 25 most
popular campaigns.
   Another casualty in 1987 was Burger King advertising, which fell
out of the top 25 for the first time in five years with advertising
billing it as ``The Best Food for Fast Times.'' The chain recently
dumped the theme, changed ad agencies and is pitching the taste of
its flame-broiled hamburgers in new ads.
   Another hamburger chain, Wendy's, placed 12th with an ad
campaign that spoofed taste tests by having customers pick a
pre-cooked hamburger over a freshly cooked Wendy's burger for some
very strange reasons.
   Next were campaigns for Levi's jeans, Kibbles 'n Bits dog food,
Seagrams wine coolers, Michelob beer and Oscar Meyer meats.
   The Partnership for Drug-Free America, a campaign aimed at
discouraging illegal drug use, was the first public service
campaign to place in the top 25, finishing 18th.
   Rounding out the top 25 were ads for Chevrolet cars, Lucky Dog
dog food, Angel Soft tissue, Energizer batteries, Sprite soft
drinks, Tender Chops dog food and Long John Silver restaurants.
</TEXT>
