<1ST_LINE>r f PM-KoppersBid Bjt   03-04 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers Bid, Bjt,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shearson, British Company Offer $1.3 Billion for Koppers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Koppers Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. Inc., a huge construction and
chemicals concern, has offered no reply to an unsolicited $1.3
billion takeover bid from a group led by a major British
contruction company and a U.S. investment firm.
   But traders on Wall Street seem to think the bidding might go
higher, and sent the price of Koppers' stock well above the $45 a
share offer.
   Koppers rose $6.62{ a share to close at $51.75 on Thursday on
the New York Stock Exchange. It was the sixth most-actively traded
stock with 3.1 million shares changing hands.
   The tender offer for Koppers was launched Thursday by a concern
called BNS Inc., whose biggest shareholder is Beazer PLC, a
London-based general construction company that owns 49 percent of
BNS.
   Other participants in BNS are subsidiaries of Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., a New York-based investment firm that reportedly owns
about 46 percent of BNS, and NatWest Investment Bank Ltd., a
British investment bank.
   Affiliates of BNS already own nearly 2.1 million shares, or
about 7.45 percent of Koppers' outstanding common stock, the
company said.
   Based on Koppers' nearly 28.6 million common shares outstanding,
the tender offer would be worth a total of about $1.29 billion.
   Several securities analysts said Koppers, which recently
completed a restructuring that shed several engineering and metals
products businesses over the past three years, was worth more than
the offered price.
   Its main businesses now are construction materials and services,
which mainly involve road construction, and chemical and allied
products.
   BNS indicated that it planned to sell the chemicals and allied
products business if its tender offer is successful.
   Robert Kanters, senior vice president for the stock brokerage
Legg Mason Masten in Pittsburgh, said Koppers holds ``a commanding
position in aggregates and the coal-based chemicals businesses''
and may be worth $55- to $60-a-share.
   Aggregates are the rock mixtures used in road and bridge
construction. Among Koppers' coal-based chemicals products are
substances used to treat lumber.
   Fred Siemer, who follows the chemicals business for the firm
Chemical Research, said Beazer probably is attracted to Koppers'
quarries, which are essential to roadbuilding. Koppers said it
operates about 150 quarries in 20 states.
   Beazer has been expanding rapidly in recent years. It bought
Gifford-Hill & Co., a cement-maker based in Dallas, in 1986; and
also operates Phillips Builders in Nashville, Tenn., Tidewater
Construction Co. in Norfolk, Va., and Cohn Communities in Atlanta.
   The bid is conditioned on, among other things, Koppers
stockholders tendering a majority of the company's common shares,
approval by the non-management directors of Koppers, approval by
Beazer's shareholders and the bidding group's satisfaction that
certain elements of Delaware antitakeover laws are invalid.
   The offer expires at midnight March 30 unless extended.
   Brian C. Beazer, chairman of Beazer PLC, told Koppers' chairman,
Charles R. Pullin, in a letter, ``We plan to operate Koppers as an
independent autonomous business and we have no plans to move the
headquarters from Pittsburgh.''
   BNS said Shearson had agreed to provide $465 million in
financing for the offer and that Citibank had indicated to arrange
additional financing.
   Koppers reported its profit for 1987 fell to $10.2 million, or
36 cents share, from $74.1 million, or $2.59 a share, a year
earlier. The results included a charge of $59.4 million in 1987 due
to settlement of a lawsuit.
   Revenue rose to $1.52 billion from $1.4 billion in 1986.
   Beazer said it earned $82.8 million on sales of $1.7 billion in
its latest fiscal year, which ended last June 30.
</TEXT>
