<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SentimentalJourneys Bjt   03-04 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sentimental Journeys, Bjt,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cookie Company Starts Nostalgic Air Tours In DC-3</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos FX1, FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN LEANDRO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Otis Spunkmeyer Inc. is wagering a
few million cookies that it has Goodyear out-blimped when it comes
to midair advertising.
   The gourmet baking company embarks today on a sky tours business
featuring a vintage 1945 DC-3, hoping to capture the romance of
aviation's golden era along with the hearts and wallets of
well-heeled customers.
   Kenneth Rawlings, chairman and chief executive officer of Otis
Spunkmeyer, sees the tour business as a can't-miss proposition:
even if planefuls of customers don't line up for hour-long flights
at $75 a pop _ or $1,200 to charter the entire 18-seat aircraft _
the promotional value is high.
   ``We look at it as our Goodyear blimp,'' Rawlings said, noting
that a 95-foot-long sign bearing the company's name under the wing
should grab the attention of ground-bound consumers.
   ``We're just trying to find a way of flying it full at the same
time we're promoting our product.''
   The company inaugurated its ``Sentimental Journeys'' venture on
Thursday, whisking press and invited guests on half-hour trips
around San Francisco Bay in the two-propeller airplane, complete
with champagne and crew in 1940s style uniforms.
   Otis Spunkmeyer, which expects $30 million in sales over the
next 12 months, bought the DC-3 for $165,000 two months ago.
   Rawlings took his first airplane ride on a DC-3 as a child and
says he's been mulling over the sky tours idea for some time. Last
summer he decided to go ahead with it after his wife Linda _ the
company president and a white-knuckle flier _ accompanied him on a
commercial DC-3 flight from Cape Cod to Boston and was lulled to
sleep by its comfort.
   Victory Lap Inc., the Spunkmeyer subsidiary that operates the
tours, has spiffed up the inside of its DC-3 and offers deluxe
limousine service as well.
   Inside the plane, crew members wear 1940s-style uniforms, the
in-flight music features Doris Day and Glenn Miller, and
stewardesses distribute champagne, gourmet hors d'oeuvres and _ of
course _ cookies as the slow but steady aircraft flies past the
Golden Gate Bridge at 1,500 feet.
   The DC-3 revolutionized air travel in comfort and safety, and
accounted for 90 percent of the world's airline traffic in 1939.
Rawlings estimates there are more than 1,000 of them still
operating, mostly flying cargo in other countries.
   Aviation historian Ed Davies of nearby Millbrae, Calif., said he
believed the DC-3 venture was the first of its kind.
   If the tours venture is successful, Rawlings envisions a fleet
of refurbished DC-3s serving the nation's major metropolitan areas,
starting with Seattle, San Diego or Los Angeles.
   Such a move would mark a new chapter for San Leandro-based Otis
Spunkmeyer, founded by Rawlings in 1977 as a California chain of
fresh-baked cookie stores. The company moved into selling frozen
gourmet cookie dough wholesale in 1983 and now employs 250 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
