<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mexico-Debt     03-04 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Debt,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Announces Results of Debt-for-Bonds Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only about a quarter of Mexico's creditor
banks submitted bids in a unique debt-for-securities swap aimed at
reducing the nation's $105 billion foreign debt, according to the
Treasury Department.
   The government said Thursday it had accepted 55 percent of the
$6.7 billion in bids that 139 creditor banks submittd under the
swap plan, which has been hailed by some as a major new initiative
in dealing with troubled Third World debtors.
   Under the plan, the government will issue over $2.5 billion in
new, 20-year bonds to its creditor banks to replace $3.66 billion
in old bank debt, a swap that will save Mexico over $2.6 billion
over 20 years.
   Mexico had invited its international bank creditors to trade
their Mexican loans at a discount for the 20-year bonds, which are
backed by U.S. Treasury securities.
   The plan unveiled last December was seen as a way of reducing
the banks' exposures to troubled Mexican loans while minimizing the
impact on the banks' ledgers from having to write down the value of
those loans.
   But there were indications when the plan was announced that a
number of major foreign lenders would not participate. Citibank,
for example, indicated it was satisfied with its loan portfolio and
viewed the swaps instead as a way for banks to get out of Third
World lending.
   Mexico's approximately 560 creditor banks had until Feb. 25 to
submit their sealed bids to Morgan Guaranty Trust Co., which acted
as exchange agent for the plan.
   Of the $6.7 billion in bids received from 139 creditor banks,
Mexico accepted bids representing $3.66 billion in old loans at an
average discount exchange rate of just over 69 cents on the dollar,
the Treasury Department said.
   The remaining 45 percent of the bids were rejected because they
sought a price for the old debt that was higher than that sought by
the government, the department said.
   By agreeing to issue the $2.557 billion in new bonds, Mexico
will reduce its debt principal by $1.108 billion. It also will save
$1.537 billion in interest over the 20-year term of the bonds, for
a total savings of $2.645 billion.
   The government will back the bond issue by buying $520 million
in zero-coupon U.S. Treasury bonds. It had been prepared to invest
up to $2 billion to purchase up to $10 billion of the U.S.
securities.
   The department did not identify the banks which had bids
accepted or detail the amounts.
   It did state that the government would continue ``to actively
explore new mechanisms to reduce its external debt.''
   ``It is hoped that in the future...international financial
organizations can play a more active role in designing and
assisting other solutions to alleviate the weight of the debt,''
the department stated.
</TEXT>
