<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Batus-Farmers     03-04 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Batus-Farmers,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Suitor Batus Turns Hostile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. HACKETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. said it launched a $4.5
billion hostile tender offer for Farmers Group Inc. because the
insurance giant's board of directors declined to negotiate over
Batus' earlier $4.2 billion proposal.
   Batus began the $63 a share offer on Thursday, sweetening its
initial unsolicited $60 a share proposal that Farmers had rejected
on Jan. 20 as inadequate.
   A spokesman for Los Angeles-based Farmers, the nation's
seventh-largest insurer, said that while the Farmers board would
consider the higher price, ``this highly conditional offer changes
very little.''
   Wall Street reacted to the latest development by sending the
price of Farmers' stock up 75 cents _ to $62.75 per share _ on the
over-the-counter market.
   In a statement, Batus Chairman Patrick Sheehy said the tender
offer ``represents a pemium of 47 percent over the $43 price at
which Farmers' shares closed on the day before our initial
proposal.''
   He said Batus would be willing to meet Farmers' directors at any
time to discuss all terms of the proposal.
   One New York analyst, who has followed the maneuvering, said
Batus' latest attempt ``may be a ploy to get some action out of
Farmers. They have been sitting there ignoring everything that is
done.''
   ``I wouldn't be surprised to see a further offer down the
line,'' said D. Gordon Luce, of Brown Brothers Harriman.
   Other analysts had said previously that Batus needed to sweeten
its offer by $5 to $20 a share before Farmers would consider it.
   The tender offer was conditioned upon Batus obtaining at least
51 percent of Farmers' 69 million outstanding shares and on Batus
gaining required state regulatory approval. The offer expires March
30.
   Batus is a subsidiary of British-based BAT Industries PLC, a
tobacco, retailing and insurance conglomerate.
   Batus announced last month that it had lined up a $3.2 billion
revolving line of credit from an international group of banks for
use in its takeover bid.
   After rejecting Batus's $60 a share offer, Farmers Chairman Leo
Denlea Jr. said his shareholders would be best served if the
company remained independent.
   Farmers has about $11 billion in assets, mostly in insurance. It
ranks third in the United States in home and auto insurance behind
State Farm and Allstate and is the seventh-largest property and
casualty insurance company.
</TEXT>
