<1ST_LINE>r f PM-KaiserTech     03-04 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-KaiserTech,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minority Group of Company Directors Files New Suit Against
Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five directors of KaiserTech Ltd. have
filed suit against Alan Clore, the company's chairman, to keep him
from turning over control of the board to Houston financier Charles
Hurwitz.
   The lawsuit, filed Thursday in Alameda County Superior Court,
was the second against Clore involving KaiserTech in three days. On
Tuesday, the world's fifth-largest aluminum maker sued the British
investor for illegal insider stock trading.
   Among the minority group of directors that sued Clore on
Thursday was retired Kaiser Chairman Cornell Maier. The suit said
that Clore's resignation ``is in order'' because of an alleged
breach of contract.
   Clore agreed earlier this week to sell his 32.1 percent stake in
KaiserTech for up to $234 million to Hurwitz, who acquired Pacific
Lumber Co. in 1986.
   The five directors wanted Clore to sell his shares more broadly.
They also are concerned that all board positions expire in May.
   The minority directors claim Clore has breached the so-called
Clore Agreement, which gave Clore the right to nominate a majority
of the board in exchange for a $140 million investment last year.
   They said in the lawsuit that ``driven by his financial
desperation and (in) violation of Delaware law and his agreement
with KaiserTech, Clore has entered into agreements with Hurwitz
under which Clore will pretend to nominate his own (slate of
directors), but in fact will nominate only those Hurwitz selects.''
   ``In plain English,'' the suit continued, ``the foregoing
agreements and schemes are a sham designed to enable Hurwitz to
obtain board control, all without stockholder approval.''
   Clore and his lawyers could not be reached for comment on the
suit. A representative for Hurwitz, not a defendant in the
complaint, said the suit is ``without merit.''
   Besides Maier, those suing include Stephen Hutchcraft, corporate
president under Maier and now president of KaiserTech's only
operating subsidiary, Kaiser Aluminum; John Beckett, retired
Transamerica Corp. chairman and the BankAmerica Corp. director who
helped persuade Tom Clausen to return as chairman of the San
Francisco-based bank corporation; Charles Lynch, chairman of DHL
Worldwide Express in Redwood City; and John Merow, Kaiser's former
vice chairman. All but Lynch were directors under Maier.
</TEXT>
