<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TWA-Attendants 1stLd-Writethru   03-04 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TWA-Attendants, 1st Ld-Writethru,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Rules In Favor Of TWA In Attendants' Suit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Restores dropped time element to 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled that Trans
World Airlines did not bargain in bad faith to precipitate and
prolong a 1986 strike by flight attendants, a decision that could
save the airline $300 million.
   The ruling Thursday went against the Independent Federation of
Flight Attendants, which represents about 5,000 TWA flight
attendants who were seeking reinstatement with back pay to the jobs
they lost in the strike.
   U.S. District Judge Howard F. Sachs rejected contentions by the
union that TWA and its largest shareholder, Carl Icahn, bargained
in bad faith in violation of federal labor laws to precipitate the
bitter 72-day walkout. The union demanded its jobs back with back
pay at prestrike wage rates.
   Union President Vicki Frankovich said she was disappointed by
the judge's ruling but was ``confident we will win on appeal.''
   If Sachs' order is upheld upon appeal, it will lift from the
airline a potential financial liability that has been accumulating
at the rate of $8 million to $15 million a month since the strike
began March 7, 1986.
   ``We are very pleased the court made this decision,'' Icahn
said. ``We try to be fair to our employees. We tried to negotiate
with IFFA. We are happy the court vindicated us.''
   Icahn said the decision would not alter TWA's financial plans
because ``we never put any reserves aside because we always thought
we could win it.''
   The walkout began after Icahn bargained unsuccessfully for
cost-saving concessions from the union. Freed from the supervision
of a federal mediator who could not resolve the differences, Icahn
cut flight attendant wages by 22 percent, increased working hours
and changed work rules. The union struck.
   TWA hired 2,700 new flight attendants to replace the strikers.
About 1,300 attendants resigned from the union, crossed its picket
lines and continued to work.
   On May 17, 1986, the union offered unconditionally to return to
work without a contract.
   In one of several lawsuits it filed, the union alleged that the
airline had bargained in bad faith to bring about and prolong the
strike.
   While chastising both sides for their sometimes angry and
abrasive conduct in negotiations _ particularly Icahn for allegedly
sexist comments _ Sachs found that the actions of the airline were
legal responses to economic conditions.
   ``I cannot conclude from the evidence presented that TWA's
bargaining was in bad faith,'' the judge wrote in his 78-page
opinion.
   Sachs said case law permitted an aggressive union to bargain for
benefits that will increase an employer's costs. An aggressive
employer can lawfully bargain for reductions in total expenses of a
group thought to be considerably overpaid and much less productive
than is feasible, he said.
   Sachs went on to say that ``it is not a function of the court to
insist that an employer cheerfully accept strike losses or show
generosity in victory.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0958EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Airlines-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru f0036 03-04 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airlines-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0036,0638</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 11 grafs new material; picks up 8th graf pvs, A
fact. A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight attendants' union official said today
that Transportation Department plans to test airline crews and
ground workers for drug use would be unfair and unnecessary.
   But Transportation Secretary James Burnley defended the proposal
announced Thursday, saying he did not want to wait until hundreds
of people are killed before taking action to stop any potential
problem.
   Vicky Francovich, president of the Independent Federation of
Flight Attendants, said that in the 50-year history of the
industry, there have been no accidents blamed on employee drug use.
   Ms. Francovich, interviewed with Burnley on ABC-TV's ``Good
Morning America,'' said the department should be looking for ways
to combat fatigue among overworked airline personnel and to tighten
certification procedures.
   ``I think there are more responsible ways to deal with the
problems,'' she said, adding that false positive drug tests could
lead to an unfair stigma against an employee.
   ``While the government is not dealing with problems in the
deregulated industry ... it is attacking a problem here that
doesn't really exist,'' she said. ``This is not a necessary
approach.''
   Burnley acknowledged that no airline accidents have been traced
to drug use, but he cited a Pittsburgh Press survey showing that
six hospital emergency rooms had treated 23 cockpit crew members or
flight attendants for drug overdoses.
   Burnley, who was also interviewed on ``CBS This Morning,'' said
one airline reported that 16 percent of job applicants for
mechanics jobs were found to be using drugs and, at another
airline, 6 percent of flight attendant applicants were drug users.
He did not name the airlines.
   ``There is nothing beyond that anecdotal evidence that would
indicate that the airline industry is somehow exempt from this
problem that is plaguing all of American society, so I think it's
pretty clear that we need to move in this area,'' he said.
   Burnley said he expects a final rule to be implemented before
the end of the year, despite several pending court challenges to
mandatory drug testing.
   Testing would cover the more than half a million commercial
aviation employees who hold safety-senstive jobs: from pilots and
flight attendants to mechanics and security workers at airport
checkpoints.
   A fact sheet provided by the department suggested as many as 7.5
percent of the 511,000 workers who would be subject to the tests
might show evidence of drug use. But Burnley sought to distance
himself from the estimate, saying it was included only as a means
of roughly estimating the possible cost of such a program and not
meant to indicate the extent of drug use in the industry.
   The pilots and otherairline unions promised to challenge any
random drug testing rule in court once it is made final. Drug
testing already is the subject of numerous lawsuits and several
federal courts of appeal have either upheld testing or knocked it
down.
   ``We can't wait for weeks and months while these (drug testing)
cases wind themselves through the courts,'' Burnley said.
   In addition to pilots and flight attendants, the testing
requirements would cover aircraft mechanics, other cockpit crew
member such as flight engineers and navigators, aircraft
dispatchers and security personnel who work at screening
checkpoints at airports.
   Under the proposal, employees would be subject to a
pre-employment test, periodic testing whenever a person is taking a
physical, post-accident testing and random testing as well as test
for reasonable cause. An employee would be subject to an initial
test on a sample of urine and a more sophisticated test if the
first test shows the presence of drugs.
</TEXT>
