<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1002EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Japan-Trade     03-04 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Trade,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Current Account Surplus Fell 27.4 Percent In January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan posted an unadjusted current account surplus
of $3.52 billion in January, down 27.4 percent from $4.84 billion a
year earlier, the Finance Ministry said Friday.
   January's surplus in the broadest measure of trade was also down
from $9.44 billion in December, said Finance Ministry official
Toshio Naito. The current account includes services and investment
income as well as merchandise trade.
   When adjusted for seasonal fluctuations, the current account
surplus for January stood at $8.03 billion, down from $8.71 billion
a year earlier but up from an adjusted $7.47 billion in December.
   Japan's seasonally adjusted trade surplus in January fell 19.6
percent from its level a year earlier, marking the seventh
consecutive monthly decline, Naito.
   The seasonally adjusted surplus in merchandise trade, a narrower
measure, came to $4.58 billion, down from $5.70 billion last
January and $10.06 billion in December, Naito said. It was the
seventh straight monthly decline in the trade surplus compared to
its year-earlier level.
   Imports of aluminum, platinum, textiles, food and crude oil
increased, apparently because of the yen's continued rise against
the U.S. dollar and stronger domestic demand, Naito said. The
higher yen has raised prices of Japanese exports overseas and made
imports cheaper, encouraging Japanese to buy more foreign goods.
   In 1987's January-March quarter, the current account surplus
rose 65.5 percent from a year earlier. On the other hand, it
declined 1.5 percent in the April-June quarter year-on-year, 13.2
percent in the July-September quarter and 15.2 percent in the
October-December quarter.
   Exports rose 16.1 percent in January from a year earlier to
$17.0 billion, compared to $14.6 billion a year earlier, but down
from the holiday-impacted $22.8 billion in December.
   Imports rose 38.8 percent to $12.4 billion from $8.94 billion a
year earlier.
   Toshiaki Kakimoto, chief economist for Sumitomo Bank Ltd., said
January's unadjusted 16.1 percent surge in exports was ``somewhat
disturbing.''
   Kakimoto said Japanese exporters, in part, had boosted their
shipments in December and January on fears the yen would rise
against the dollar and make their products less competitive.
   In a separate report, the Japan Automobile Importers'
Association said imported cars sold in Japan reached 8,212 autos in
February, up 39.4 percent from the 5,890 sold in the same month
last year.
   The number of imported autos sold in Japan has increased every
month since January 1984, said Kunihiko Ono of the association.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
