<DOCNO> AP880304-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Chrysler-Acustar 1stLd-Writethru   03-04 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Acustar, 1st Ld-Writethru,0694</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last two grafs with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Stepp
recommendation to open bargaining early and include analyst
comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A massive protest and other strong opposition
from the United Auto Workers union influenced Chrysler Corp.'s
decision not to sell its Acustar Inc. parts-making subsidiary, the
automaker says.
   Chrysler said Thursday it would keep Acustar, but would close or
sell four plants within the next 18 months because of their
``competitive position.''
   The UAW had threatened plant-by-plant strikes if Chrysler sold
the subsidiary, which employs 28,000 in the United States, Canada
and Mexico and had $3 billion in sales last year.
   Last Thursday, more than 1,000 sign-waving workers protested the
proposed sale outside Chrysler's Highland Park headquarters.
   Furthermore, workers at Chrysler plants throughout the No. 3
automaker also had stopped attending management-union meetings and
participating in other joint activities since the automaker
disclosed the possible sale.
   ``That played a role,'' Chrysler spokesman John Guiniven said of
the company's decision. ``(Workers) stated very strongly that they
wanted to remain a part of Chrysler.''
   Chrysler had said it was considering selling the subsidiary,
which represents a fifth of its worldwide operations, because it
didn't want to invest in the research needed to upgrade some
operations. Chrysler already buys about 70 percent of its parts
from outside sources.
   The UAW had opposed the sale of Acustar on the grounds that it
would threaten the job security of all Chrysler workers.
   ``We looked at all the offers, took into account the feelings of
our employees and decided not to sell,'' Guiniven said.
   ``We certainly welcome this announcement, since we have
maintained all along that Chrysler is a stronger company with its
own internal parts-making capacity,'' UAW President Owen Bieber and
UAW Vice President Marc Stepp said in joint statement.
   Chrysler said the four plants it plans to close or sell _ Amplex
Van Wert in Van Wert, Ohio, Trenton Chemical in suburban Detroit,
Detroit Forge and Detroit Trim _ employ about 2,000 workers.
   The largest of the four plants is Detroit Trim, which employs
1,177 workers and makes trim for automobiles.
   Trenton Chemical employs 189 and makes chemicals used in auto
paints, Amplex Van Vert employs 333 and makes powered metal
products and Detroit Forge employs 419 and makes forged parts.
   ``We are going to sell all four and if not, they will be
closed,'' Guiniven said. ``But we feel strongly that Ampex and
Trenton Chemical will be sold.''
   The union would not have been able to call a national strike
over the sale of Acustar, but union locals were given permission to
authorize strikes on a plant-by-plant basis over unresolved issues
such as health and safety grievances.
   At least seven locals had voted to ask for strike authorization,
including workers at Trenton Chemical. Workers also had stopped
participating in union-management meetings at plants throughout
Chrysler in protest.
   Chrysler said it expected the company-union joint activities
suspended last month would resume in the wake of its decision.
   Bieber and Stepp said they believed workers who had stayed away
from the meetings probably would begin cooperating as a result of
the decision.
   The company also said it was ready to open negotiations for a
national contract to replace the agreement that expires Sept. 14.
   Stepp said Thursday he would recommend to the union's 140-member
Chrysler council that negotiations, which normally begin in
midsummer, be started early this year.
   ``It surprised me a bit that they offered to open talks early,
but I'm, very interested in getting a new agreement like Ford and
GM that covers workers being laid off by plant closings,'' Stepp
said Thursday night.
   Harley Shaiken, a professor and labor relations expert at the
University of California at San Diego, said Chrysler misjudged its
workers when it said Acustar was up for sale.
   ``Chrysler miscalculated, thinking that they might only have
problems with Acustar workers,'' he said. ``Instead Acustar became
a lightning rod for union discontent throughout the corporation.''
</TEXT>
