<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Upjohn-Japan     03-04 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Upjohn-Japan,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Upjohn, Japanese Pharmaceutical Firm in Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Upjohn Co. and a Tokyo-based
pharmaceutical company have announced a joint venture to bring
Japanese health products to the United States.
   Upjohn and Chugai Pharmaceutical Co. Ltd. will form a third
company, which will be named later. Chugai will own 55 percent and
Upjohn will own the rest. The new company will be based in the
United States, the companies said Friday.
   The agreement announced today calls for Chugai to license
products to the new company and for Upjohn to be the exclusive
distributor for seven years. Among the products heading for the
United States are erythropoietin, which stimulates production of
red blood cells, and granulocyte-colony stimulating factor, which
stimulates white blood cells.
   They can be used to treat anemia associated with kidney dialysis
and in transfusions and cancer chemotherapy.
   ``Upjohn and Chugai have had an excellent business relationship
since 1982,'' said Lawrence C. Hoff, Upjohn president and chief
operating officer.
   Kimio Uyeno, chairman of Chugai, said, ``We intend to establish
our capability to develop Chugai's new products and technologies
through the joint venture. ...
   ``With Upjohn's help, the corporation is expected to become a
fully integrated pharmaceutical company through gradual transitions
in the future,'' he said.
   Upjohn spokesman Robert D. LaRue said the location of the new
company's headquarters and its employment level haven't been
decided. He declined to speculate about the new company's sales
level.
</TEXT>
