<HEAD>Michigan Congressman Urges Union to Strike Northwest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Detroit filed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Michigan congressman is urging unionized
flight attendants at Northwest Airlines to strike the company,
saying a cooling off period has ended.
   Rep. William Ford, a Democrat from Taylor in suburban Detroit,
said Thursday the Teamsters union should strike the airline since
talks between the two sides have reached an impasse.
   ``The demands the company are making now would provoke a strike
in any factory in my district,'' said Ford, whose district includes
Detroit Metropolitan Airport, one of Northwest's three major hubs.
The others are in Minneapolis and Memphis, Tenn.
   Teamsters airline division leader William Genoese Sr. said he
met Thursday with Ford and Michigan Sen. Donald Riegle, also a
Democrat, and was pleased with their support for his union.
   A Teamsters strike deadline passed nearly a week ago as
negotiations between the Minnesotat-based company and the union
representing its 6,700 flight attendants continued. Since then,
talks have broken off and no new negotiations have been scheduled.
   The union has said there will be a strike, but has not said when
or to what extent.
