<HEAD>Wheat Futures Open Higher; Other Grains Move Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures opened higher while other grains
and soybeans opened lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices advanced in reaction to the Agriculture
Department's announcement Thursday afternoon that it had sold just
1.4 million bushels of surplus wheat Wednesday in the second of
three auctions slated for this week, analysts said.
   The USDA had set a target of 10 million bushels for each of the
auctions, which are designed to meet increased demand by selling
government-owned stocks of the grain.
   The agency hit its target on Tuesday, but fell far short on
Wednesday, easing fears among traders that the increased
availability of wheat could depress cash prices. Another auction
was scheduled for this afternoon.
   The USDA also announced Thursday that American and Soviet
negotiators would meet next week to start work on a new, long-term
grain agreement. The announcement prompted further confidence in
the wheat market, said Richard Loewy, an analyst in New York for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   He said prices for future delivery of soybeans fell on technical
factors while corn was nearly unchanged.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.06{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to { cent lower with March at $2.00{ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1 cent lower with March at $1.86 a bushel; soybeans
were 2{ cents to 3{ cents lower with March at $6.19{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .18 cent higher with April at
70.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .35 cent
higher with March at 79.25 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to
.50 cent higher with April at 42.70 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .75 cent to .88 cent higher with March at 53.05 cents
a pound.
   Cattle futures settled sharply lower on Thursday. Pork futures
finished slightly lower.
</TEXT>
