<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Bonds     03-04 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Way Down Because of Stronger Employment Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bonds prices tumbled in heavy trading and
interest rates jumped sharply this morning in reaction to the
government's surprisingly strong February employment report.
   The Treasury's key 30-year issue fell more than 1{ points or $15
per $1,000 in face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to
price and is a barometer of interest rate trends, surged to 8.44
percent from 8.31 percent late Thursday.
   ``The deterioration is quite obviously a response to the
employment situation,'' said William Sullivan, director of money
market research at the investment firm of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   The Labor Department said the economy created half a million
jobs last month, dropping the civilian unemployment rate to 5.7
percent, its lowest since the summer of 1979. The January rate had
been 5.8 percent.
   Credit-market analysts said the job-creation figure was more
than twice the general estimate and suggested there would be
heightening demand for credit and rising inflation, which depresses
bond prices.
   Nevertheless, some saw elements of weakness in the Labor
Department report, particularly a slowdown in the creation of
manufacturing jobs, suggesting future inventory buildups and
production cutbacks.
   After a detailed analysis of the report filtered through the
bond market, prices were likely to stabilize or recover somewhat,
some analysts speculated.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments fell { point, intermediate maturities fell one point
and long-term issues fell more than 1{ points, the financial
information service Telerate Inc. reported.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, fell 0.76 to 113.25. The Shearson Lehman Daily
Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, dropped
8.05 to 1,184.34.
   Among corporate bonds, industrials and utilities fell between }
to 1 point in heavy trading.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, fell 1.07 to 285.09.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills jumped 13 basis points to
5.73 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
Six-month bills rose 12 basis points to 5.98 percent and year bills
rose 13 basis points to 6.16 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 6{ percent, up from 67-16 percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
