<1ST_LINE>u f BC-TektronixLayoffs     03-04 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Tektronix Layoffs,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tektronix Inc. To Lay Off About 1,000 Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEAVERTON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tektronix Inc. will lay off about 1,000
employees by May 28 to cut the growth of expenses, which has
outpaced sales growth, the electronics manufacturer announced.
   ``There's just no question that we must reverse that trend to
get Tek back on the track to growth and profitability,'' said David
P. Friedley, president and chief executive officer, on Friday.
   Tektronix employs about 16,900 workers, with about 11,000 in
Oregon and southwest Washington. Most of the layoffs will affect
managerial and professional workers in the Portland area, the
company said in a news release.
   The first phase of the layoffs will affect about 300 employees
in the company's information display group. They were notified of
the layoffs Friday. Employees in other divisions will be notified
of their job status in the next few weeks, the company said.
   The layoffs follow a recent companywide review by a new
management team.
   ``The reductions cause us to lose some very fine people,''
Friedley said. ``Their talents will be missed. But the fact is,
we've been operating at less-than-maximum efficiency and our
appetite for many projects and programs is greater than our
pocketbook can adequately fund.''
   Friedley was chosen to succeed Earl Wantland on Nov. 1.
Friedley's new management team was announced Jan. 12.
   ``We have a number of growing, profitable businesses which are
performing well, including portable oscilloscopes,
television-related units, and the graphics printer and terminal
division,'' Friedley said. ``We are also aggressively pursuing
other growth opportunities, such as telecommunications equipment,
workstations and measurement systems.''
   The company said it expects to record a loss for the third
quarter, which ends March 5. The layoffs will result in significant
expenses for severance pay and restructuring during the quarter.
   Employees will be offered one week's severance pay for each year
with the company, with a minimum of two weeks' pay.
   The company's sales in 1987 totaled $1.39 billion.
</TEXT>
