<2ND_LINE>BC-Standard Chemical,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Employees Buy Out Livestock Feed Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten employees have purchased Standard
Chemical Manufacturing Co. of Omaha, a 102-year-old livestock feed
firm, from a group of New York and St. Louis investors.
   The price of the leveraged buyout was not disclosed.
   ``After 98 years of profitability, the company was unprofitable
the last couple of years,'' Executive Vice President Bill Dyer said.
   Dyer and Greg Kluck, who becomes the seventh president in
Standard Chemical's history, are the firm's majority owners.
   James M. Paxson will remain as chairman, Dyer said. Paxson
joined the company in 1953 as assistant to the president and became
president in 1961.
   In October 1983, Paxson, the majority stockholder in the
employee-owned company, sold to a buying group headed by Tom M.
Reese of St. Louis, who became president, and R.B. Halaby,
president of Ibec Agri-Finance Co. of New York, who became chairman
of the finance committee.
   Dyer said Standard Chemical, which sells its feed items via the
Standard Quality Feeds label, would remain intact.
   Standard Chemical, has plants in Malvern, Iowa, and Marshall,
Minn. It sells livestock feed in Nebraska, Iowa, Wisconsin, South
Dakota, Minnesota and Montana.
   The company was founded in 1886 as the Standard Stock Food Co.
by F.E. Sanborn, a veterinarian. The company adopted its present
name in 1912.
</TEXT>
