<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DeficitCommission 1stLd-Writethru f0039 03-04 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deficit Commission, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0039,0593</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Baker statement; picks up 8th graf pvs,
Baker had said; also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary James Baker said today that
the new commission created to find solutions to the government's
huge budget deficits would be making a mistake if it became
embroiled in election-year politics.
   The National Economic Commission was holding its initial meeting
today behind closed doors with Baker scheduled to address the
group. Before entering the session, Baker told reporters he would
urge the commission to keep a low profile during the 1988
presidential campaign.
   ``We will simply be making a point that the commission will be
more effective if it is not politicized. To be effective it should
not be viewed as a political apparatus of the 1988 campaign,''
Baker said.
   The Treasury secretary's position has drawn criticism from one
member of the commission, House Budget Committee Chairman William
Gray III, who on Thursday charged that the White House was trying
to dictate how the commission would function before it had even had
its first organizational session.
   He claimed that the administration, in an effort to cover up its
biggest economic failure, was lobbying to keep the National
Economic commission under wraps until after the presidential
election.
   The blue ribbon panel, which includes Chrysler Corp. Chairman
Lee Iacocca and New York investment banker Felix Rohatyn as
members, was expected to select a chairman today.
   Sources close to the panel said Robert Strauss, a Washington
lawyer and former head of the Democratic National Committee, was a
likely pick to head the group.
   Gray, one of six Democrats on the panel, took issue Thursday
with remarks made by Baker, who had suggested that the commission
should hold its deliberations in secret and not release any reports
before the November presidential election.
   Baker had said earlier this week that the administration was
eager for the commission ``to go to work,'' but he also said that
the commission's findings would carry more weight if the panel did
not become embroiled in election-year politics.
   Baker said the best way to avoid this was to meet in secret and
not release any interim reports. The panel, which was created by
Congress, is scheduled to present its final recommendations by
March 1 of next year.
   ``I don't think this commission should start off being dictated
to by the White House,'' Gray told reporters. ``Someone is
suggesting that we meet in a cave and roll a stone over the
opening.''
   Supporters of the deficit commission hope that because of its
bipartisan nature it will be able to break the logjam which has
prevented the government from crafting solutions to the budget
deficit, which this year is expected to top $150 billion.
   Gray suggested that Baker and other Republicans were trying to
keep the commission under wraps so that it would not become a forum
for airing the administration's biggest economic failure, the
doubling of the national debt.
   ``I don't think it is appropriate for the White House to say
there should be nothing said or done until they get out of town,''
Gray said. ``That is like the guilty party saying don't hand down
sentence until we leave town.''
   The commission is considered by many to be the best hope the
next president will have to reach a quick consensus with Congress
on significant ways to reduce the budget deficit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880304-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Federated     03-04 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>May Agrees With Campeau On Conditional Purchase Of Filene's,
Foley's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. today said May Department Stores
Co. has agreed to buy two divisions of Federated Department Stores
Inc. _ Filene's and Foley's _ if Campeau completes its hostile
takeover bid for Federated.
   Toronto-based Campeau said the agreement with May would make it
easier to obtain the financing for its bid for Cincinnati-based
Federated and reduce the amount of long-term debt that would be
needed after the acquisition.
   May said the purchase of Filene's and Foley's would strengthen
its business. Filene's is based in Boston and Foley's in Houston.
Campeau said they were worth about $1.5 billion together, but did
not say how much May had agreed to pay.
   On Thursday, Campeau threatened a court challenge to a merger
agreement between Federated and R.H. Macy & Co.
   Campeau, which had its rival buyout offer snubbed by Federated,
stated it intended to challenge provisions requiring Federated to
pay Macy fees of up to $45 million if their merger fell through
under certain conditions.
   Macy late Tuesday agreed to acquire Federated for cash and
securities in a deal valued by some analysts at a total of about
$6.1 billion.
   In accepting Macy's offer, Federated spurned Campeau's bid to
pay about $6.18 billion in cash for the retailing company.
   Under its current offer, Campeau would pay $75 per share in cash
for 80 percent of Federated's shares, and after a merger would pay
$44 per share for the remaining 20 percent. The company said the
offer _ revised from a previous $68 a share offer for all Federated
shares _ had a total value of about $68 a share on a fully diluted
basis.
   Campeau also has offered to raise its offer by 50 cents a share
if the breakup fee provision was withdrawn.
   The Macy-Federated merger will take six to 12 weeks to conclude,
when it will be submitted to Federated's shareholders for a vote.
</TEXT>
