<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-PostageRates 3rdLd-Writethru   03-04 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Postage Rates, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0749</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3 grafs for 9th graf pvs, _The postal, to CORRECT that
commission did not propose specific rate cut for suggested new type
of mail; also running on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mailing a letter will soon cost 25 cents, 3
cents more than at present.
   The independent Postal Rate Commission today recommended a
series of postage increases including boosting the price of a
first-class stamp from 22 cents to a quarter.
   A final decision on implementing the new rates is up to the
board of governors of the U.S. Postal Service, which requested the
increases 10 months ago, calling for a 25-cent stamp for first
class mail.
   The detailed and complex package of rate hikes recommended by
the rate commission included increases in most classes of mail. The
Postal Service had wanted increases averaging 16 percent.
   The new rate decision called for:
   _Raising the rate for post cards from 14 cents to 15 cents. The
Postal Service had requested a 16-cent rate.
   _Increasing the second-class rate for periodicals from 9.1 cents
to 9.8 cents per pound and the per-item rate from a range of 3.1 to
4.9 cents to a range of 4.9 to 5.9 cents.
   _For third-class advertising mail, the minimum bulk rate would
rise from 12.5 cents to 16.7 cents. The non-profit minimum would
rise from 8.5 cents to 9.0 cents.
   _The postal rate commission also recommended establishing a
special type of mail to give consumers a break in paying bills or
answering advertisements.
   The commission urged the Postal Service to come up with a
discount from regular first-class rates for such mail, but did not
propose a particular amount.
   The rate decision did, however, suggest giving businesses a
two-cent cut from the present seven-cent minimum in their cost for
business-reply envelopes. That, the agency said, would encourage
the use of such envelopes.
   The last increase in postage rates was Feb. 17, 1985, when
first-class stamps climbed to 22 cents.
   The planned higher rates are not related to recent cutbacks in
postal hours and collections, which resulted from budget cuts
mandated by Congress in December.
   The commission ruling will go to the Postal Service board of
governors, probably early next week. It can put the new rate into
effect within a few weeks, institute the rates under protest or ask
the rate commission for reconsideration, depending on its opinion
of the recommendation.
   Because it had no way of knowing what new rates the commission
would settle on, the Postal Service has printed non-denominated
stamps to cover eny eventuality.
   When the new rates take effect, the first class stamp will carry
the letter ``E.'' The stamp carries a colorful space-based image of
the Earth and the word ``Domestic,'' to indicate that it can be
used only within the United States, not for mail going to other
countries.
   The same procedure was used the last four times rates were
raised, with those undenominated stamps all carrying images of
Eagles and the letters ``A'' through ``D.''
   In seeking the rate hike, postal officials noted that the agency
is required to break even. It lost more than $220 million last year.
   After the Postal Service was made an independent agency in the
early 1970s, its taxpayer subsidy was eliminated.
   John N. Griesemer, chairman of the postal service's board of
governors, said the proposed increase should cost the average
individual less than $10 per year.
   In addition to raising the price of a first-class stamp from 22
cents to 25 cents, the Postal Service proposed a multitude of
changes in its complex structure of rates for the various types of
mail.
   Prices for the expensive but highly competitive overnight mail
would drop somewhat, for example, while rates for advertising bulk
mail would rise.
   The Postal Service has been in the black five of the last 10
years. It finished 1986 with a $305 million surplus after an
intensive campaign to cut costs, but had losses of $200 million or
more in both 1985 and 1987.
   In addition to increasing the first-class base rate to 25 cents,
the Postal Service called for an increase in the charge for each
additional ounce of weight for first class mail from 17 cents to 20
cents. Post cards would increase from 14 cents to 16 cents.
</TEXT>
