<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Toshiba 2ndLd-Writethru f0095 03-04 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toshiba, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0095,0522</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new, picking up 7th graf pvs, The deals</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Toshiba Corp. sold machines for making
computer parts to Czechoslovakia and East Germany but broke off a
third deal last summer after it was discovered by U.S. officials,
according to congressional sources.
   A Pentagon spokesman denied that the deals had occurred, but
several members of Congress said intelligence analysts have
prepared reports that the illegal technology transfers did take
place.
   ``Toshiba has been involved over the last seven years in
enhancing the microchip capability of the Warsaw pact nations,''
said an aide to Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif.
   The aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he had no
direct knowledge of classified reports from the Central
Intelligence Agency and the military Defense Intelligence Agency.
   Those reports were described in today's editions of The
Washington Times. Another congressional source, also speaking on
condition of anonymity, confirmed those allegations, which come six
months after Toshiba admitted that a subsidiary had sold the Soviet
Union machine tools for making quiet submarine propellers, thereby
neutralizing a portion of U.S. anti-submarine defenses.
   According to congressional sources, Toshiba sold Czechoslovakia
a complete factory in 1979 to make computer chips, sold East
Germany a similar but more advanced computer-chip assembly line in
1986, and negotiated a deal for a second assembly line in East
Germany in 1987.
   The deals have become known as Toshiba 2, Toshiba 3 and Toshiba
4. Toshiba 1 is the submarine case.
   A Pentagon spokesman, Col, Arnold Williams, said that ``the
information that we have is that we feel these actions, Toshiba 2,
3 and 4, have not occurred.''
   Williams said he was unable to discuss the CIA and DIA reports.
   Officials in the office of Stephen Bryen, the deputy
undersecretary of defense for trade security, also declined to
discuss the allegations.
   According to congressional sources, the Czechoslovak deal was of
questionable legality, and the 1986 East Germany deal was illegal
under Western export laws.
   Defenders say the first deal was legal, the second never
happened and in the third instance, Toshiba voluntarily acted out
of public-relations concerns to halt what would have been a legal
sale.
   Toshiba attorney David Houlihan called the allegations the
result of a ''vendetta'' by a group of CIA analysts against Toshiba
and Japan, according to the published report.
   As a result of the sale to the Soviet bloc, House and Senate
conferees are working on a bill that could ban Toshiba sales in the
United States for two to five years, said Duncan's aide.
   The congressman has organized classified briefings for about 30
lawmakers by CIA and DIA analysts who are convinced that the
transactions did occur, said the aide.
   ``Intelligence officials have confirmed them to our
satisfaction,'' said the aide.
   ``There has been a lot of pressure from the administration'' not
to damage trade relations with Japan, said the aide. ``The strength
of the conflict between the Congress and the administration is
intense.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
