<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AmericanStandard     03-04 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-American Standard,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeover Target Sweetens Recap Plan to Thwart Black & Decker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc. today intensified a
struggle to escape a hostile $2.1 billion takeover from Black &
Decker Corp. by sweetening a rival recapitalization plan that
analysts valued at about $2.3 billion.
   The move disclosed by the New York-based plumbing and air
conditioning giant would add $5 cash to the payment of cash and
securities that American Standard has offered shareholders to woo
them away from the $68-a-share cash payment Black & Decker has
offered for each of the target's 31 million shares.
   Wall Street analysts figured the sweetened American Standard
offer of $64 in cash, $5 in debt securities and one share of stock
in the recapitalized company was worth about $74 a share. The
company's stock surged $1.50 a share to $70.12{ on the New York
Stock Exchange by early afternoon.
   Black & Decker, a tool and appliance maker based in Towson, Md.,
said it was studying the sweetened American Standard offer but had
no other comment.
   American Standard's move came a few days after it disclosed
discussions with unidentified parties regarding the possible sale
of debt securities to sweeten the cash portion of its
recapitalization.
   Under the revised proposal, American Standard will sell $160
million worth of debt securities to Emerson Electric Co. As part of
the transaction, American Standard also will purchase some
unidentified products from Emerson, a St. Louis-based maker of
electronics, tools and cooling and heating systems.
   A recapitalization, in which a company restructures its amount
of debt and equity, is used often to thwart unwelcome takeovers.
The strategy usually plunges a company into debt, making it less
attractive as an acquisition.
   American Standard's revised plan, which would raise the
company's long-term debt from $412 million to about $2.46 billion,
would pay shareholders about $2.06 billion plus give them a stake
in the recapitalized company.
   Black & Decker has been attempting since late January to acquire
American Standard.
</TEXT>
