<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1403EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Unemployment Bjt   03-04 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unemployment, Bjt,0862</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Favorable Jobless Report Allays Fears of Economic Recession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With more than a half-million new jobs last
month, the nation's civilian unemployment rate dropped to 5.7
percent, the government said Friday, indicating a much stronger
U.S. economy than most analysts had thought.
   Only once since 1974 _ in May 1979 when the rate was 5.6 percent
_ has the percentage of jobless Americans been lower. With a
one-tenth percentage point drop from December's and January's
jobless rates of 5.8 percent, the rolls of the unemployed declined
by 108,000 in February to just over 6.9 million, the lowest jobless
number since early 1980.
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics said its survey of households
showed 280,000 more Americans going to work last month, with an
all-time record 62.2 percent of the nation's working-age population
_ age 16 and over _ now holding jobs.
   Business and other employers reported in a separate survey
increasing their payrolls by a net 531,000 new jobs _ 115,000 of
them in business and health services, 110,000 in retail trade,
105,000 in construction, 68,000 in government and 20,000 in
manufacturing.
   ``These numbers have killed all discussion about no growth this
quarter,'' said James Cochran, chief economist for Texas Bancshares
in Houston.
   ``The economy is doing pretty well,'' Cochran said. ``And to
everyone's surprise, the strength is coming from basic domestic
activity rather than companies hiring people to produce things to
sell overseas.''
   Donald Straszheim, chief economist for Merrill Lynch, said the
February job numbers were the most surprising economic statistics
he has ever seen.
   ``There's 400,000 more people working now than we had thought,''
he said. ``The housing market is weak, construction is weak and,
except for automobiles, consumers don't seem to be buying anything.
Some of it just doesn't make any sense.''
   Nonetheless, Straszheim joined a chorus of other economists in
saying that the unemployment report effectively negates their
earlier predictions of little or no economic growth this year.
   ``This report makes it clear there is no recession in the
cards,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co., a
New York-based financial consultant. ``The real question is how
much steam the economy will gather. As incomes start flowing from
this surge in jobs, the future looks pretty bright.''
   The jobless report shines brightest on Republican presidential
candidates seeking to retain GOP control of the White House, the
economic gurus agreed.
   ``The economic statistic that has more political import than any
other is unemployment,'' said Straszheim, ``and this is a very
strong report.''
   ``George Bush ought to be running over to kiss the people at the
Bureau of Labor Statistics,'' said David Wyss, chief financial
economist of Data Resources Inc. of Lexington, Mass. ``People vote
their pocketbooks, and right now their pocketbooks look pretty
full.''
   At the White House, Reagan administration officials also basked
in the numbers.
   ``Both the February increase in employment and the decline in
unemployment exceeded the expectations of private forecasters,''
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said. ``Jobs are the best
indicator of a sound economy.''
   Sinai said the unemployment rate, down from a full percentage
point from 12 months ago, can only be a ``big plus for
Republicans.''
   ``It certainly doesn't argue that we need protectionism to help
our job market,'' said Wyss, referring to Rep. Richard Gephardt's
campaign theme for winning the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Democrats, however, could utilize some of the figures in the
report. Despite inflation running at an annual rate of 4.2 percent
so far this year, average wages dropped by 2 cents last month to
$9.12 an hour, the BLS said.
   ``That's both bad and good news,'' Straszheim said. ``If you're
working, it means your wages aren't keeping you up. But if you're
fearful about inflation, don't be.''
   The figures also indicate that 199,000 of the 280,000 increase
in the number of Americans holding jobs were people working
part-time only because they could not find full-time employment.
   However, the Labor Department said recent employment growth has
been strongest in high-wage administrative and management
occupations, accounting for more than one-third of the 3 million
new jobs in the past year.
   The biggest beneficiaries of that trend and the recent rebound
in manufacturing and construction employment have been adult men,
whose jobless rate has dropped from 5.8 percent in February 1987 to
4.9 percent last month.
   The jobless rate for women, also at 5.8 percent a year ago, was
5.2 percent in February.
   Jobless rates for minority groups remained high despite the fact
that blacks and Hispanics have obtained one of every three new jobs
over the last year, the government said.
   Black unemployment, at 12.6 percent last month, was more than
double the 4.8 percent for whites. Hispanic unemployment, after
declining to 7.2 percent in January, rose to 8.3 percent last month.
   An alternate jobless rate, including the 1.7 million members of
the uniformed armed services stationed in the United States, also
dropped 0.1 percentage point last month, to 5.6 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
