<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined broadly today as
interest rates jumped following a stronger-than-expected report on
employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 6 points
in early trading, was down 17.90 at 2,045.59 by 2 p.m. on Wall
Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 2 to 1 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 495 up, 943 down and
466 unchanged.
   Before the opening the Labor Department reported that the
civilian unemployment rate dropped a tenth of a percentage point
last month to an 8{-year low of 5.7 percent.
   Nonfarm payroll employment increased by 531,000, considerably
more than most advance estimates on Wall Street.
   The news was seen as an emphatic signal that the economy remains
strong several months after the stock market crash last October.
But it was not well received in the credit markets, where traders
interpreted is as a likely portent of upward pressure on interest
rates.
   Prices of long-term government bonds fell more than $15 for each
$1,000 in face value, raising their yields to the 8.4-8.5 percent
range.
   Among actively traded blue-chip industrials, American Telephone
& Telegraph fell [ to 28}; Eastman Kodak ] to 43[; Ford Motor ] to
45|, and General Electric ~ to 43~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 1.21 to 149.49. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .81 at 291.70.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 151.84 million shares with two
hours to go.
