<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Wine-Japan     03-04 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wine-Japan,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wente Wines Completes Order For Japan's Bullet Train</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The century-old Wente Bros. winery has
completed its first shipment of wine for Japan's Bullet Train, the
winery reported on Friday.
   The delivery to Japan Railways marks the first order of American
wine by the Toyota Motor Co., according to Debra Sanchez,
spokeswoman for Toyota Motor Sales, U.S.A.
   ``It's just the beginning,'' she said. ``The Japanese are
falling in love with California wines.''
   The first order was for 29,000 mini-bottles of chablis, blanc de
blancs, and white zinfandel, chosen after exhaustive taste tests of
the Livermore winery's 14 wines, said Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A.
Vice President Robert Best.
   ``Exporting California wines to Japan is another example of
Toyota's commitment to increase Japanese purchases of U.S.
products,'' said Best.
   ``I'm excited, not only for Wente Brothers but the entire
California wine industry,'' said Wente spokeswoman Carolyn Wente.
Her ancestor, Carl Wente, acquired his first vineyards in Livermore
in 1883, growing sauvignon blanc and semillon grapes. Wente whites
have been sold in the United States for 100 years.
   The wines for Japan were chosen for their expected popularity on
the trains. The choices virtually parallel American popular tastes.
The blanc de blancs is a light, sweet blend that includes chenin
blanc. Chablis is regarded around the world as the typical dry
white table wine.
   Wente has been exporting small amounts of wine to Japan for 20
years but thwarted by extremely high tariffs that found a bottle of
wine that sold for $4 in Califoria selling for $18-20 in Japan. The
taxes were lowered a couple of years ago, and the retail price in
Japan is now reported to be about double the California price.
   The United States today already is the second largest exporter
of wine to Japan, behind France, with Germany in third.
   Best said Toyota acted in this instance as a broker ordering the
wine, exporting it and selling it to the railway in Japan.
   The 6.3-ounce bottles will be sold on the 120 mph trains that
travel from Tokyo. The wines will go for about $2.50 each, he said.
   Toyota established a U.S. exports office in 1985 to search out
American products appropriate for the Japanese market and to reduce
the U.S. deficit in the balance of payments, Best said. Wente is
the first U.S. wine taken on by Toyota, he said.
   ``There has been a doubling in Japanese consumption of wine over
the last several years, and wine sales have grown over 400 percent
in the last five years,'' said Best.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
