<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     03-04 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
in European trading Friday. Gold prices rose nearly $10 an ounce in
London and $3 in Zurich.
   Merrill Lynch metals specialist Ted Arnold said gold bullion
climbed to $437.50 bid per troy ounce because of a short-covering
rally and a dip in monthly U.S. unemployment figures. Gold closed
at 427.80 an ounce late Thursday.
   He said the figures, which showed that the February rate fell to
5.7 percent from 5.8 percent in January, rekindled fears of
inflation.
   In Zurich, gold rose less sharply, to $432 bid an ounce, from
$429 dollars, on short-covering prompted by gains in silver and
platinum, dealers said.
   In a short sale, traders sell borrowed gold in expectation of
``covering'' those sales by replacing the gold with new lots bought
at cheaper prices.
   Foreign exchange dealers said U.S. unemployment figures briefly
pushed up the U.S. currency but the improvement in the rate was not
enough to have a lasting effect on the dollar.
   In Tokyo, the dollar inched lower to a closing 129.22 Japanese
yen from 129.30 yen. In London, it fell further to 128.95 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
were: 1.6940 West German marks, down from 1.6955; 1.4030 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4035; 5.7300 French francs, down from 5.7355;
1.9010 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9025; 1,248.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,249.25, and 1.2547 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2535
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7740 from $1.7680 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.67 to a closing bid of
$431.27.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.41 a troy
ounce, up from $6.22 bid late Thursday.
</TEXT>
