<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv05-06   03-04 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 05-06,0609</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 05</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 5-6</NOTE>
<HEAD>Kodak Note Sale Sets Record; Investors Snap It Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest investment-grade corporate bond
issue ever sold in the United States _ $1.1 billion in 10-year
notes _ went off with picture-perfect ease this past week.
   And experts say they weren't surprised since the seller was
Eastman Kodak Co., which priced the issue generously to compensate
for a recent drop in its credit rating.
   ``A lot of people love to own the name ...,'' explained Anthony
Naylor, a senior vice president in fixed-income securities for
Rodman & Renshaw Inc. ``But they've always had to pay through the
nose before.''
   The record issue _ undertaken partly to help finance Kodak's
recent $5.1 billion acquisition of Sterling Drug Inc. _ was priced
at par to yield 9.125 percent, a percentage point more than
comparable Treasury securities.
   The 10-year notes are noncallable for seven years and rated A-2
by Moody's Investors Service and A-minus by Standard & Poor's Corp.
   Both Wall Street rating services lowered Kodak's senior debt
rating in response to the Sterling deal and legal problems with
Polaroid Corp. over an instant photography patent.
   But analysts say that probably added to the allure of the $1.1
billion issue because the lower the rating a company receives, the
higher the interest it must pay to compensate for the increased
credit risk.
   ``It was very generously priced,'' said Naylor of the notes,
noting that previous issues by the blue-chip company have had a
much narrower yield spread.
   For instance, Kodak's $300 million in four-year notes issued in
October yielded 60 basis points above Treasury securities with
similar maturities, and $125 million in five-year notes from last
spring had only a 25-basis point spread, he said. A basis point is
one-hundredth of a percentage point.
   Naylor said the fact that the issue was so large also
contributed to its success since ``everyone can get in and play,
giving it plenty of liquidity,'' or the ability to sell at any time
without depressing the market price.
   Kodak also came out ahead by the fact that the bonds were sold
at par, or the full face amount. In less successful deals, bonds
are sold at a discount to increase their attractiveness.
   The Rochester, N.Y., company originally had planned to sell only
$750 million in 10-year notes, but increased the size by $350
million because of the strong demand by domestic institutions,
explained Richard W. Swift, a principal at Morgan Stanley & Co.,
underwriters of the issue.
   ``I think it was one of the hottest deals I ever experienced,''
he said, adding that one institution snapped up $75 million of the
notes. ``There's magic to the Kodak name.''
   Some analysts said the popularity of the issue could be read as
a vote of confidence in Kodak's management and its ability to
digest the Sterling deal, which had been criticized as overly
ambitious by some who follow the company.
   Before this past week's issue, the single largest issue by a
U.S. corporation with investment-grade ratings came from Occidental
Petroleum Corp., which sold $1 billion of debentures in March 1986,
Swift said. About two years earlier, Chevron Corp. sold $1 billion
in three-year notes, he said.
   Kodak filed a shelf registration Dec. 30 with the Securities and
Exchange Commission for $1.5 billion worth of bonds. The company
has $400 million left from that registration.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 5-6</NOTE>
</DOC>
