<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TransitionStamp     03-04 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transition Stamp,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`E' Stamp To Mark Rate Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Postage Rate Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When new postage rates go into effect,
Americans will be using special ``E'' stamps on an interim basis to
mail first-class letters.
   The stamps were printed with the letter E on them, instead of
the amount of postage, because the new first-class rate was not
known.
   The Postal Rate Commission on Friday suggested postage rate
increases that included a 25-cent first-class stamp, but those
recommendations still must be accepted by the Postal Service board
of governors. The new rates could go into effect in 10 days to two
weeks after a decision is made, perhaps as early as next week.
   A similar procedure has been used four times in the past,
although the basic design of the undenominated stamp has changed.
   The A, B, C and D stamps all showed the head of an eagle, each
in a different color.
   The E stamp carries a multicolored, space-based image of the
plant with the word Earth printed beneath.
   The stamp also carries the notation ``Domestic'' since it can be
used only for mail within the country. Mail traveling to other
nations requires stamps that show their demoninations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
