<DOCNO> AP880304-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1512EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-IBM-Siemens     03-04 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM-Siemens,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM In Talks With Siemens On Its New PC Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. confirmed
Friday it has discussed a deal involving its new personal computer
line with Siemens AG of West Germany, but said the executive who
made the talks public ``feels his comment on Siemens was premature
and inappropriate.''
   IBM's unusual statement was in reaction to an article Friday in
the Wall Street Journal that quoted William C. Lowe, the vice
president in charge of personal computers, on IBM's plans for its
Personal System-2 line.
   Siemens executives ``were very disturbed by what appeared in the
Journal,'' but the statement Friday will probably help matters,
said Martin Weitzner, a spokesman for Siemens' U.S. operations.
   According to the Journal, Lowe said that if a pact was reached,
Siemens would either license or buy from IBM the crucial parts of
IBM's PS-2 line and incorporate them into its own computers. Lowe
said it was even possible that some companies might buy PS-2
computers whole and sell them under their own labels.
   The Journal said IBM was in similar talks with Ing. C. Olivetti
& Co. of Italy, but IBM said that Lowe had only mentioned Olivetti
as an example of a company that could be considered.
   Such deals would be a major departure for IBM, which
traditionally keeps a tight grip on its own technology. But they
might benefit the company by helping establish the Personal
System-2 as an industry standard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
