<DOCNO> AP880304-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 1514EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BankBid     03-04 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bank Bid,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Plans to Request Court Review of Fed Takeover Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp., the target of a hostile $1.08
billion takeover bid, said Friday it plans to appeal the Federal
Reserve Board's recent decision to allow a proposed merger with
Bank of New York Co.
   Irving filed a notice of appeal in the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the District of the Columbia earlier this week, saying it would ask
the court to reviw the central bank's decision, Irving spokesman
Don Phelps said.
   He said Irving also asked the Fed to delay the effect of its
ruling until the appeals court can review it.
   Irving has rejected takeover efforts by Bank of New York, which
has offered $60 a share in cash and securities for Irving's 18.1
million common shares.
   The takeover fight, launched last fall, has attracted attention
because hostile acquisitions are unusual in banking. Some analysts
speculate that if it succeeds, it may encourage other unsolicited
takeovers in the banking industry.
   The Fed and the New York State Banking Board concluded last
month that a merger of the two New York banks wouldn't hurt
competition in the nation's biggest financial center.
   The central bank said federal law ``does not draw any
distinction between acquisitions that are agreed to between the
parties and those where, as here, there is no agreement.''
   A merger would create the nation's 12th largest banking company
with assets of nearly $12 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
