<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NorthwestAirlines-Findings     03-04 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northwest Airlines-Findings,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Northwest Airlines, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>FAA Criticizes Maintenance Procedures, Record-Keeping At Northwest
Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES PLAINES, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the findings released
Friday by the Federal Aviation Administration from its report on
the results of a monthlong inspection of Minneapolis-based
Northwest Airlines.
   In the area of operations, the inspectors found that:
   _``Northwest Airlines Inc. does not provide enough qualified
dispatchers at each dispatch center to ensure proper operational
control of each flight. Anonymous letters, phone calls and flight
crew complaints that dispatcher workloads were excessive and that
the monitoring of flight progress was untimely were substantiated
by observations of FAA inspectors at both the Tokyo and Minneapolis
dispatch centers.''
   _In several instances, Northwest pilots flew more than 30 hours
during a six-day period. FAA regulations prohibit pilots from
flying more than 30 hours in a seven-day period.
   _``On seven flights, the weight and balance information and
flight release data did not accurately reflect the total number of
infants@crew members@passengers.''
   _``The First Officer on Northwest Airlines Flight 455 (on)
2@12@88 did not have in his personal possession an appropriate
current medical certificate nor a current pilot certificate.''
   _Northwest ``has no provisions in their flight training program
to check an (individual pilot's) proficiency in hand-flying a
non-precision approach.''
   In the area of ``airworthiness,'' the inspectors found that:
   _On Jan. 14, a Northwest DC-10 pilot ``indicated a small
inspection cover on top of No. 3 engine pylon was missing.'' The
jetliner ``flew in an unairworthy condition from 1@14@88 until
2@3@88 when the inspection cover was properly replaced.''
   _The airline flew a DC-10 ``in an unairworthy condition several
flights between 2@1@88 and 2@11@88'' because it ``failed to
neutralize or identify the exact cause'' of a problem with a gauge
that monitored turbine speed in the jet's No. 3 engine.
   _A Boeing 747 ``experienced over 40 repeat discrepancies
relating (to) performance problems on installed engines. During
this period from Sept. 27, 1987, through Jan. 13, one fuel control
and two engines were replaced.''
</TEXT>
