<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close, 1st Ld-Writethru,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Off Sharply; Grains Close Mixed To Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to show action occurred on the Chicago Board of
Trade; pickup 2nd graf: A combination...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged as much as 9 cents
a bushel Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a late sell-off
led by large investment funds. Grain futures closed mixed to lower.
   A combination of bearish factors, including weak export demand
and expectations of a large South American soybean harvest, had
weighed on the soybean market for most of the week.
   Heavy selling of soybean futures by the Chicago-based
professional trading firm C&D Commodities late in Friday's session
sparked fear among other traders that soybean futures prices had
reached a seasonal peak, analysts said.
   ``What you're really getting here is a delayed winter break that
was expected back in January or February, and it's coming now,''
said Richard Loewy, an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Wheat futures were supported by some new export bids and by news
that the Agriculture Department had sold much less surplus wheat
than expected in an auction on Wednesday.
   Corn exports were down for the week, which set a bullish tone
for corn futures, Loewy said.
   At the close, wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.03} a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 2\ cents lower with March at $1.99{ a bushel; oats were }
cent lower to { cent higher with March at $1.86{ a bushel; soybeans
were 6{ cents to 9 cents lower with March at $6.16{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
