<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Morgan-Mexico 1stLd-Writethru f0168 03-04 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Morgan-Mexico, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0168,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Morgan Expects Charge From Mexico Debt Auction</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT to charge against credit losses sted
earnings</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Morgan & Co. said Friday that it expects to
have a charge to allowance-for-credit losses as a result of its
participation in Mexico's debt-for-securities swap aimed at
reducing that country's $105 billion foreign debt.
   The large bank holding company said Mexico accepted about $400
million face value of Morgan's Mexican loans tendered at last
week's auction.
   In exchange for the loans, Morgan said, it will be receiving
about $263 million face value of new Mexican bonds. The face value
of the loans is about 66 percent of the loans that were tendered.
   The Mexican government announced Thursday that it accepted 55
percent of the $6.7 billion in bids that 139 creditor banks
submitted under the unique swap plan.
   The plan calls for Mexico to issue more than $2.5 billion in
new, 20-year bonds to its creditor banks to replace $3.66 billion
in old bank debt, an exchange that will save Mexico over $2.6
billion over 20 years. The bonds are backed by U.S. Treasury
securities.
   In a statement, Morgan said ``as a result of acceptance of the
loans ... a loss determined by the difference between the book
value of the loans tendered and the fair value of the bonds
received will be charged against the allowance for credit losses in
the first quarter.''
   The amount of the credit loss provision will be determined at
the end of the period, the company said.
</TEXT>
