<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0034EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-HBJ     03-04 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-HBJ,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Profit Gain in 4th Qtr as It Spold Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. said
Thursday its fourth-quarter profit climbed more than tenfold from a
year earlier mostly because of the sale of assets.
   Harcourt, which has interests in publishing, insurance and theme
parks, reported a profit of $95.1 million, or $1.36 a share, in the
three months ended Dec. 31, 1987, compared with earnings of $8.9
million, or 23 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the quarter rose 21.4 percent to $327.6 million from
$269.9 million a year earlier.
   The company completed the sale of its business periodicals,
trade shows and school supply distribution companies for $334
million and of two television station for $10.8 million in the
quarter.
   The latest results included a onetime gain on disposal of assets
of $136.9 million and income from discontinued operations of $141.6
million.
   The sales fulfilled the company's asset sale obligation incurred
when it borrowed to finance a recapitalization last May that helped
it avoid a hostile takeover bid from British publisher Robert
Maxwell.
   Interest expense in the latest quarter shot up to $78.5 million
from $6.1 million a year earlier, and the company said it had a
loss from continuing operations of $46.4 million in the latest
quarter in contrast to a profit of $6.2 million a year earlier.
   For the year, Harcourt reported net income of $90.5 million, or
$1.34 a share, up from $70.5 million, or $1.91 a share, a year
earlier.
   The decline in per share earnings reflected an increase in the
average number of shares for the year to 48.1 million from 37
million in 1986.
   Revenue for the year rose to $1.52 billion from $1.11 billion a
year earlier.
</TEXT>
