<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0040EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-BuyingMission     03-04 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Buying Mission,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Buying Mission To Visit U.S. In May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea plans to send a
large-scale buying mission to the United States in May as part of
its effort to ease growing trade frictions with Washington,
government and industry officials said Friday.
   The mission, to be headed by Nam Duck-woo, president of the
Korea Foreign Trade Association, will tour various U.S. cities for
15 days to purchase machinery and other industrial products, the
officials said.
   Details of the mission's itinerary and shopping list have not
yet been fixed, officials said.
   In the past, South Korea sent buying missions to the United
States once or twice a year to help ease trade frictions.
   The United States is pressuring South Korea to open its market
wider to American products to cut its growing trade surplus. The
United States ran a trade deficit of $9.5 billion with South Korea
last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
